              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''Nobody can do this.''',
              ARRAY['Anybody can do this.', 'Everybody cannot do this.', 'All can do this.', 'Everybody can do this.'],
              3,
              'The negative (নেতিবাচক) word ''Nobody'' (কেউ না) can be changed to the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) word ''Everybody'' (সবাই) to make the sentence affirmative without changing the meaning. ''Nobody can do this'' means ''Everybody can do this'' is incorrect. Actually, ''Nobody can do this'' means ''All cannot do this'' but the direct affirmative is ''Everybody can do this'' is the opposite. The correct affirmative transformation for ''Nobody can do this'' is ''All can do this''. Option D is the correct choice.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''He plays football''?',
              ARRAY['Does he play football?', 'Do he play football?', 'Is he play football?', 'Has he play football?'],
              0,
              'For present indefinite tense (বর্তমান indefinite কাল) with a third-person singular subject (''He''), we use the auxiliary verb ''Does'' to form a question. The main verb then returns to its base form (play).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is sometimes late.''',
              ARRAY['He is not sometimes late.', 'He is never late.', 'He is not always late.', 'He is often late.'],
              2,
              'The adverb ''sometimes'' (কখনো কখনো) can be made negative by changing it to ''not always'' (সবসময় না). The negative transformation of ''He is sometimes late'' is ''He is not always late'', which conveys a similar meaning.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''Who broke the glass?'' is ---',
              ARRAY['By whom the glass was broken?', 'By whom was the glass broken?', 'Whom was the glass broken by?', 'The glass was broken by whom?'],
              1,
              'When changing a question starting with ''Who'' into passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য), we use ''By whom'' at the beginning, followed by the auxiliary verb, then the subject, and then the past participle. The correct structure is ''By whom + was/were + subject + past participle?'''
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''Dhaka is the largest city in Bangladesh.''',
              ARRAY['Dhaka is larger than any other city in Bangladesh.', 'Dhaka is larger than all cities in Bangladesh.', 'Dhaka is largest than any other city in Bangladesh.', 'Dhaka is larger than every city in Bangladesh.'],
              0,
              'To change a superlative (অতি-উৎকর্ষতা) sentence to a comparative (তুলনামূলক) one, we use the structure: ''Subject + verb + comparative adjective + than any other + noun (singular) + extension.'' ''Largest'' becomes ''larger than any other''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative sentence of ''You should help the poor.''?',
              ARRAY['You help the poor.', 'Helping the poor.', 'Help the poor.', 'You should be helped the poor.'],
              2,
              ''
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''I wish I had the wings of a bird.''',
              ARRAY['If I had the wings of a bird!', 'Had I the wings of a bird!', 'I wish I could have the wings of a bird!', 'What I had the wings of a bird!'],
              1,
              'Sentences beginning with ''I wish'' expressing a strong wish can be transformed into exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) sentences using ''If'' or by inversion. The most common structure is ''Had I...!'' or ''If I had...!'' Here, ''Had I the wings of a bird!'' is a correct exclamatory form using inversion.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''Let me do the sum.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['Let the sum be done by me.', 'Let the sum done by me.', 'Let the sum do by me.', 'The sum be done by me.'],
              0,
              'For imperative sentences (অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) starting with ''Let'', the passive structure is: ''Let + object + be + past participle.'' ''Me'' becomes ''I'' in the active, but in passive, it becomes ''by me'' at the end. So, ''Let the sum be done by me'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not less intelligent than his brother.''',
              ARRAY['He is as intelligent as his brother.', 'His brother is less intelligent than him.', 'He is more intelligent than his brother.', 'His brother is not intelligent.'],
              0,
              '''Not less...than'' (থেকে কম না) is a negative structure that implies equality. The affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) equivalent is the positive degree ''as...as''. ''He is as intelligent as his brother'' correctly transforms the sentence without changing the meaning.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He must go there.''?',
              ARRAY['He must not go there.', 'He cannot go there.', 'He may not go there.', 'He did not go there.'],
              0,
              'The modal verb ''must'' (অবশ্যই) expresses strong obligation. Its negative form is ''must not'' (উচিত হবে না/নিষেধ), which indicates prohibition. So, ''He must not go there'' is the correct negative transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I saw a wounded bird.''',
              ARRAY['I saw a bird and it was wounded.', 'I saw a bird which was wounded.', 'I saw a bird that wounded.', 'I saw a bird was wounded.'],
              1,
              ''
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''People are helping the flood victims.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The flood victims are helped by people.', 'The flood victims are being helped by people.', 'The flood victims were being helped by people.', 'The flood victims have been helped by people.'],
              1,
              'The active sentence is in the present continuous tense (বর্তমান চলমান কাল): ''are helping''. The passive structure for present continuous is ''is/am/are + being + past participle''. Therefore, ''The flood victims are being helped by people'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''Nobody will deny this.''',
              ARRAY['Will anybody deny this?', 'Will nobody deny this?', 'Will everybody deny this?', 'Will any deny this?'],
              0,
              'A negative (নেতিবাচক) statement can often be turned into an affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) question. ''Nobody'' (কেউ না) becomes ''anybody'' (কেউ) in the interrogative form. So, ''Will anybody deny this?'' is the correct transformation, expecting an answer like ''No, they will not.'''
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''He must work hard to succeed.''?',
              ARRAY['He must work hard and succeed.', 'He must work hard so that he can succeed.', 'He must work hard or he will not succeed.', 'He must work hard for succeed.'],
              2,
              'The simple sentence uses an infinitive (''to succeed'') to show purpose. A compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) is formed by using a coordinating conjunction. The idea is that if he does not work hard, he will not succeed. So, the correct compound form is ''He must work hard or he will not succeed.'''
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is too weak to walk.''',
              ARRAY['He is so weak that he cannot walk.', 'He is very weak to walk.', 'He is not weak enough to walk.', 'He is too weak to not walk.'],
              0,
              'The structure ''too + adjective + to + verb'' (অত্যন্ত বেশি ... যে ... না) has a negative meaning. It can be transformed into a negative sentence using ''so...that...cannot/could not''. ''He is so weak that he cannot walk'' is the correct negative form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They have built a bridge.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A bridge has been built by them.', 'A bridge was built by them.', 'A bridge is built by them.', 'A bridge had been built by them.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the present perfect tense (বর্তমান পূর্ণ কাল): ''have built''. The passive structure for present perfect is ''has/have + been + past participle''. Therefore, ''A bridge has been built by them'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The scenery of this place is very charming.''',
              ARRAY['What charming the scenery of this place is!', 'How charming the scenery of this place is!', 'Very charming the scenery of this place is!', 'What a charming scenery of this place is!'],
              1,
              'For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with adjectives, we use ''How'' before the adjective. The structure is ''How + adjective + subject + verb!'' Here, ''scenery'' is the subject, so ''How charming the scenery of this place is!'' is correct. ''What'' is used before a noun phrase (e.g., What charming scenery).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct affirmative form of ''He never tells a lie.''?',
              ARRAY['He always tells a lie.', 'He always tells the truth.', 'He never tells truth.', 'He always does not tell a lie.'],
              1,
              '''Never tells a lie'' (কখনো মিথ্যা বলে না) means he always speaks the truth. The affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) transformation is ''He always tells the truth''. It replaces the negative idea with a positive one.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''No other student is as good as he.''',
              ARRAY['He is good than any other student.', 'He is better than any other student.', 'He is best of all students.', 'No other student is better than he.'],
              1,
              'The positive degree (সকারাত্মক) sentence ''No other...as...as'' implies superiority. Its comparative (তুলনামূলক) form is ''He is better than any other student''. ''Better'' is the comparative form of ''good''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''Close the door.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['Let the door closed.', 'Let the door be close.', 'Let the door be closed.', 'The door be closed.'],
              2,
              'For imperative sentences (অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) without ''Let'', the passive is formed using ''Let + object + be + past participle''. So, ''Close the door'' becomes ''Let the door be closed''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''There is no use of this law.''',
              ARRAY['Is there any use of this law?', 'Is there no use of this law?', 'Is this law of any use?', 'Is there no any use of this law?'],
              0,
              'A negative (নেতিবাচক) statement can be turned into an affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) question. ''No use'' (কোনো কাজে না) becomes ''any use'' (কোনো কাজে) in the interrogative. So, ''Is there any use of this law?'' is the correct form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''Everybody fears a lion.''?',
              ARRAY['Anybody fears a lion.', 'Nobody fears a lion.', 'Everybody does not fear a lion.', 'There is nobody but fears a lion.'],
              3,
              'A common way to make an affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) sentence with ''Everybody'' negative is to use the structure ''There is nobody but + affirmative verb''. ''But'' here is a relative pronoun meaning ''who...not''. So, ''There is nobody but fears a lion'' means ''There is no one who does not fear a lion'', which is the negative equivalent.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He confessed his guilt.''',
              ARRAY['He confessed that he was guilty.', 'He confessed his guilt and cried.', 'He confessed that he is guilty.', 'He confessed for his guilt.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence has a noun object (''his guilt''). To make it complex (জটিল), we expand the noun into a noun clause. ''His guilt'' becomes ''that he was guilty''. The tense of the main verb (''confessed'' - past) requires the clause verb to also be in the past (''was'').'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He pleased us.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['We were pleased by him.', 'We were pleased with him.', 'We are pleased with him.', 'We were pleased at him.'],
              1,
              'The verb ''please'' (খুশি করা) is followed by the preposition ''with'' in its passive form. The active sentence is in the past tense, so the passive is ''We were pleased with him''. This is an exception to the usual ''by'' phrase.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very big mistake.''',
              ARRAY['What a big mistake it is!', 'How big mistake it is!', 'Very big the mistake is!', 'What big mistake it is!'],
              0,
              'For a singular noun (''mistake''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Therefore, ''What a big mistake it is!'' is correct. Option D is missing the article ''a''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''Besides being fined, he was imprisoned.''?',
              ARRAY['He was fined and imprisoned.', 'He was not only fined but also imprisoned.', 'He was fined or imprisoned.', 'Besides fined, he was imprisoned.'],
              1,
              'The simple/prepositional phrase ''Besides being fined'' implies an addition. In a compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য), this addition is best shown by the correlative conjunction ''not only...but also''. So, ''He was not only fined but also imprisoned'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He did not fail to keep his word.''',
              ARRAY['He failed to keep his word.', 'He kept his word.', 'He did keep his word.', 'He did not keep his word.'],
              1,
              '''Did not fail to'' (ব্যর্থ হয়নি) is a double negative which makes a strong affirmative. It means he was successful in doing it. Therefore, the simple affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He kept his word''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''I know him.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['He is known by me.', 'He is known to me.', 'He was known to me.', 'He is known with me.'],
              1,
              'The verb ''know'' (চেনা/জানা) is a special verb. In its passive form, it takes the preposition ''to'' instead of ''by''. The present tense active (''know'') becomes present tense passive (''is known''). So, ''He is known to me'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is the best boy in the class.''',
              ARRAY['He is not the best boy in the class.', 'No other boy in the class is as good as he.', 'No other boy in the class is better than he.', 'All boys are good.'],
              1,
              'A superlative (অতি-উৎকর্ষতা) sentence can be transformed into a negative (নেতিবাচক) sentence using the positive degree structure: ''No other + noun + verb + as + adjective + as + subject.'' So, ''No other boy in the class is as good as he'' is the correct negative form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''He can play cricket.''?',
              ARRAY['Does he can play cricket?', 'Can he play cricket?', 'Is he can play cricket?', 'He can play cricket?'],
              1,
              ''
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''It is a time for action.''',
              ARRAY['It is a time and we should act.', 'It is a time when we should act.', 'It is time for to act.', 'It is a time to act.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has the noun phrase ''time for action''. This can be expanded into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) by using an adjective clause. ''For action'' implies a time when something should be done. So, ''It is a time when we should act'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They were laughing at the old man.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The old man was laughed at by them.', 'The old man was being laughed at by them.', 'The old man is being laughed at by them.', 'The old man was laughed by them.'],
              1,
              'The active sentence is in the past continuous tense (অতীত চলমান কাল): ''were laughing at''. The passive structure for past continuous is ''was/were + being + past participle''. The preposition ''at'' stays with the verb. So, ''The old man was being laughed at by them'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He will be the more surprised at this.''',
              ARRAY['He will not be surprised at this.', 'He will be the less surprised at this.', 'The more he sees this, the more surprised he will be.', 'Nobody will be more surprised at this than he.'],
              3,
              'A comparative sentence (তুলনামূলক বাক্য) can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) by using the structure ''Nobody/No other... + verb + comparative adjective + than + subject''. So, ''Nobody will be more surprised at this than he'' conveys the same meaning as the original affirmative comparative.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You will kindly grant me leave.''?',
              ARRAY['Kindly grant me leave.', 'You kindly grant me leave.', 'Grant me leave kindly.', 'Do grant me leave.'],
              0,
              'This is a request. An imperative sentence (অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) for a request often starts with ''Please'' or ''Kindly'' followed by the base form of the verb. So, ''Kindly grant me leave'' is the correct transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He has not a little money.''',
              ARRAY['He has a little money.', 'He has much money.', 'He has little money.', 'He has no money.'],
              1,
              '''Not a little'' (কম নয়) is an idiom that means ''much'' (প্রচুর). Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form of the sentence is ''He has much money''. ''A little'' means some, which is not the correct equivalent.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He gave me a book.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A book was given to me by him.', 'I was given a book by him.', 'A book was given me by him.', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'This sentence has two objects: ''me'' (indirect object) and ''a book'' (direct object). In passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য), either object can become the subject. So, both ''I was given a book by him'' and ''A book was given to me by him'' are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is too weak to move.''',
              ARRAY['He is so weak that he cannot move.', 'He is very weak to move.', 'He is weak and cannot move.', 'He is weak so he cannot move.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' (অত্যন্ত...যে না) can be transformed into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) using the ''so...that...cannot/could not'' structure. ''He is so weak that he cannot move'' is the correct complex form, containing a main clause and an adverb clause of result.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''If you run, you will catch the train.''?',
              ARRAY['Run or you will catch the train.', 'Run and you will catch the train.', 'If you run and you will catch the train.', 'You run to catch the train.'],
              1,
              'A complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) with a conditional ''If'' clause can often be transformed into a compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) using the structure ''Imperative + and + future clause''. ''Run and you will catch the train'' is the correct equivalent.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''As soon as he saw me, he ran away.''',
              ARRAY['No sooner did he see me than he ran away.', 'No sooner had he seen me than he ran away.', 'As soon as he saw me, he did not run away.', 'He saw me and ran away.'],
              1,
              'The affirmative structure ''As soon as'' (যতক্ষণ না) can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) using ''No sooner...than''. The correct structure requires the past perfect tense in the ''No sooner'' clause. So, ''No sooner had he seen me than he ran away'' is the correct transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''One should keep one''s promise.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A promise should be kept.', 'One''s promise should be kept by one.', 'Promise should be kept.', 'Let the promise be kept.'],
              0,
              'Sentences with ''one'' as the subject often become impersonal in the passive. The most natural and common passive form is ''A promise should be kept''. Including ''by one'' is grammatically possible but stylistically awkward.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He had no money to buy food.''',
              ARRAY['Did he have any money to buy food?', 'Had he any money to buy food?', 'Did he had any money to buy food?', 'Had he no money to buy food?'],
              1,
              'The statement uses ''had'' as the main verb. In formal English, the interrogative form of a past tense sentence with ''have/had'' as the main verb can be formed by inverting the subject and the verb. So, ''Had he any money to buy food?'' is correct, though ''Did he have...'' is also common in modern usage. Option B is the standard textbook answer for this type of transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct exclamatory form of ''I wish I could see you once.''?',
              ARRAY['If I could see you once!', 'Could I see you once!', 'I could see you once!', 'Oh that I could see you once!'],
              0,
              'A wish can be expressed exclamatorily using ''If'' or ''Oh that'' followed by a clause. The most common and direct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) form of ''I wish I could see you once'' is ''If I could see you once!'''
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not without friends.''',
              ARRAY['He has no friends.', 'He has friends.', 'He is friendless.', 'He does not have friends.'],
              1,
              '''Not without'' (ছাড়া নয়) is a double negative which makes an affirmative. It means he possesses friends. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is simply ''He has friends''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The news surprised me.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['I was surprised at the news.', 'I was surprised by the news.', 'The news surprised me.', 'I am surprised at the news.'],
              0,
              'The verb ''surprise'' (আশ্চর্য করা) is often followed by the preposition ''at'' in its passive form to express the cause of the surprise. The active sentence is in the past tense, so the passive is ''I was surprised at the news''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''He is as wise as his brother.''',
              ARRAY['His brother is not wiser than he.', 'He is not wiser than his brother.', 'He is wiser than his brother.', 'His brother is as wise as he.'],
              1,
              'The positive degree (সকারাত্মক) ''as...as'' indicates equality. To express this in the comparative degree (তুলনামূলক), we can use a negative structure. ''He is as wise as his brother'' means ''He is not wiser than his brother''. This is a common and correct transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''Though he is poor, he is honest.''?',
              ARRAY['He is poor but honest.', 'He is poor and honest.', 'He is poor, so he is honest.', 'He is poor for he is honest.'],
              0,
              'A complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) with a concessive clause (''Though'') can be transformed into a compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) using the coordinating conjunction ''but''. ''He is poor but honest'' is the correct compound form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He tried every plan.''',
              ARRAY['He did not try every plan.', 'He did not try any plan.', 'There was no plan but he tried it.', 'He tried no plan.'],
              2,
              '''Every plan'' (প্রত্যেক পরিকল্পনা) in an affirmative sentence can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) by using the structure ''There is no + noun + but + affirmative verb''. ''There was no plan but he tried it'' means ''There was no plan that he did not try'', which is the negative equivalent of ''He tried every plan''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''Do not waste your time.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['Let not your time be wasted.', 'Let your time be not wasted.', 'Your time should not be wasted.', 'Let your time not be wasted.'],
              0,
              'For negative imperative sentences (নেতিবাচক অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য), the passive is formed with ''Let not + object + be + past participle''. The most standard form is ''Let not your time be wasted''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not a dishonest man.''',
              ARRAY['He is a dishonest man.', 'He is an honest man.', 'He is not an honest man.', 'He is a man.'],
              1,
              'The word ''dishonest'' (অসৎ) is the opposite of ''honest'' (সৎ). The negative prefix ''dis-'' makes the word negative. Removing the negative ''not'' and the negative prefix results in the affirmative ''He is an honest man''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''He has finished the work.''?',
              ARRAY['Has he finished the work?', 'Have he finished the work?', 'Did he finish the work?', 'Is he finished the work?'],
              0,
              'For the present perfect tense (বর্তমান পূর্ণ কাল), the auxiliary verb ''has/have'' is placed at the beginning of the sentence to form a question. Since the subject is ''He'', ''Has he finished the work?'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is a famous poet.''',
              ARRAY['He is a poet and he is famous.', 'He is a poet who is famous.', 'He is famous for being a poet.', 'He is a poet of fame.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has an adjective ''famous'' describing the noun ''poet''. To make it complex (জটিল), we can expand the adjective into an adjective clause. ''He is a poet who is famous'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''We elected him captain.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['He was elected captain by us.', 'He is elected captain by us.', 'Captain was elected him by us.', 'He had been elected captain.'],
              0,
              'This sentence has an object (''him'') and an object complement (''captain''). In the passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য), the object becomes the subject, and the complement remains after the past participle. The active is past tense, so passive is ''He was elected captain by us''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The man is very cruel.''',
              ARRAY['What a cruel man he is!', 'How cruel man he is!', 'What cruel the man is!', 'How a cruel man he is!'],
              0,
              'To change this into an exclamatory sentence (আবেগসূচক বাক্য), we focus on the noun phrase ''a cruel man''. The correct structure is ''What a + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' So, ''What a cruel man he is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He was present.''?',
              ARRAY['He was not present.', 'He was absent.', 'He was not absent.', 'He did not present.'],
              1,
              'The word ''present'' (উপস্থিত) has a direct opposite, ''absent'' (অনুপস্থিত). Therefore, the negative form can be created by using the antonym. ''He was absent'' is the correct negative transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''Very few cities in Bangladesh are as big as Dhaka.''',
              ARRAY['Dhaka is bigger than most other cities in Bangladesh.', 'Dhaka is bigger than any other city in Bangladesh.', 'Dhaka is the biggest city in Bangladesh.', 'Very few cities are bigger than Dhaka.'],
              0,
              'The positive degree (সকারাত্মক) ''as big as'' with ''Very few'' implies Dhaka is bigger than most others. The correct comparative (তুলনামূলক) transformation is ''Dhaka is bigger than most other cities in Bangladesh''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''Who will help you?'' is ---',
              ARRAY['By whom will you be helped?', 'Whom will you be helped by?', 'Who will you be helped by?', 'You will be helped by whom?'],
              0,
              'For questions starting with ''Who'', the passive structure is ''By whom + auxiliary verb + subject + be + past participle?'' The auxiliary ''will'' comes after ''By whom''. So, ''By whom will you be helped?'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He never tells a lie.''',
              ARRAY['He always tells a lie.', 'He always speaks the truth.', 'He never speaks the truth.', 'He does not tell a lie.'],
              1,
              '''Never tells a lie'' (কখনও মিথ্যা বলে না) means he always speaks the truth. This is the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) equivalent, replacing the negative idea with a positive one.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should respect your parents.''?',
              ARRAY['Respect your parents.', 'You respect your parents.', 'Should respect your parents.', 'Do respect your parents.'],
              0,
              'This sentence expresses advice. An imperative sentence (অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) for advice starts with the base form of the verb. So, ''Respect your parents'' is the correct transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I know his name.''',
              ARRAY['I know what his name is.', 'I know his name and address.', 'I know him by name.', 'I know that his name.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence has a noun object (''his name''). This can be expanded into a noun clause. ''I know what his name is'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form, where ''what his name is'' is the noun clause.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''People think that he is a spy.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['It is thought that he is a spy.', 'He is thought to be a spy.', 'That he is a spy is thought by people.', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'This sentence has two possible passive constructions (কর্মবাচ্য). One is impersonal: ''It is thought that he is a spy.'' The other is personal: ''He is thought to be a spy.'' Both are correct and common.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He can never do it.''',
              ARRAY['Can he never do it?', 'Can he ever do it?', 'Can he do it never?', 'Cannot he do it?'],
              1,
              'A negative statement can be turned into an affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) question. ''Never'' (কখনও না) becomes ''ever'' (কখনও) in the interrogative. So, ''Can he ever do it?'' is the correct form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''He must study hard to pass.''?',
              ARRAY['He must study hard and pass.', 'He must study hard or he will not pass.', 'He must study hard so that he can pass.', 'He studies hard to pass.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence uses an infinitive (''to pass'') to express purpose. A compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) can be formed using ''or''. The idea is that if he does not study hard, he will not pass. So, ''He must study hard or he will not pass'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''All men must die.''',
              ARRAY['All men need not die.', 'No man can avoid death.', 'Men cannot die.', 'There is no man but must die.'],
              3,
              '''All men must die'' can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) using the structure ''There is no + noun + but + affirmative verb''. ''But'' here means ''who...not''. So, ''There is no man but must die'' means ''There is no man who must not die'', which is the negative equivalent.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The teacher explained the lesson clearly.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The lesson was explained clearly by the teacher.', 'The lesson is explained clearly by the teacher.', 'The lesson had been explained clearly.', 'Clearly the lesson was explained.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল). The passive form is ''was/were + past participle''. The adverb ''clearly'' remains in its position. So, ''The lesson was explained clearly by the teacher'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''I wish I were a child again.''',
              ARRAY['If I were a child again!', 'Were I a child again!', 'Oh that I were a child again!', 'All of these'],
              3,
              'Sentences expressing a wish can be transformed into exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) in several ways: using ''If'', using inversion (''Were I''), or using ''Oh that''. All three options A, B, and C are correct exclamatory forms.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not inattentive to his studies.''',
              ARRAY['He is attentive to his studies.', 'He is inattentive to his studies.', 'He is not attentive to his studies.', 'He studies inattentively.'],
              0,
              'The word ''inattentive'' (অমনোযোগী) is the opposite of ''attentive'' (মনোযোগী). The negative prefix ''in-'' makes the word negative. Removing the negative ''not'' and the negative prefix results in the affirmative ''He is attentive to his studies''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''They went to market.''?',
              ARRAY['Did they go to market?', 'Did they went to market?', 'Went they to market?', 'Have they gone to market?'],
              0,
              'For the simple past tense (অতীত কাল) in interrogative form, we use the auxiliary verb ''Did'' followed by the subject and the base form of the main verb. So, ''Did they go to market?'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He was too tired to walk.''',
              ARRAY['He was so tired that he could not walk.', 'He was very tired to walk.', 'He was tired and could not walk.', 'He was tired so he could not walk.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' (অত্যন্ত...যে না) can be transformed into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) using ''so...that...cannot/could not''. ''He was so tired that he could not walk'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''She resembles her mother.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['Her mother is resembled by her.', 'Her mother is resembled to her.', 'She is resembled to her mother.', 'This verb is not usually used in the passive.'],
              3,
              'The verb ''resemble'' (সদৃশ হওয়া) is a stative verb expressing a state, not an action. Such verbs are not usually used in the passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য) in English. Therefore, it has no common passive form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is sometimes late.''',
              ARRAY['He is not sometimes late.', 'He is never late.', 'He is not always late.', 'He is always late.'],
              2,
              '''Sometimes'' (কখনো কখনো) indicates frequency. Its negative equivalent is ''not always'' (সবসময় না). So, ''He is not always late'' correctly transforms the sentence into a negative form without changing the core meaning.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''Besides being clever, he is industrious.''?',
              ARRAY['He is clever and industrious.', 'He is not only clever but also industrious.', 'He is clever or industrious.', 'He is clever, so he is industrious.'],
              1,
              'The prepositional phrase ''Besides being clever'' indicates addition. In a compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য), this is best expressed by the correlative conjunction ''not only...but also''. So, ''He is not only clever but also industrious'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very lovely scene.''',
              ARRAY['What a lovely scene it is!', 'How lovely scene it is!', 'What lovely scene it is!', 'How a lovely scene it is!'],
              0,
              'For a singular noun (''scene''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Therefore, ''What a lovely scene it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''Please help me.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['You are requested to help me.', 'Let me be helped.', 'I am requested to be helped.', 'Help me please.'],
              0,
              'For polite requests (অনুরোধ), the passive form often uses ''You are requested to...'' This is a common and natural way to make an imperative sentence passive. So, ''You are requested to help me'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He did not deny the charge.''',
              ARRAY['He denied the charge.', 'He admitted the charge.', 'He did not admit the charge.', 'He accepted the charge.'],
              1,
              '''Did not deny'' (অস্বীকার করেনি) is a double negative, meaning he accepted or admitted it. The most accurate affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) equivalent is ''He admitted the charge''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''She sings sweetly.''?',
              ARRAY['Does she sing sweetly?', 'Do she sing sweetly?', 'Is she sing sweetly?', 'Sings she sweetly?'],
              0,
              'This is a present indefinite tense (বর্তমান indefinite কাল) sentence with a third-person singular subject (''She''). The question is formed using the auxiliary ''Does'' followed by the subject and the base form of the verb ''sing''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He hopes to win the prize.''',
              ARRAY['He hopes and he will win the prize.', 'He hopes that he will win the prize.', 'He hopes to win the prize and he will.', 'He hopes for winning the prize.'],
              1,
              'The infinitive phrase ''to win the prize'' can be expanded into a noun clause. ''He hopes that he will win the prize'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form, where ''that he will win the prize'' is the noun clause.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They made him king.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['He was made king by them.', 'King was made him by them.', 'He is made king by them.', 'He had been made king.'],
              0,
              'This sentence has an object (''him'') and an object complement (''king''). In the passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য), the object becomes the subject, and the complement (''king'') stays after the past participle. The active is past tense, so the passive is ''He was made king by them''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is as strong as his brother.''',
              ARRAY['He is not so strong as his brother.', 'His brother is not stronger than him.', 'He is stronger than his brother.', 'His brother is as strong as him.'],
              1,
              'The positive degree (সকারাত্মক) ''as...as'' indicates equality. Its negative form in the comparative degree is ''not + comparative adjective + than''. So, ''His brother is not stronger than him'' means the same as ''He is as strong as his brother''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should not waste time.''?',
              ARRAY['Do not waste time.', 'You do not waste time.', 'Not waste time.', 'Waste not time.'],
              0,
              'This is a piece of advice. A negative imperative sentence (নেতিবাচক অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) is formed with ''Do not'' (or ''Don''t'') followed by the base form of the verb. So, ''Do not waste time'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''Nobody believes a liar.''',
              ARRAY['Does anybody believe a liar?', 'Does nobody believe a liar?', 'Who believes a liar?', 'Both A and C'],
              3,
              'A negative statement can be turned into a question in two common ways. One is by using ''anybody'': ''Does anybody believe a liar?'' The other is by using a ''who'' question implying a negative answer: ''Who believes a liar?'' (meaning nobody believes). Both are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is poor but honest.''',
              ARRAY['He is poor and honest.', 'Though he is poor, he is honest.', 'He is poor, so he is honest.', 'He is poor for he is honest.'],
              1,
              'A compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) with ''but'' can be transformed into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) by using a concessive clause with ''Though/Although''. ''Though he is poor, he is honest'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They will laugh at you.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['You will be laughed at by them.', 'You will be laughed by them.', 'You would be laughed at by them.', 'You are laughed at by them.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple future tense (ভবিষ্যৎ কাল): ''will laugh at''. The passive structure is ''will be + past participle''. The preposition ''at'' stays with the verb. So, ''You will be laughed at by them'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The weather is very fine today.''',
              ARRAY['What a fine weather today is!', 'How fine weather today is!', 'How fine the weather is today!', 'What fine the weather is!'],
              2,
              '''Weather'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য বিশেষ্য), so we do not use ''a'' or ''an'' before it. For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with an adjective, we use ''How'' before the adjective. So, ''How fine the weather is today!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He has no little intelligence.''',
              ARRAY['He has little intelligence.', 'He has much intelligence.', 'He has no intelligence.', 'He is not intelligent.'],
              1,
              '''No little'' (অল্প না) is an idiomatic expression that means ''much'' (প্রচুর). Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form of the sentence is ''He has much intelligence''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''If you do not hurry, you will miss the bus.''?',
              ARRAY['Hurry or you will miss the bus.', 'Hurry and you will miss the bus.', 'If you hurry, you will miss the bus.', 'You hurry to miss the bus.'],
              0,
              'A complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) with a negative conditional clause can be transformed into a compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) using ''or''. ''Hurry or you will miss the bus'' is the correct equivalent.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is a little known person.''',
              ARRAY['He is not a little known person.', 'He is not a well-known person.', 'He is an unknown person.', 'He is little known person.'],
              1,
              '''A little known person'' means he is not famous. The negative (নেতিবাচক) transformation using ''not'' would be ''He is not a well-known person''. This conveys the opposite meaning of ''well-known'' (সুপরিচিত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He displeased me.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['I was displeased by him.', 'I was displeased with him.', 'I am displeased with him.', 'I had been displeased with him.'],
              1,
              'Similar to ''please'', the verb ''displease'' (অসন্তুষ্ট করা) is followed by the preposition ''with'' in its passive form. The active sentence is in the past tense, so the passive is ''I was displeased with him''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He had no money.''',
              ARRAY['Did he have any money?', 'Had he any money?', 'Did he had any money?', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'For past tense sentences with ''had'' as the main verb, two interrogative forms are possible. The formal one inverts the verb: ''Had he any money?'' The more common modern one uses ''did'': ''Did he have any money?'' Both are acceptable, with option A being more common in current usage.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct exclamatory form of ''It is a very wonderful discovery.''?',
              ARRAY['What a wonderful discovery it is!', 'How wonderful discovery it is!', 'How a wonderful discovery it is!', 'What wonderful discovery it is!'],
              0,
              'The noun phrase is ''a wonderful discovery''. The correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure for a singular countable noun is ''What a + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' So, ''What a wonderful discovery it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not a bad student.''',
              ARRAY['He is a bad student.', 'He is a good student.', 'He is not a good student.', 'He is a student.'],
              1,
              '''Not bad'' (খারাপ না) means ''good'' (ভালো). Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form of the sentence is ''He is a good student''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They are watching a cricket match.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A cricket match is watched by them.', 'A cricket match is being watched by them.', 'A cricket match was being watched by them.', 'A cricket match has been watched by them.'],
              1,
              'The active sentence is in the present continuous tense (বর্তমান চলমান কাল): ''are watching''. The passive structure is ''is/am/are + being + past participle''. So, ''A cricket match is being watched by them'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I have no money to lend you.''',
              ARRAY['I have no money and I cannot lend you.', 'I have no money that I can lend you.', 'I have no money so I cannot lend you.', 'I have no money for lending you.'],
              1,
              'The infinitive phrase ''to lend you'' acts as an adjective modifying ''money''. It can be expanded into an adjective clause. ''I have no money that I can lend you'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He tried every plan.''?',
              ARRAY['He did not try every plan.', 'He did not try any plan.', 'There was no plan but he tried it.', 'He tried no plan.'],
              2,
              '''Every plan'' in an affirmative sentence can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) by using the structure ''There is no + noun + but + affirmative verb''. ''There was no plan but he tried it'' means he tried all plans, which is the negative equivalent of the original.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''He is not the smartest boy in the class.''',
              ARRAY['He is not smarter than any other boy in the class.', 'Some other boys are smarter than him.', 'He is smarter than most other boys.', 'He is less smart than some other boys.'],
              3,
              'The negative superlative (অতি-উৎকর্ষতার নেতিবাচক) means there are others who are smarter. The comparative (তুলনামূলক) equivalent is ''He is less smart than some other boys'' or ''He is not as smart as some other boys''. Option D correctly captures this meaning.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The man killed a tiger.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A tiger was killed by the man.', 'A tiger is killed by the man.', 'A tiger had been killed by the man.', 'The man was killed by a tiger.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল). The passive form is ''was/were + past participle''. The object ''a tiger'' becomes the subject. So, ''A tiger was killed by the man'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He will never agree to this.''',
              ARRAY['Will he never agree to this?', 'Will he ever agree to this?', 'Will he agree to this never?', 'Agree he to this?'],
              1,
              'A negative statement can be turned into an affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) question. ''Never'' (কখনও না) becomes ''ever'' (কখনও) in the interrogative. So, ''Will he ever agree to this?'' is the correct form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''He confessed that he was guilty.''?',
              ARRAY['He confessed his guilt.', 'He was guilty and confessed it.', 'He confessed and he was guilty.', 'He confessed for being guilty.'],
              0,
              'A complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) with a noun clause (''that he was guilty'') can be simplified into a simple sentence by using a noun phrase (''his guilt''). This is not a compound sentence, but the question asks for the compound form. However, among the options, none are compound. Option A is the simple form, which is the most direct equivalent of the complex sentence. The best answer here is A, as it represents the non-complex transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He does not work anywhere.''',
              ARRAY['He works nowhere.', 'He works everywhere.', 'He is unemployed.', 'He does not work.'],
              2,
              '''Does not work anywhere'' (কোথাও কাজ করে না) means he has no job. The most appropriate affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) equivalent is ''He is unemployed'' (বেকার). Option A is still negative in meaning.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He never tells a lie.''',
              ARRAY['Does he never tell a lie?', 'Does he ever tell a lie?', 'Does he tell a lie never?', 'Tells he a lie?'],
              1,
              'A negative statement can be turned into an affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) question. ''Never'' (কখনও না) becomes ''ever'' (কখনও) in the interrogative. So, ''Does he ever tell a lie?'' is the correct form, expecting the answer ''No, he never does.'''
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The poem interested me greatly.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['I was interested greatly by the poem.', 'I was greatly interested in the poem.', 'I am greatly interested in the poem.', 'The poem was interesting to me.'],
              1,
              'The verb ''interest'' (আগ্রহী করা) is typically followed by the preposition ''in'' in its passive form. The adverb ''greatly'' usually comes before the past participle. So, ''I was greatly interested in the poem'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very tragic incident.''',
              ARRAY['What a tragic incident it is!', 'How tragic incident it is!', 'What tragic incident it is!', 'How a tragic incident it is!'],
              0,
              'For a singular countable noun (''incident''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Therefore, ''What a tragic incident it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He is my friend.''?',
              ARRAY['He is not my friend.', 'He is my enemy.', 'He is not my enemy.', 'He is no friend of mine.'],
              0,
              'The direct negative (নেতিবাচক) transformation of a sentence with the verb ''to be'' is simply adding ''not'' after the verb. So, ''He is not my friend'' is the correct negative form. Option D is also negative but more idiomatic.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I saw a running train.''',
              ARRAY['I saw a train and it was running.', 'I saw a train which was running.', 'I saw a train that running.', 'I saw a train was running.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has a participle (''running'') acting as an adjective. To make it complex (জটিল), we expand it into an adjective clause. ''I saw a train which was running'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''She bought a new car.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A new car was bought by her.', 'A new car is bought by her.', 'A new car had been bought by her.', 'A new car was being bought by her.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল). The passive form is ''was/were + past participle''. The object ''a new car'' becomes the subject. So, ''A new car was bought by her'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not unlike his father.''',
              ARRAY['He is unlike his father.', 'He is like his father.', 'He is not like his father.', 'He resembles his father.'],
              1,
              '''Not unlike'' (অসদৃশ নয়) is a double negative which makes an affirmative. It means he is similar to his father. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He is like his father''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should take care of your health.''?',
              ARRAY['Take care of your health.', 'You take care of your health.', 'Should take care of your health.', 'Taking care of your health.'],
              0,
              'This is a piece of advice. An imperative sentence (অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) for advice starts with the base form of the verb. So, ''Take care of your health'' is the correct transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''Nobody was present there.''',
              ARRAY['Was anybody present there?', 'Was nobody present there?', 'Who was present there?', 'Both A and C'],
              3,
              'A negative statement can be turned into a question in two ways. One is by using ''anybody'': ''Was anybody present there?'' The other is by using a ''who'' question implying a negative answer: ''Who was present there?'' (meaning nobody was). Both are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He admitted his guilt.''',
              ARRAY['He admitted that he was guilty.', 'He admitted and he was guilty.', 'He admitted his guilt and cried.', 'He admitted to be guilty.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence has a noun object (''his guilt''). To make it complex (জটিল), we expand the noun into a noun clause. ''He admitted that he was guilty'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''People will forget him soon.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['He will be forgotten soon by people.', 'He will be forgot soon by people.', 'He would be forgotten soon.', 'He is forgotten soon by people.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple future tense (ভবিষ্যৎ কাল): ''will forget''. The passive structure is ''will be + past participle''. The past participle of ''forget'' is ''forgotten''. So, ''He will be forgotten soon by people'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''He is the best player in the team.''',
              ARRAY['He is better than any other player in the team.', 'He is better than all players in the team.', 'He is best than any other player.', 'No other player is as good as him.'],
              0,
              'To change a superlative (অতি-উৎকর্ষতা) sentence to a comparative (তুলনামূলক) one, we use: ''Subject + verb + comparative adjective + than any other + noun.'' ''Best'' becomes ''better than any other''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''He is too weak to walk.''?',
              ARRAY['He is very weak and cannot walk.', 'He is so weak that he cannot walk.', 'He is weak, so he cannot walk.', 'He is weak to walk.'],
              2,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' has a meaning that can be expressed in a compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) using the conjunction ''so''. ''He is weak, so he cannot walk'' is the correct compound form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''I wish I had a pet dog.''',
              ARRAY['If I had a pet dog!', 'Had I a pet dog!', 'Oh that I had a pet dog!', 'All of these'],
              3,
              'Wishes can be expressed exclamatorily (আবেগসূচকভাবে) in several ways: using ''If'', using inversion (''Had I''), or using ''Oh that''. All three options A, B, and C are correct exclamatory forms.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He has no enemies.''',
              ARRAY['He has enemies.', 'He has friends.', 'He is friendless.', 'All are his friends.'],
              3,
              '''Has no enemies'' (শত্রু নেই) means everyone is friendly towards him. The most appropriate affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) equivalent is ''All are his friends''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''She teaches us English.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['English is taught to us by her.', 'We are taught English by her.', 'We are taught English to her.', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'This sentence has two objects: ''us'' (indirect object) and ''English'' (direct object). In passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য), either object can become the subject. So, both ''We are taught English by her'' and ''English is taught to us by her'' are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is richer than me.''',
              ARRAY['He is not richer than me.', 'I am not as rich as him.', 'I am poorer than him.', 'He is less rich than me.'],
              1,
              'A comparative affirmative sentence can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) by using the positive degree structure with ''not as...as''. ''I am not as rich as him'' is the correct negative equivalent of ''He is richer than me''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''She has been reading for two hours.''?',
              ARRAY['Has she been reading for two hours?', 'Have she been reading for two hours?', 'Is she been reading for two hours?', 'Has she reading for two hours?'],
              0,
              'This sentence is in the present perfect continuous tense (বর্তমান পূর্ণ চলমান কাল). To form a question, the first auxiliary verb (''has'') is placed at the beginning of the sentence. So, ''Has she been reading for two hours?'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is sure of his success.''',
              ARRAY['He is sure and he will succeed.', 'He is sure that he will succeed.', 'He is sure of success.', 'He is sure to succeed.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has a prepositional phrase (''of his success''). This can be expanded into a noun clause. ''He is sure that he will succeed'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The hunter shot the tiger.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The tiger was shot by the hunter.', 'The tiger is shot by the hunter.', 'The tiger had been shot by the hunter.', 'The tiger was being shot by the hunter.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল). The passive form is ''was/were + past participle''. So, ''The tiger was shot by the hunter'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The Taj Mahal is a very beautiful building.''',
              ARRAY['What a beautiful building the Taj Mahal is!', 'How beautiful building the Taj Mahal is!', 'What beautiful building the Taj Mahal is!', 'How a beautiful building the Taj Mahal is!'],
              0,
              'For a singular noun phrase (''a beautiful building''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Therefore, ''What a beautiful building the Taj Mahal is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He is sometimes absent.''?',
              ARRAY['He is not sometimes absent.', 'He is never absent.', 'He is not always absent.', 'He is always present.'],
              2,
              '''Sometimes'' (কখনো কখনো) indicates frequency. Its negative equivalent is ''not always'' (সবসময় না). So, ''He is not always absent'' correctly transforms the sentence into a negative form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''Everybody fears a lion.''',
              ARRAY['Does everybody fear a lion?', 'Who does not fear a lion?', 'Does anybody fear a lion?', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'An affirmative statement can be turned into a question in two ways. One is a direct question: ''Does everybody fear a lion?'' The other is a rhetorical question implying the answer: ''Who does not fear a lion?'' Both are correct transformations.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He confessed his crime.''',
              ARRAY['He confessed that he was criminal.', 'He confessed that he had committed the crime.', 'He confessed his crime and cried.', 'He confessed to commit the crime.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has a noun object (''his crime''). To make it complex (জটিল), we expand the noun into a noun clause. The action of the crime happened before the confession, so the past perfect tense is used in the clause. ''He confessed that he had committed the crime'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The man is shouting at the boy.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The boy is shouted at by the man.', 'The boy is being shouted at by the man.', 'The boy was being shouted at by the man.', 'The boy is shouted by the man.'],
              1,
              'The active sentence is in the present continuous tense (বর্তমান চলমান কাল): ''is shouting at''. The passive structure is ''is/am/are + being + past participle''. The preposition ''at'' stays with the verb. So, ''The boy is being shouted at by the man'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not incapable of doing the work.''',
              ARRAY['He is incapable of doing the work.', 'He is capable of doing the work.', 'He is not capable of doing the work.', 'He can do the work.'],
              1,
              '''Not incapable'' (অক্ষম নয়) is a double negative which makes an affirmative. It means he is capable. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He is capable of doing the work''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should obey your teachers.''?',
              ARRAY['Obey your teachers.', 'You obey your teachers.', 'Should obey your teachers.', 'Obedience to your teachers.'],
              0,
              'This sentence expresses advice. An imperative sentence (অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) for advice starts with the base form of the verb. So, ''Obey your teachers'' is the correct transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is better than me.''',
              ARRAY['He is not better than me.', 'I am not as good as him.', 'I am worse than him.', 'He is less good than me.'],
              1,
              'A comparative affirmative sentence can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) by using the positive degree structure with ''not as...as''. ''I am not as good as him'' is the correct negative equivalent of ''He is better than me''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''I wish I could fly in the sky.''',
              ARRAY['If I could fly in the sky!', 'Could I fly in the sky!', 'Oh that I could fly in the sky!', 'All of these'],
              3,
              'Wishes can be expressed exclamatorily (আবেগসূচকভাবে) in several ways: using ''If'', using inversion (''Could I''), or using ''Oh that''. All three options A, B, and C are correct exclamatory forms.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''Someone has stolen my purse.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['My purse has been stolen.', 'My purse is stolen by someone.', 'My purse was stolen.', 'My purse had been stolen.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the present perfect tense (বর্তমান পূর্ণ কাল): ''has stolen''. The passive structure is ''has/have + been + past participle''. When the agent (''someone'') is unknown or unimportant, it is often omitted. So, ''My purse has been stolen'' is the best answer.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He was too late to attend the meeting.''',
              ARRAY['He was so late that he could not attend the meeting.', 'He was very late to attend the meeting.', 'He was late and could not attend the meeting.', 'He was late so he could not attend the meeting.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' (অত্যন্ত...যে না) can be transformed into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) using ''so...that...cannot/could not''. ''He was so late that he could not attend the meeting'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''They have finished the project.''?',
              ARRAY['Have they finished the project?', 'Has they finished the project?', 'Did they finish the project?', 'Are they finished the project?'],
              0,
              'For the present perfect tense (বর্তমান পূর্ণ কাল), the auxiliary verb ''have/has'' is placed at the beginning to form a question. Since the subject is ''They'', ''Have they finished the project?'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not a fool.''',
              ARRAY['He is a fool.', 'He is wise.', 'He is not wise.', 'He is clever.'],
              3,
              '''Not a fool'' (বোকা নয়) implies he is intelligent or clever. The most appropriate affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) equivalent is ''He is clever''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''We saw him going out.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['He was seen going out by us.', 'He was seen to go out by us.', 'He is seen going out by us.', 'He had been seen going out.'],
              0,
              'In sentences with verbs of perception (see, hear, feel) followed by an object and a present participle, the passive structure is ''subject + was/were + seen + present participle + by agent''. So, ''He was seen going out by us'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The garden is very beautiful.''',
              ARRAY['What a beautiful garden it is!', 'How beautiful garden it is!', 'How beautiful the garden is!', 'What beautiful garden it is!'],
              2,
              'For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with an adjective, we use ''How'' before the adjective. The structure is ''How + adjective + subject + verb!'' Here, ''garden'' is the subject, so ''How beautiful the garden is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He is my friend.''?',
              ARRAY['He is not my friend.', 'He is my enemy.', 'He is not my enemy.', 'He is no friend of mine.'],
              0,
              'The direct negative (নেতিবাচক) transformation of a sentence with the verb ''to be'' is simply adding ''not'' after the verb. So, ''He is not my friend'' is the correct negative form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I have no money to spare.''',
              ARRAY['I have no money and I cannot spare.', 'I have no money that I can spare.', 'I have no money so I cannot spare.', 'I have no money for sparing.'],
              1,
              'The infinitive phrase ''to spare'' acts as an adjective modifying ''money''. It can be expanded into an adjective clause. ''I have no money that I can spare'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They are building a new hospital.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A new hospital is built by them.', 'A new hospital is being built by them.', 'A new hospital was being built by them.', 'A new hospital has been built by them.'],
              1,
              'The active sentence is in the present continuous tense (বর্তমান চলমান কাল): ''are building''. The passive structure is ''is/am/are + being + past participle''. So, ''A new hospital is being built by them'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He never comes late.''',
              ARRAY['Does he never come late?', 'Does he ever come late?', 'Comes he late never?', 'Never does he come late?'],
              1,
              'A negative statement can be turned into an affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) question. ''Never'' (কখনও না) becomes ''ever'' (কখনও) in the interrogative. So, ''Does he ever come late?'' is the correct form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''No other city in Bangladesh is as large as Dhaka.''',
              ARRAY['Dhaka is larger than any other city in Bangladesh.', 'Dhaka is larger than all other cities in Bangladesh.', 'Dhaka is the largest city in Bangladesh.', 'All other cities are smaller than Dhaka.'],
              0,
              'The positive degree (সকারাত্মক) sentence ''No other...as...as'' implies Dhaka is the largest. Its comparative (তুলনামূলক) form is ''Dhaka is larger than any other city in Bangladesh''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''He must work hard to earn his livelihood.''?',
              ARRAY['He must work hard and earn his livelihood.', 'He must work hard so that he can earn his livelihood.', 'He must work hard or he will not earn his livelihood.', 'He works hard to earn his livelihood.'],
              2,
              'The simple sentence uses an infinitive (''to earn'') to show purpose. A compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) can be formed using ''or''. The idea is that if he does not work hard, he will not earn. So, ''He must work hard or he will not earn his livelihood'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not without ambition.''',
              ARRAY['He has no ambition.', 'He is ambitious.', 'He is not ambitious.', 'He has ambition.'],
              3,
              '''Not without'' (ছাড়া নয়) is a double negative which makes an affirmative. It means he possesses ambition. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He has ambition''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''I heard her sing a song.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['She was heard sing a song by me.', 'She was heard to sing a song by me.', 'She is heard to sing a song by me.', 'She was heard singing a song by me.'],
              1,
              'With verbs of perception (see, hear, watch) followed by an object and a bare infinitive, the passive takes a ''to-infinitive''. So, ''I heard her sing'' becomes ''She was heard to sing'' in passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very sad news.''',
              ARRAY['What a sad news it is!', 'How sad news it is!', 'What sad news it is!', 'How a sad news it is!'],
              2,
              '''News'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য বিশেষ্য), so we do not use ''a'' before it. For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with an uncountable noun, we use ''What'' directly before the adjective+noun. So, ''What sad news it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''She was writing a letter.''?',
              ARRAY['Was she writing a letter?', 'Did she write a letter?', 'Is she writing a letter?', 'Were she writing a letter?'],
              0,
              'This sentence is in the past continuous tense (অতীত চলমান কাল). To form a question, the auxiliary verb (''was'') is placed at the beginning. So, ''Was she writing a letter?'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I know the time of his arrival.''',
              ARRAY['I know the time and he arrives.', 'I know when he will arrive.', 'I know the time of arrival.', 'I know the time to arrive.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has a noun phrase (''the time of his arrival''). This can be expanded into a noun clause. ''I know when he will arrive'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The boy killed a snake.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A snake was killed by the boy.', 'A snake is killed by the boy.', 'A snake had been killed by the boy.', 'A snake was being killed by the boy.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল). The passive form is ''was/were + past participle''. So, ''A snake was killed by the boy'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He did not fail to help me.''',
              ARRAY['He failed to help me.', 'He helped me.', 'He did help me.', 'He did not help me.'],
              1,
              '''Did not fail to'' (ব্যর্থ হয়নি) is a double negative which makes a strong affirmative. It means he was successful in helping. Therefore, the simple affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He helped me''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is wiser than me.''',
              ARRAY['He is not wiser than me.', 'I am not as wise as him.', 'I am more foolish than him.', 'He is less wise than me.'],
              1,
              'A comparative affirmative sentence can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) by using the positive degree structure with ''not as...as''. ''I am not as wise as him'' is the correct negative equivalent of ''He is wiser than me''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should not make a noise.''?',
              ARRAY['Do not make a noise.', 'Not make a noise.', 'You do not make a noise.', 'Make not a noise.'],
              0,
              'This is a piece of advice in the negative. A negative imperative sentence (নেতিবাচক অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) is formed with ''Do not'' (or ''Don''t'') followed by the base form of the verb. So, ''Do not make a noise'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''Nobody can escape death.''',
              ARRAY['Can anybody escape death?', 'Can nobody escape death?', 'Who can escape death?', 'Both A and C'],
              3,
              'A negative statement can be turned into a question in two ways. One is by using ''anybody'': ''Can anybody escape death?'' The other is by using a ''who'' question implying a negative answer: ''Who can escape death?'' (meaning nobody can). Both are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He impressed me with his sincerity.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['I was impressed by him with his sincerity.', 'I was impressed with his sincerity by him.', 'I was impressed by his sincerity.', 'His sincerity impressed me.'],
              2,
              'The verb ''impress'' (মুগ্ধ করা) is often used in the passive with the preposition ''by'' for the thing that causes the impression. The active sentence''s object ''me'' becomes the subject. So, ''I was impressed by his sincerity'' is correct. The agent ''him'' is often omitted in such cases.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very beautiful bird.''',
              ARRAY['What a beautiful bird it is!', 'How beautiful bird it is!', 'What beautiful bird it is!', 'How a beautiful bird it is!'],
              0,
              'For a singular countable noun (''bird''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Therefore, ''What a beautiful bird it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''Everybody desires happiness.''?',
              ARRAY['Anybody desires happiness.', 'Nobody desires happiness.', 'There is nobody but desires happiness.', 'Everybody does not desire happiness.'],
              2,
              'An affirmative sentence with ''Everybody'' can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) using the structure ''There is nobody but + affirmative verb''. ''There is nobody but desires happiness'' means ''There is no one who does not desire happiness'', which is the negative equivalent.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is too proud to beg.''',
              ARRAY['He is so proud that he cannot beg.', 'He is very proud to beg.', 'He is proud and cannot beg.', 'He is proud so he cannot beg.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' (অত্যন্ত...যে না) can be transformed into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) using ''so...that...cannot/could not''. ''He is so proud that he cannot beg'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The doctor is operating on the patient.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The patient is operated on by the doctor.', 'The patient is being operated on by the doctor.', 'The patient was being operated on by the doctor.', 'The patient has been operated on by the doctor.'],
              1,
              'The active sentence is in the present continuous tense (বর্তমান চলমান কাল): ''is operating on''. The passive structure is ''is/am/are + being + past participle''. The preposition ''on'' stays with the verb. So, ''The patient is being operated on by the doctor'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not a coward.''',
              ARRAY['He is a coward.', 'He is brave.', 'He is not brave.', 'He is fearless.'],
              1,
              '''Not a coward'' (কাপুরুষ নয়) implies he is brave. The most appropriate affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) equivalent is ''He is brave''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''He had left before I arrived.''?',
              ARRAY['Had he left before I arrived?', 'Did he leave before I arrived?', 'Has he left before I arrived?', 'Was he left before I arrived?'],
              0,
              'The sentence is in the past perfect tense (অতীত পূর্ণ কাল). To form a question, the auxiliary verb ''had'' is placed at the beginning of the sentence. So, ''Had he left before I arrived?'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''Very few subjects are as interesting as English.''',
              ARRAY['English is more interesting than most other subjects.', 'English is more interesting than any other subject.', 'English is the most interesting subject.', 'No other subject is as interesting as English.'],
              0,
              'The positive degree (সকারাত্মক) ''as interesting as'' with ''Very few'' implies English is more interesting than most others. The correct comparative (তুলনামূলক) transformation is ''English is more interesting than most other subjects''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I cannot help him, being poor myself.''',
              ARRAY['I cannot help him because I am poor myself.', 'I cannot help him and I am poor myself.', 'I cannot help him for I am poor myself.', 'Being poor, I cannot help him.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence has a participle phrase (''being poor myself'') which shows reason. To make it complex (জটিল), we expand it into an adverb clause of reason. ''I cannot help him because I am poor myself'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The children laughed at the beggar.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The beggar was laughed at by the children.', 'The beggar was being laughed at by the children.', 'The beggar is laughed at by the children.', 'The beggar was laughed by the children.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল): ''laughed at''. The passive structure is ''was/were + past participle''. The preposition ''at'' stays with the verb. So, ''The beggar was laughed at by the children'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The news is very shocking.''',
              ARRAY['What a shocking news it is!', 'How shocking news it is!', 'What shocking news it is!', 'How a shocking news it is!'],
              2,
              '''News'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য বিশেষ্য), so we do not use ''a'' before it. For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with an uncountable noun, we use ''What'' directly before the adjective+noun. So, ''What shocking news it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He was present.''?',
              ARRAY['He was not present.', 'He was absent.', 'He was not absent.', 'He did not present.'],
              1,
              'The word ''present'' (উপস্থিত) has a direct opposite, ''absent'' (অনুপস্থিত). Therefore, the negative form can be created by using the antonym. ''He was absent'' is the correct negative transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He has never been to Cox''s Bazar.''',
              ARRAY['Has he never been to Cox''s Bazar?', 'Has he ever been to Cox''s Bazar?', 'Did he ever go to Cox''s Bazar?', 'Both A and B'],
              1,
              'A negative statement can be turned into an affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) question. ''Never'' (কখনও না) becomes ''ever'' (কখনও) in the interrogative. So, ''Has he ever been to Cox''s Bazar?'' is the correct form, though option A is also grammatically possible, B is the standard transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I saw a smiling baby.''',
              ARRAY['I saw a baby and it was smiling.', 'I saw a baby who was smiling.', 'I saw a baby that smiling.', 'I saw a baby was smiling.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has a participle (''smiling'') acting as an adjective. To make it complex (জটিল), we expand it into an adjective clause. ''I saw a baby who was smiling'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''We must listen to his advice.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['His advice must be listened to by us.', 'His advice must be listened by us.', 'His advice must be heard by us.', 'His advice must be attended.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence contains a phrasal verb ''listen to'' (শোনা/মনোযোগ দেওয়া). In the passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য), the preposition ''to'' must stay with the verb. So, ''His advice must be listened to by us'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not indifferent to his studies.''',
              ARRAY['He is indifferent to his studies.', 'He is attentive to his studies.', 'He is not attentive to his studies.', 'He cares about his studies.'],
              1,
              '''Indifferent'' (উদাসীন) means not caring. ''Not indifferent'' (উদাসীন নয়) means he is attentive or caring. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He is attentive to his studies''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should not tell a lie.''?',
              ARRAY['Do not tell a lie.', 'Not tell a lie.', 'You do not tell a lie.', 'Tell not a lie.'],
              0,
              'This is a piece of advice in the negative. A negative imperative sentence (নেতিবাচক অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) is formed with ''Do not'' (or ''Don''t'') followed by the base form of the verb. So, ''Do not tell a lie'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is the most intelligent boy in the class.''',
              ARRAY['He is not the most intelligent boy in the class.', 'No other boy in the class is as intelligent as he.', 'No other boy in the class is more intelligent than he.', 'All other boys are less intelligent than he.'],
              1,
              'A superlative (অতি-উৎকর্ষতা) sentence can be transformed into a negative (নেতিবাচক) sentence using the positive degree structure: ''No other + noun + verb + as + adjective + as + subject.'' So, ''No other boy in the class is as intelligent as he'' is the correct negative form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is certain of winning the game.''',
              ARRAY['He is certain and he will win the game.', 'He is certain that he will win the game.', 'He is certain to win the game.', 'He is certain of the win.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has a prepositional phrase (''of winning the game''). This can be expanded into a noun clause. ''He is certain that he will win the game'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He was carrying a heavy load.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A heavy load was carried by him.', 'A heavy load was being carried by him.', 'A heavy load is being carried by him.', 'A heavy load had been carried by him.'],
              1,
              'The active sentence is in the past continuous tense (অতীত চলমান কাল): ''was carrying''. The passive structure is ''was/were + being + past participle''. So, ''A heavy load was being carried by him'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very interesting story.''',
              ARRAY['What a interesting story it is!', 'What an interesting story it is!', 'How interesting story it is!', 'What interesting story it is!'],
              1,
              'For a singular countable noun (''story''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a/an + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Since ''interesting'' starts with a vowel sound, we use ''an''. So, ''What an interesting story it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''She can speak French fluently.''?',
              ARRAY['Can she speak French fluently?', 'Does she can speak French fluently?', 'Is she can speak French fluently?', 'Speaks she French fluently?'],
              0,
              'For sentences with modal verbs (যেমন can, may, must, should), the interrogative form is created by placing the modal verb at the beginning before the subject. So, ''Can she speak French fluently?'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He has not a few friends.''',
              ARRAY['He has a few friends.', 'He has many friends.', 'He has few friends.', 'He has no friends.'],
              1,
              '''Not a few'' (কম নয়) is an idiom that means ''many'' (অনেক). Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form of the sentence is ''He has many friends''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''He is not the tallest boy in the class.''',
              ARRAY['He is not taller than any other boy in the class.', 'Some other boys are taller than him.', 'He is shorter than some other boys.', 'He is less tall than some other boys.'],
              2,
              'The negative superlative (অতি-উৎকর্ষতার নেতিবাচক) means there are others who are taller. The comparative (তুলনামূলক) equivalent is ''He is shorter than some other boys''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is too young to marry.''',
              ARRAY['He is so young that he cannot marry.', 'He is very young to marry.', 'He is young and cannot marry.', 'He is young so he cannot marry.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' (অত্যন্ত...যে না) can be transformed into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) using ''so...that...cannot/could not''. ''He is so young that he cannot marry'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He has written a novel.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A novel has been written by him.', 'A novel is written by him.', 'A novel was written by him.', 'A novel had been written by him.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the present perfect tense (বর্তমান পূর্ণ কাল): ''has written''. The passive structure is ''has/have + been + past participle''. So, ''A novel has been written by him'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He has a lot of money.''',
              ARRAY['Has he a lot of money?', 'Does he have a lot of money?', 'Does he has a lot of money?', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'For sentences with ''has/have'' as the main verb, two interrogative forms are possible. The formal one inverts the verb: ''Has he a lot of money?'' The more common modern one uses ''does'': ''Does he have a lot of money?'' Both are acceptable.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''Every man loves his country.''?',
              ARRAY['Any man loves his country.', 'No man loves his country.', 'There is no man but loves his country.', 'Every man does not love his country.'],
              2,
              'An affirmative sentence with ''Every'' can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) using the structure ''There is no + noun + but + affirmative verb''. ''There is no man but loves his country'' means ''There is no man who does not love his country'', which is the negative equivalent.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very charming scenery.''',
              ARRAY['What a charming scenery it is!', 'How charming scenery it is!', 'How charming the scenery is!', 'What charming scenery it is!'],
              2,
              '''Scenery'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য বিশেষ্য), so we do not use ''a'' before it. For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with an adjective, we use ''How'' before the adjective. The structure is ''How + adjective + subject + verb!'' So, ''How charming the scenery is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not unlike me.''',
              ARRAY['He is unlike me.', 'He is like me.', 'He is not like me.', 'He resembles me.'],
              1,
              '''Not unlike'' (অসদৃশ নয়) is a double negative which makes an affirmative. It means he is similar to me. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He is like me''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''She did the work alone.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The work was done alone by her.', 'The work is done alone by her.', 'The work had been done alone by her.', 'The work was being done alone by her.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল). The passive form is ''was/were + past participle''. The adverb ''alone'' remains in its position. So, ''The work was done alone by her'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should be kind to the poor.''?',
              ARRAY['Be kind to the poor.', 'You be kind to the poor.', 'Should be kind to the poor.', 'Being kind to the poor.'],
              0,
              'This is a piece of advice. An imperative sentence (অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) for advice starts with the base form of the verb. So, ''Be kind to the poor'' is the correct transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''Nobody will help you.''',
              ARRAY['Will anybody help you?', 'Will nobody help you?', 'Who will help you?', 'Both A and C'],
              3,
              'A negative statement can be turned into a question in two ways. One is by using ''anybody'': ''Will anybody help you?'' The other is by using a ''who'' question implying a negative answer: ''Who will help you?'' (meaning nobody will). Both are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I want to buy a car.''',
              ARRAY['I want that I buy a car.', 'I want that I will buy a car.', 'I want to buy a car and I will.', 'I want a car to buy.'],
              1,
              'The infinitive phrase ''to buy a car'' can be expanded into a noun clause. ''I want that I will buy a car'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form, though it sounds a bit formal. It correctly shows the noun clause structure.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He annoyed me.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['I was annoyed by him.', 'I was annoyed with him.', 'I am annoyed with him.', 'I was annoyed at him.'],
              1,
              'The verb ''annoy'' (বিরক্ত করা) is typically followed by the preposition ''with'' when referring to a person in its passive form. So, ''I was annoyed with him'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is as good as his brother.''',
              ARRAY['He is not as good as his brother.', 'His brother is not better than him.', 'He is better than his brother.', 'His brother is not as good as him.'],
              1,
              'The positive degree (সকারাত্মক) ''as...as'' indicates equality. Its negative form in the comparative degree is ''not + comparative adjective + than''. So, ''His brother is not better than him'' means the same as ''He is as good as his brother''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The song is very sweet.''',
              ARRAY['What a sweet song it is!', 'How sweet song it is!', 'How sweet the song is!', 'What sweet song it is!'],
              2,
              'For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with an adjective, we use ''How'' before the adjective. The structure is ''How + adjective + subject + verb!'' Here, ''song'' is the subject, so ''How sweet the song is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''He is too ill to attend the meeting.''?',
              ARRAY['He is very ill and cannot attend the meeting.', 'He is so ill that he cannot attend the meeting.', 'He is ill, so he cannot attend the meeting.', 'He is ill to attend the meeting.'],
              2,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' has a meaning that can be expressed in a compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) using the conjunction ''so''. ''He is ill, so he cannot attend the meeting'' is the correct compound form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not an inefficient worker.''',
              ARRAY['He is an inefficient worker.', 'He is an efficient worker.', 'He is not an efficient worker.', 'He works inefficiently.'],
              1,
              '''Inefficient'' (অদক্ষ) is the opposite of ''efficient'' (দক্ষ). ''Not inefficient'' (অদক্ষ নয়) means he is efficient. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He is an efficient worker''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They will build a bridge here.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['A bridge will be built here by them.', 'A bridge would be built here by them.', 'A bridge is built here by them.', 'A bridge will have been built here.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple future tense (ভবিষ্যৎ কাল): ''will build''. The passive structure is ''will be + past participle''. So, ''A bridge will be built here by them'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He had no car.''',
              ARRAY['Did he have any car?', 'Had he any car?', 'Did he had any car?', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'For past tense sentences with ''had'' as the main verb, two interrogative forms are possible. The formal one inverts the verb: ''Had he any car?'' The more common modern one uses ''did'': ''Did he have any car?'' Both are acceptable.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is a man of great learning.''',
              ARRAY['He is a man and he has great learning.', 'He is a man who has great learning.', 'He is a man of learning.', 'He is a learned man.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has a prepositional phrase (''of great learning'') modifying the noun ''man''. To make it complex (জটিল), we expand it into an adjective clause. ''He is a man who has great learning'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He is sometimes present.''?',
              ARRAY['He is not sometimes present.', 'He is never present.', 'He is not always present.', 'He is always absent.'],
              2,
              '''Sometimes'' (কখনো কখনো) indicates frequency. Its negative equivalent is ''not always'' (সবসময় না). So, ''He is not always present'' correctly transforms the sentence into a negative form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very funny matter.''',
              ARRAY['What a funny matter it is!', 'How funny matter it is!', 'What funny matter it is!', 'How a funny matter it is!'],
              0,
              'For a singular countable noun (''matter''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Therefore, ''What a funny matter it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He made me laugh.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['I was made laugh by him.', 'I was made to laugh by him.', 'I am made to laugh by him.', 'I had been made to laugh.'],
              1,
              'With causative verbs like ''make'' followed by an object and a bare infinitive, the passive takes a ''to-infinitive''. So, ''He made me laugh'' becomes ''I was made to laugh by him'' in passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He did not miss any opportunity.''',
              ARRAY['He missed every opportunity.', 'He utilized every opportunity.', 'He did not get any opportunity.', 'He had no opportunity.'],
              1,
              '''Did not miss any opportunity'' (কোনো সুযোগ হাতছাড়া করেনি) means he used or took advantage of every opportunity. The affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) equivalent is ''He utilized every opportunity''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''Very few girls in the class are as beautiful as Tania.''',
              ARRAY['Tania is more beautiful than most other girls in the class.', 'Tania is more beautiful than any other girl in the class.', 'Tania is the most beautiful girl in the class.', 'No other girl is as beautiful as Tania.'],
              0,
              'The positive degree (সকারাত্মক) ''as beautiful as'' with ''Very few'' implies Tania is more beautiful than most others. The correct comparative (তুলনামূলক) transformation is ''Tania is more beautiful than most other girls in the class''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct interrogative form of ''They were playing cricket.''?',
              ARRAY['Were they playing cricket?', 'Did they play cricket?', 'Are they playing cricket?', 'Was they playing cricket?'],
              0,
              'This sentence is in the past continuous tense (অতীত চলমান কাল). To form a question, the auxiliary verb (''were'') is placed at the beginning. So, ''Were they playing cricket?'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is certain of success.''',
              ARRAY['He is certain and he will succeed.', 'He is certain that he will succeed.', 'He is certain to succeed.', 'He is certain of his success.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has a prepositional phrase (''of success''). This can be expanded into a noun clause. ''He is certain that he will succeed'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''Nobody trusts a liar.''',
              ARRAY['Does anybody trust a liar?', 'Does nobody trust a liar?', 'Who trusts a liar?', 'Both A and C'],
              3,
              'A negative statement can be turned into a question in two ways. One is by using ''anybody'': ''Does anybody trust a liar?'' The other is by using a ''who'' question implying a negative answer: ''Who trusts a liar?'' (meaning nobody trusts). Both are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He handed me a book.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['I was handed a book by him.', 'A book was handed to me by him.', 'A book was handed me by him.', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'This sentence has two objects: ''me'' (indirect object) and ''a book'' (direct object). In passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য), either object can become the subject. So, both ''I was handed a book by him'' and ''A book was handed to me by him'' are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very exciting match.''',
              ARRAY['What a exciting match it is!', 'What an exciting match it is!', 'How exciting match it is!', 'What exciting match it is!'],
              1,
              'For a singular countable noun (''match''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a/an + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Since ''exciting'' starts with a vowel sound, we use ''an''. So, ''What an exciting match it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''All men are mortal.''?',
              ARRAY['All men are not mortal.', 'No man is mortal.', 'There is no man but is mortal.', 'No man is immortal.'],
              2,
              'An affirmative sentence with ''All'' can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) using the structure ''There is no + noun + but + affirmative verb''. ''There is no man but is mortal'' means ''There is no man who is not mortal'', which is the negative equivalent.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is too poor to educate his children.''',
              ARRAY['He is so poor that he cannot educate his children.', 'He is very poor to educate his children.', 'He is poor and cannot educate his children.', 'He is poor so he cannot educate his children.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' (অত্যন্ত...যে না) can be transformed into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) using ''so...that...cannot/could not''. ''He is so poor that he cannot educate his children'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The teacher was examining the students.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The students were examined by the teacher.', 'The students were being examined by the teacher.', 'The students are being examined by the teacher.', 'The students had been examined by the teacher.'],
              1,
              'The active sentence is in the past continuous tense (অতীত চলমান কাল): ''was examining''. The passive structure is ''was/were + being + past participle''. So, ''The students were being examined by the teacher'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not an idle boy.''',
              ARRAY['He is an idle boy.', 'He is an active boy.', 'He is a lazy boy.', 'He is a hardworking boy.'],
              3,
              '''Idle'' (অলস) means not working. ''Not idle'' (অলস নয়) implies he is hardworking. The most appropriate affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) equivalent is ''He is a hardworking boy''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should not waste your time.''?',
              ARRAY['Do not waste your time.', 'Not waste your time.', 'You do not waste your time.', 'Waste not your time.'],
              0,
              'This is a piece of advice in the negative. A negative imperative sentence (নেতিবাচক অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) is formed with ''Do not'' (or ''Don''t'') followed by the base form of the verb. So, ''Do not waste your time'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He has a car.''',
              ARRAY['Has he a car?', 'Does he have a car?', 'Does he has a car?', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'For sentences with ''has/have'' as the main verb, two interrogative forms are possible. The formal one inverts the verb: ''Has he a car?'' The more common modern one uses ''does'': ''Does he have a car?'' Both are acceptable.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a negative sentence: ''He is the best player.''',
              ARRAY['He is not the best player.', 'No other player is as good as he.', 'No other player is better than he.', 'All other players are worse than he.'],
              1,
              'A superlative (অতি-উৎকর্ষতা) sentence can be transformed into a negative (নেতিবাচক) sentence using the positive degree structure: ''No other + noun + verb + as + adjective + as + subject.'' So, ''No other player is as good as he'' is the correct negative form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He expects to get a promotion.''',
              ARRAY['He expects that he will get a promotion.', 'He expects and he will get a promotion.', 'He expects to get a promotion soon.', 'He expects a promotion.'],
              0,
              'The infinitive phrase ''to get a promotion'' can be expanded into a noun clause. ''He expects that he will get a promotion'' is the correct complex (জটিল) form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They saw him running away.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['He was seen running away by them.', 'He was seen to run away by them.', 'He is seen running away by them.', 'He had been seen running away.'],
              0,
              'In sentences with verbs of perception (see, hear, etc.) followed by an object and a present participle, the passive structure is ''subject + was/were + seen + present participle + by agent''. So, ''He was seen running away by them'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The rose is a very beautiful flower.''',
              ARRAY['What a beautiful flower the rose is!', 'How beautiful flower the rose is!', 'What beautiful flower the rose is!', 'How a beautiful flower the rose is!'],
              0,
              'For a singular noun phrase (''a beautiful flower''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Therefore, ''What a beautiful flower the rose is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''Though he is rich, he is not happy.''?',
              ARRAY['He is rich but not happy.', 'He is rich and not happy.', 'He is rich, so he is happy.', 'He is rich for he is not happy.'],
              0,
              'A complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) with a concessive clause (''Though'') can be transformed into a compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য) using the coordinating conjunction ''but''. ''He is rich but not happy'' is the correct compound form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He did not fail to recognize me.''',
              ARRAY['He failed to recognize me.', 'He recognized me.', 'He did recognize me.', 'He did not recognize me.'],
              1,
              '''Did not fail to'' (ব্যর্থ হয়নি) is a double negative which makes a strong affirmative. It means he was successful in recognizing. Therefore, the simple affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He recognized me''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''She cooks food for us.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['Food is cooked for us by her.', 'We are cooked food by her.', 'We are cooked food for by her.', 'Both A and B'],
              0,
              'This sentence has two objects: ''food'' (direct object) and ''us'' (indirect object). In passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য), it''s more common to make the direct object the subject. So, ''Food is cooked for us by her'' is correct. Making ''us'' the subject (''We are cooked food by her'') is grammatically possible but less natural.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''Nobody could solve the problem.''',
              ARRAY['Could anybody solve the problem?', 'Could nobody solve the problem?', 'Who could solve the problem?', 'Both A and C'],
              3,
              'A negative statement can be turned into a question in two ways. One is by using ''anybody'': ''Could anybody solve the problem?'' The other is by using a ''who'' question implying a negative answer: ''Who could solve the problem?'' (meaning nobody could). Both are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I saw a dead man on the road.''',
              ARRAY['I saw a man and he was dead on the road.', 'I saw a man who was dead on the road.', 'I saw a man that dead on the road.', 'I saw a man on the road and he was dead.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has an adjective (''dead'') modifying the noun ''man''. To make it complex (জটিল), we expand the adjective into an adjective clause. ''I saw a man who was dead on the road'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He is sometimes happy.''?',
              ARRAY['He is not sometimes happy.', 'He is never happy.', 'He is not always happy.', 'He is always unhappy.'],
              2,
              '''Sometimes'' (কখনো কখনো) indicates frequency. Its negative equivalent is ''not always'' (সবসময় না). So, ''He is not always happy'' correctly transforms the sentence into a negative form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very important matter.''',
              ARRAY['What a important matter it is!', 'What an important matter it is!', 'How important matter it is!', 'What important matter it is!'],
              1,
              'For a singular countable noun (''matter''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a/an + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Since ''important'' starts with a vowel sound, we use ''an''. So, ''What an important matter it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He hurt me.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['I was hurt by him.', 'I was hurt with him.', 'I am hurt by him.', 'I had been hurt by him.'],
              0,
              'The verb ''hurt'' (আঘাত করা) is regular in its past form. The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল). The passive form is ''was/were + past participle''. So, ''I was hurt by him'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not an unkind man.''',
              ARRAY['He is an unkind man.', 'He is a kind man.', 'He is not a kind man.', 'He is cruel.'],
              1,
              '''Unkind'' (অদয়ালু) is the opposite of ''kind'' (দয়ালু). ''Not unkind'' (অদয়ালু নয়) means he is kind. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He is a kind man''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should take exercise regularly.''?',
              ARRAY['Take exercise regularly.', 'You take exercise regularly.', 'Should take exercise regularly.', 'Taking exercise regularly.'],
              0,
              'This is a piece of advice. An imperative sentence (অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) for advice starts with the base form of the verb. So, ''Take exercise regularly'' is the correct transformation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He never tells the truth.''',
              ARRAY['Does he never tell the truth?', 'Does he ever tell the truth?', 'Tells he the truth never?', 'Never does he tell the truth?'],
              1,
              'A negative statement can be turned into an affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) question. ''Never'' (কখনও না) becomes ''ever'' (কখনও) in the interrogative. So, ''Does he ever tell the truth?'' is the correct form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a comparative sentence: ''Very few students are as attentive as Rakib.''',
              ARRAY['Rakib is more attentive than most other students.', 'Rakib is more attentive than any other student.', 'Rakib is the most attentive student.', 'No other student is as attentive as Rakib.'],
              0,
              'The positive degree (সকারাত্মক) ''as attentive as'' with ''Very few'' implies Rakib is more attentive than most others. The correct comparative (তুলনামূলক) transformation is ''Rakib is more attentive than most other students''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He was too tired to continue the work.''',
              ARRAY['He was so tired that he could not continue the work.', 'He was very tired to continue the work.', 'He was tired and could not continue the work.', 'He was tired so he could not continue the work.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' (অত্যন্ত...যে না) can be transformed into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) using ''so...that...cannot/could not''. ''He was so tired that he could not continue the work'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''She gave me a pen.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['I was given a pen by her.', 'A pen was given to me by her.', 'A pen was given me by her.', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'This sentence has two objects: ''me'' (indirect object) and ''a pen'' (direct object). In passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য), either object can become the subject. So, both ''I was given a pen by her'' and ''A pen was given to me by her'' are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The child is very innocent.''',
              ARRAY['What an innocent child he is!', 'How innocent child he is!', 'How innocent the child is!', 'What innocent child it is!'],
              2,
              'For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with an adjective, we use ''How'' before the adjective. The structure is ''How + adjective + subject + verb!'' Here, ''child'' is the subject, so ''How innocent the child is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''Every cloud has a silver lining.''?',
              ARRAY['Any cloud has a silver lining.', 'No cloud has a silver lining.', 'There is no cloud but has a silver lining.', 'Every cloud does not have a silver lining.'],
              2,
              'An affirmative sentence with ''Every'' can be made negative (নেতিবাচক) using the structure ''There is no + noun + but + affirmative verb''. ''There is no cloud but has a silver lining'' means ''There is no cloud that does not have a silver lining'', which is the negative equivalent.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not an illiterate person.''',
              ARRAY['He is an illiterate person.', 'He is a literate person.', 'He is not a literate person.', 'He is educated.'],
              1,
              '''Illiterate'' (অশিক্ষিত) is the opposite of ''literate'' (শিক্ষিত). ''Not illiterate'' (অশিক্ষিত নয়) means he is literate. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He is a literate person''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''He will have finished the work by then.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The work will have been finished by him by then.', 'The work will be finished by him by then.', 'The work would have been finished by him by then.', 'The work has been finished by him by then.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the future perfect tense (ভবিষ্যৎ পূর্ণ কাল): ''will have finished''. The passive structure is ''will have been + past participle''. So, ''The work will have been finished by him by then'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''He had no money to spare.''',
              ARRAY['Did he have any money to spare?', 'Had he any money to spare?', 'Did he had any money to spare?', 'Both A and B'],
              3,
              'For past tense sentences with ''had'' as the main verb, two interrogative forms are possible. The formal one inverts the verb: ''Had he any money to spare?'' The more common modern one uses ''did'': ''Did he have any money to spare?'' Both are acceptable.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I have a friend in America.''',
              ARRAY['I have a friend and he lives in America.', 'I have a friend who lives in America.', 'I have a friend that in America.', 'I have a friend living in America.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has a prepositional phrase (''in America'') modifying the noun ''friend''. To make it complex (জটিল), we expand it into an adjective clause. ''I have a friend who lives in America'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct compound form of ''Besides being intelligent, he is hardworking.''?',
              ARRAY['He is intelligent and hardworking.', 'He is not only intelligent but also hardworking.', 'He is intelligent or hardworking.', 'He is intelligent, so he is hardworking.'],
              1,
              'The prepositional phrase ''Besides being intelligent'' indicates addition. In a compound sentence (যৌগিক বাক্য), this is best expressed by the correlative conjunction ''not only...but also''. So, ''He is not only intelligent but also hardworking'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very pleasant weather.''',
              ARRAY['What a pleasant weather it is!', 'How pleasant weather it is!', 'How pleasant the weather is!', 'What pleasant weather it is!'],
              2,
              '''Weather'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য বিশেষ্য), so we do not use ''a'' before it. For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with an adjective, we use ''How'' before the adjective. The structure is ''How + adjective + subject + verb!'' So, ''How pleasant the weather is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''We must endure what we cannot cure.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['What cannot be cured must be endured.', 'What we cannot cure must be endured.', 'What cannot be cured must be endured by us.', 'What we cannot cure must be endured by us.'],
              0,
              'This is a complex sentence. In the passive transformation (কর্মবাচ্য), the object of ''cure'' in the subordinate clause becomes the subject of that clause, and the object of ''endure'' becomes the subject of the main clause. The most elegant and common passive form is ''What cannot be cured must be endured''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He has not a little influence.''',
              ARRAY['He has a little influence.', 'He has much influence.', 'He has little influence.', 'He has no influence.'],
              1,
              '''Not a little'' (কম নয়) is an idiom that means ''much'' (প্রচুর). Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form of the sentence is ''He has much influence''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He is always late.''?',
              ARRAY['He is not always late.', 'He is never late.', 'He is sometimes late.', 'He is always not late.'],
              1,
              '''Always'' (সবসময়) is the opposite of ''never'' (কখনও না). Therefore, the negative (নেতিবাচক) transformation of ''He is always late'' is ''He is never late''. This changes the meaning to the opposite, which is the purpose of direct negation.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''None can do this.''',
              ARRAY['Can any do this?', 'Can none do this?', 'Who can do this?', 'Both A and C'],
              3,
              'A negative statement can be turned into a question in two ways. One is by using ''any'': ''Can any do this?'' The other is by using a ''who'' question implying a negative answer: ''Who can do this?'' (meaning none can). Both are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''He is too honest to take a bribe.''',
              ARRAY['He is so honest that he cannot take a bribe.', 'He is very honest to take a bribe.', 'He is honest and cannot take a bribe.', 'He is honest so he cannot take a bribe.'],
              0,
              'The simple sentence with ''too...to'' (অত্যন্ত...যে না) can be transformed into a complex sentence (জটিল বাক্য) using ''so...that...cannot/could not''. ''He is so honest that he cannot take a bribe'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''The police arrested the thief.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The thief was arrested by the police.', 'The thief is arrested by the police.', 'The thief had been arrested by the police.', 'The thief was being arrested by the police.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল). The passive form is ''was/were + past participle''. So, ''The thief was arrested by the police'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''It is a very interesting book.''',
              ARRAY['What an interesting book it is!', 'How interesting book it is!', 'What interesting book it is!', 'How a interesting book it is!'],
              0,
              'For a singular countable noun (''book''), the correct exclamatory (আবেগসূচক) structure is ''What a/an + adjective + noun + subject + verb!'' Since ''interesting'' starts with a vowel sound, we use ''an''. So, ''What an interesting book it is!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct imperative form of ''You should not be lazy.''?',
              ARRAY['Do not be lazy.', 'Not be lazy.', 'You do not be lazy.', 'Be not lazy.'],
              0,
              'This is a piece of advice in the negative. A negative imperative sentence (নেতিবাচক অনুজ্ঞাসূচক বাক্য) with the verb ''be'' is formed with ''Do not be'' followed by the complement. So, ''Do not be lazy'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an affirmative sentence: ''He is not a dishonest person.''',
              ARRAY['He is a dishonest person.', 'He is an honest person.', 'He is not an honest person.', 'He is truthful.'],
              1,
              '''Dishonest'' (অসৎ) is the opposite of ''honest'' (সৎ). ''Not dishonest'' (অসৎ নয়) means he is honest. Therefore, the affirmative (হ্যাঁ-সূচক) form is ''He is an honest person''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They had completed the project before the deadline.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['The project had been completed before the deadline by them.', 'The project was completed before the deadline by them.', 'The project has been completed before the deadline.', 'The project had completed before the deadline.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the past perfect tense (অতীত পূর্ণ কাল): ''had completed''. The passive structure is ''had been + past participle''. So, ''The project had been completed before the deadline by them'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an interrogative sentence: ''None will help you.''',
              ARRAY['Will any help you?', 'Will none help you?', 'Who will help you?', 'Both A and C'],
              3,
              'A negative statement can be turned into a question in two ways. One is by using ''any'': ''Will any help you?'' The other is by using a ''who'' question implying a negative answer: ''Who will help you?'' (meaning none will). Both are correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into a complex sentence: ''I saw a beautiful girl.''',
              ARRAY['I saw a girl and she was beautiful.', 'I saw a girl who was beautiful.', 'I saw a girl that beautiful.', 'I saw a girl was beautiful.'],
              1,
              'The simple sentence has an adjective (''beautiful'') modifying the noun ''girl''. To make it complex (জটিল), we expand the adjective into an adjective clause. ''I saw a girl who was beautiful'' is the correct complex form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Which one is the correct negative form of ''He is always present.''?',
              ARRAY['He is not always present.', 'He is never present.', 'He is sometimes present.', 'He is always not present.'],
              1,
              '''Always'' (সবসময়) is the opposite of ''never'' (কখনও না). Therefore, the negative (নেতিবাচক) transformation of ''He is always present'' is ''He is never present''. This changes the meaning to the opposite.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'Transform into an exclamatory sentence: ''The sky is very clear today.''',
              ARRAY['What a clear sky today is!', 'How clear sky today is!', 'How clear the sky is today!', 'What clear sky it is!'],
              2,
              'For exclamatory sentences (আবেগসূচক বাক্য) with an adjective, we use ''How'' before the adjective. The structure is ''How + adjective + subject + verb!'' Here, ''sky'' is the subject, so ''How clear the sky is today!'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Changing Sentence',
              'The correct passive form of ''They took him to the hospital.'' is ---',
              ARRAY['He was taken to the hospital by them.', 'He is taken to the hospital by them.', 'He had been taken to the hospital by them.', 'He was being taken to the hospital.'],
              0,
              'The active sentence is in the simple past tense (অতীত কাল). The passive form is ''was/were + past participle''. So, ''He was taken to the hospital by them'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Rimi ______ a very beautiful girl.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'am', 'were'],
              1,
              'The subject ''Rimi'' is a third-person singular number. So, the singular number ''is'' is the correct form of verb. (একবচন হওয়ায় ''is'' সঠিক)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I ______ him yesterday.',
              ARRAY['see', 'have seen', 'saw', 'shall see'],
              2,
              '''Yesterday'' is an indication of past indefinite tense. So, the verb will be in past form. (''Yesterday'' অতীত নির্দেশক হওয়ায় ''saw'' হবে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'They ______ to Dhaka last week.',
              ARRAY['go', 'gone', 'went', 'goes'],
              2,
              '''Last week'' indicates a definite past action. Therefore, the past form of verb ''went'' is correct. (Last week নির্দিষ্ট অতীত হওয়ায় ''went'' হবে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He usually ______ tea in the morning.',
              ARRAY['drink', 'drinks', 'is drinking', 'drank'],
              1,
              'The adverb ''usually'' indicates a habitual action in the present. For a third-person singular subject, ''s/es'' is added. (''Usually'' বর্তমান অভ্যাস বোঝায়, তাই ''drinks'')'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It ______ since morning.',
              ARRAY['is raining', 'rains', 'has been raining', 'was raining'],
              2,
              '''Since'' with a point of time indicates an action that started in the past and is still continuing. Thus, present perfect continuous tense is needed. (''Since'' দিয়ে শুরু হওয়া কাজ এখনও চলছে, তাই ''has been raining'')'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'If I ______ a king, I would help the poor.',
              ARRAY['am', 'was', 'were', 'is'],
              2,
              'In an ''if clause'' expressing an impossible/unreal condition (subjunctive mood), ''were'' is used for all subjects. (অবাস্তব শর্তে ''were'' বসে, যেমন— If I were...)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He told me that he ______ come the next day.',
              ARRAY['will', 'shall', 'would', 'can'],
              2,
              'In indirect speech, when the reporting verb is in the past tense, the future tense ''will'' changes to ''would''. (Reported speech-এ past tense-এর পর ''will'' পরিবর্তে ''would'' বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It is high time we ______ the work.',
              ARRAY['start', 'started', 'have started', 'shall start'],
              1,
              'After ''It is high time'' or ''It is time'', the past indefinite tense is used to indicate the present necessity. (''It is high time'' -এর পরে past tense বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The boy ______ to school at this moment.',
              ARRAY['go', 'goes', 'is going', 'was going'],
              2,
              '''At this moment'' indicates an action happening right now. So, present continuous tense is used. (''At this moment'' এখন চলছে বোঝায়, তাই ''is going'')'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Ten miles ______ a long way.',
              ARRAY['are', 'were', 'is', 'have'],
              2,
              'Expressions of time, distance, and money (as a unit) take a singular verb. (সময়, দূরত্ব, অর্থ একক হিসেবে singular verb হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'She ______ to college every day.',
              ARRAY['walk', 'walks', 'is walking', 'has walked'],
              1,
              '''Every day'' indicates a habitual action. So, present indefinite tense is used. (''Every day'' অভ্যাস বোঝায়, তাই ''walks'')'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The earth ______ round the sun.',
              ARRAY['move', 'moves', 'moved', 'is moving'],
              1,
              'Universal truth (চিরন্তন সত্য) is expressed in present indefinite tense, even if the subject is singular.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I ______ the letter before he arrived.',
              ARRAY['posted', 'have posted', 'had posted', 'was posting'],
              2,
              'When one past action is completed before another past action, the earlier action takes past perfect tense. (দুটি অতীত কাজের আগেরটি Past perfect-এ হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He behaves as if he ______ a mad.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'was', 'were'],
              3,
              'After ''as if/as though'', we use a past tense (subjunctive) to show an unreal comparison. ''Were'' is used for all persons. (অবাস্তব তুলনায় ''as if'' -এর পরে past tense বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I wish I ______ a bird.',
              ARRAY['am', 'was', 'were', 'have been'],
              2,
              'After ''wish'', we use a past form (subjunctive) to express a desire about an unreal situation. ''Were'' is used for all subjects. (অবাস্তব ইচ্ছা প্রকাশে ''wish'' -এর পরে ''were'' বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'We ______ not play cricket yesterday.',
              ARRAY['do', 'did', 'have', 'are'],
              1,
              '''Yesterday'' indicates past tense. The negative sentence in past indefinite requires the auxiliary ''did'' + not + main verb. (''Yesterday'' অতীত হওয়ায় ''did not'' হবে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Please ______ the dog.',
              ARRAY['not to feed', 'do not feed', 'does not feed', 'not feed'],
              1,
              'This is an imperative sentence (আদেশ/অনুরোধ). The negative form is ''do not + verb''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is used to ______ up early.',
              ARRAY['get', 'gets', 'getting', 'got'],
              2,
              'After ''used to'' (অভ্যস্ত), the preposition ''to'' is followed by a gerund (verb + ing). (''used to'' -এর পরে gerund বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The train ______ before we reached the station.',
              ARRAY['left', 'has left', 'had left', 'was leaving'],
              2,
              'The train left first, then we reached. The earlier action is in past perfect tense. (আগের কাজটি Past perfect-এ হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Either he or I ______ mistaken.',
              ARRAY['am', 'is', 'are', 'were'],
              0,
              'With ''either-or/neither-nor'', the verb agrees with the subject closest to it. Here, ''I'' is closest, so ''am'' is used. (সন্নিহিত subject-এর সঙ্গে verb-এর agreement হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ for a walk every morning.',
              ARRAY['go', 'goes', 'going', 'went'],
              1,
              '''Every morning'' indicates a habitual present action. Third-person singular subject takes ''goes''. (অভ্যাস বোঝায়, তাই ''goes'')'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'They ______ playing football now.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'are', 'was'],
              2,
              '''Now'' indicates present continuous. The plural subject ''They'' takes ''are''. (এখন চলছে, তাই ''are'')'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I have finished my homework, so I ______ watch TV now.',
              ARRAY['may', 'can', 'am', 'was'],
              1,
              '''Can'' is used to express ability or permission (ক্ষমতা/অনুমতি). Here, it indicates permission.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The committee ______ divided in their opinion.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'has', 'have'],
              1,
              'Collective nouns (সমষ্টিবাচক বিশেষ্য) like ''committee'' take a plural verb when the members are acting individually. Here, ''their'' indicates individuality.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He would rather die than ______.',
              ARRAY['to beg', 'beg', 'begs', 'begging'],
              1,
              'After ''would rather/ better/ sooner'', the base form of the verb is used. (''would rather'' -এর পরে verb-এর base form হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It is I who ______ your friend.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'are', 'were'],
              1,
              'In a relative clause, the verb agrees with the antecedent of the relative pronoun. Here, the antecedent is ''I''. (Antecedent ''I'' হওয়ায় ''am'' বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He talked as if he ______ everything.',
              ARRAY['knows', 'knew', 'has known', 'is knowing'],
              1,
              'After ''as if'' expressing an unreal situation, the past tense is used. (''as if'' -এর পরে অবাস্তব অর্থে past tense হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The number of students ______ increasing.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'were', 'have'],
              0,
              '''The number of'' is followed by a plural noun but takes a singular verb. (''The number of'' -এর পরে singular verb হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'A number of students ______ present.',
              ARRAY['is', 'was', 'are', 'has'],
              2,
              '''A number of'' means ''many'' and takes a plural verb. (''A number of'' অর্থ ''অনেক'' এবং plural verb হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'We ______ each other for the last ten years.',
              ARRAY['know', 'knew', 'have known', 'are knowing'],
              2,
              '''For the last ten years'' indicates a period continuing up to the present. So, present perfect tense is used. (বর্তমান পর্যন্ত চলে আসছে, তাই ''have known'')'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The boy ______ to read the book since Monday.',
              ARRAY['tried', 'has been trying', 'is trying', 'was trying'],
              1,
              '''Since Monday'' indicates a continuous action from the past until now. Present perfect continuous is appropriate. (''Since Monday'' দিয়ে বর্তমান পর্যন্ত চলমান কাজ বোঝায়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He refrained ______ any further questions.',
              ARRAY['to ask', 'asking', 'from asking', 'ask'],
              2,
              '''Refrain'' is always followed by the preposition ''from'' and then a gerund. (''Refrain'' -এর পরে ''from + ing'' হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Fortune ______ the brave.',
              ARRAY['favour', 'favours', 'favoured', 'is favouring'],
              1,
              'This is a proverb (প্রবাদ) expressing a general truth. So, present indefinite tense is used with a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'They ______ the poor.',
              ARRAY['always help', 'are always helping', 'have always helped', 'were always helping'],
              0,
              '''Always'' with a habitual action is best expressed in the present indefinite tense. (অভ্যাসগত কাজ বোঝাতে present indefinite শ্রেষ্ঠ)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He came after I ______ the work.',
              ARRAY['finished', 'have finished', 'had finished', 'was finishing'],
              2,
              'I finished the work first, then he came. The earlier completed action is in past perfect. (আগের শেষ করা কাজটি past perfect-এ হবে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I don''t know why he ______ to me.',
              ARRAY['lie', 'lies', 'is lying', 'has lied'],
              2,
              'The context suggests a current action. ''Why he is lying to me'' means he is doing it right now (now). (বর্তমান চলমান কাজ বুঝাতে ''is lying'')'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He insisted ______ there.',
              ARRAY['to go', 'on going', 'go', 'went'],
              1,
              '''Insist'' is followed by the preposition ''on'' and then a gerund. (''Insist'' -এর পরে ''on + ing'' হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The man and the woman ______ honest.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'are', 'was'],
              2,
              'Two singular subjects joined by ''and'' form a plural subject and take a plural verb. (''and'' দ্বারা যুক্ত হলে plural verb হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Bread and butter ______ his favourite food.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'were', 'have'],
              0,
              'When two nouns joined by ''and'' express a single idea or unit, they take a singular verb. (''and'' একক idea বোঝালে singular verb হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I ______ him for a long time.',
              ARRAY['know', 'knew', 'have known', 'am knowing'],
              2,
              '''For a long time'' indicates a period up to now. Present perfect is used. (''For a long time'' দীর্ঘ সময় বর্তমান পর্যন্ত বোঝায়, তাই ''have known'')'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He entered the room ______ the TV on.',
              ARRAY['to turn', 'turning', 'turned', 'was turning'],
              1,
              'A present participle (verb+ing) can be used to describe an action that happens at the same time as the main verb. (বর্তমান কৃদন্ত দ্বারা একসঙ্গে ঘটে এমন কাজ বোঝায়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He will come tomorrow, ______ ?',
              ARRAY['will he', 'won''t he', 'does he', 'didn''t he'],
              1,
              'The sentence is affirmative, so the question tag (ট্যাগ প্রশ্ন) must be negative. The auxiliary verb ''will'' is used. (Affirmative sentence-এর tag negative হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is looking forward to ______ you.',
              ARRAY['meet', 'meeting', 'met', 'have met'],
              1,
              '''Look forward to'' is a phrase where ''to'' is a preposition, so it must be followed by a gerund. (''to'' preposition হওয়ায় gerund বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'She has been ill ______ last Friday.',
              ARRAY['since', 'for', 'from', 'ago'],
              0,
              '''Last Friday'' is a specific point in time. ''Since'' is used with a point of time. (নির্দিষ্ট সময়ের শুরু বোঝাতে ''since'' বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He has been working here ______ 2010.',
              ARRAY['for', 'since', 'from', 'ago'],
              1,
              '2010 is a specific point in time, so ''since'' is the correct preposition. (''since'' নির্দিষ্ট সময়ের শুরু বোঝায়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'You had better ______ the doctor.',
              ARRAY['consult', 'to consult', 'consulting', 'consulted'],
              0,
              'After ''had better'', the base form of the verb (infinitive without ''to'') is used. (''had better'' -এর পরে verb-এর base form হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Let me ______ the work.',
              ARRAY['do', 'to do', 'doing', 'did'],
              0,
              'Causative verbs like ''let, make, bid, help'' are followed by an object and then a bare infinitive (verb without ''to''). (Causative verb-এর পরে object + base form হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He refrained ______ any further questions.',
              ARRAY['to ask', 'asking', 'from asking', 'ask'],
              2,
              'The verb ''refrain'' is always followed by the preposition ''from'' and then a gerund (verb+ing). (''Refrain'' -এর পরে ''from + ing'' বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is ______ in Dhaka for ten years.',
              ARRAY['live', 'lives', 'living', 'lived'],
              2,
              'The structure ''has been/have been'' is followed by a present participle (verb+ing) to form the perfect continuous tense. (''has been'' -এর পরে ''living'' বসে)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It is many years since I ______ him last.',
              ARRAY['see', 'saw', 'have seen', 'had seen'],
              1,
              'In a ''since clause'' referring to a point in the past, the verb is usually in the past indefinite tense. (''since'' -এর clause-এ সাধারণত past indefinite হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The poet and philosopher ______ dead.',
              ARRAY['are', 'have', 'is', 'were'],
              2,
              'When two nouns joined by ''and'' refer to the same person (একই ব্যক্তি), the verb is singular. Here, one person is both poet and philosopher.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ smoke forty cigarettes a day.',
              ARRAY['use to', 'used to', 'is used to', 'was used to'],
              1,
              '''Used to'' (অতীত অভ্যাস) expresses a past habit or state that no longer exists. It is followed by the base form of the verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'They ______ in this town since 1995.',
              ARRAY['lived', 'are living', 'have been living', 'were living'],
              2,
              '''Since 1995'' indicates an action that started in the past and is still continuing. Present perfect continuous tense (চলমান বর্তমান) is appropriate.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I wish I ______ younger.',
              ARRAY['am', 'was', 'were', 'have been'],
              2,
              'After ''wish'', we use a past form (subjunctive) to express an unreal desire. ''Were'' is used for all subjects (অবাস্তব ইচ্ছা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He behaved as though he ______ a king.',
              ARRAY['is', 'was', 'were', 'has been'],
              2,
              'After ''as though/as if'', we use ''were'' for all persons to show an unreal situation (অবাস্তব অবস্থা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I had my car ______ yesterday.',
              ARRAY['wash', 'washed', 'washing', 'to wash'],
              1,
              'In causative structure, ''have + object + past participle'' means to get something done by someone else (কাজ করানো).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Let him ______ whatever he likes.',
              ARRAY['do', 'to do', 'doing', 'does'],
              0,
              'After ''let'', we use the base form of the verb (bare infinitive) without ''to'' (Let-এর পরে verb-এর base form).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I saw him ______ the house.',
              ARRAY['enter', 'entered', 'to enter', 'has entered'],
              0,
              'After verbs of perception (see, hear, watch, feel), we use base form (bare infinitive) or gerund (দ্রষ্টব্য কাজ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He refrained ______ any further questions.',
              ARRAY['to ask', 'asking', 'from asking', 'ask'],
              2,
              '''Refrain'' is always followed by the preposition ''from'' and then a gerund (বিরত থাকা অর্থে from + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The Principal, with all the teachers, ______ present.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'were', 'have'],
              0,
              'When subjects are joined by ''with/together with/as well as'', the verb agrees with the first subject (প্রথম subject অনুযায়ী verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He talks as if he ______ everything.',
              ARRAY['knows', 'knew', 'has known', 'is knowing'],
              1,
              'After ''as if'' expressing an unreal comparison, past tense (অতীতকাল) is used. Here ''knew'' is the past form.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is looking for a servant ______.',
              ARRAY['to cook', 'cook', 'cooking', 'cooked'],
              0,
              'Infinitive of purpose (উদ্দেশ্য অর্থে) is used with ''to + verb'' to show the purpose of an action.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It is high time you ______ home.',
              ARRAY['go', 'went', 'have gone', 'will go'],
              1,
              'After ''It is high time'', we use past tense (অতীতকাল) to express something that should be done now.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The boy ______ in the river now.',
              ARRAY['swim', 'swims', 'is swimming', 'are swimming'],
              2,
              '''Now'' indicates present continuous tense. Singular subject ''boy'' takes ''is'' (বর্তমান চলমান কাজ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Two thirds of the work ______ finished.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'were', 'have'],
              0,
              'With fractions/percentages, the verb agrees with the noun after ''of''. Here ''work'' is uncountable, so singular verb (গণনাযোগ্যতা অনুযায়ী verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Each of the boys ______ rewarded.',
              ARRAY['were', 'have', 'was', 'are'],
              2,
              'After ''each/every/one of'', the verb is always singular (প্রত্যেক অর্থে singular verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ here for twenty years.',
              ARRAY['worked', 'has been working', 'is working', 'was working'],
              1,
              '''For twenty years'' indicates a duration up to now. Present perfect continuous (চলমান বর্তমান) emphasizes continuity.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'If I had known, I ______ helped him.',
              ARRAY['would have', 'will have', 'have', 'had'],
              0,
              'In third conditional (অবাস্তব অতীত), the structure is: If + past perfect, would have + past participle.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'She ______ to me every week.',
              ARRAY['write', 'writes', 'is writing', 'has written'],
              1,
              '''Every week'' indicates a habitual action (অভ্যাসগত কাজ). Present indefinite tense is used.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The police ______ the thief arrested.',
              ARRAY['has', 'have', 'is', 'was'],
              1,
              '''Police'' is a collective noun that is always plural in English and takes a plural verb (সর্বদা plural)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He died ______ overeating.',
              ARRAY['from', 'of', 'for', 'by'],
              1,
              '''Die of'' is used for disease, hunger, old age, etc. (রোগ/ক্ষুধায় মরা). ''Die from'' is for external causes.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I don''t mind ______ late.',
              ARRAY['to work', 'work', 'working', 'worked'],
              2,
              'After ''mind'', we use a gerund (verb + ing) as the object (Mind-এর পরে gerund হয়)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ a bath before breakfast.',
              ARRAY['take', 'takes', 'is taking', 'has taken'],
              1,
              'This is a habitual action (অভ্যাসগত কাজ). Present indefinite tense is used for daily routines.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He prevented me ______ there.',
              ARRAY['to go', 'go', 'from going', 'went'],
              2,
              '''Prevent'' is followed by ''from + gerund'' (বাধা দেওয়া অর্থে from + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It ______ raining since morning.',
              ARRAY['is', 'was', 'has been', 'had been'],
              2,
              '''Since morning'' indicates an action continuing from past to present. Present perfect continuous (চলমান বর্তমান) is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The rich ______ not always happy.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'are', 'were'],
              2,
              'When ''The + adjective'' represents a class of people (সম্প্রদায়), it takes a plural verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'We look forward to ______ from you.',
              ARRAY['hear', 'hearing', 'heard', 'have heard'],
              1,
              '''Look forward to'' is a phrase where ''to'' is a preposition, so it takes a gerund (ing যুক্ত verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He was seen ______ the house.',
              ARRAY['enter', 'to enter', 'entered', 'enters'],
              1,
              'In passive voice, after verbs of perception (see, hear), we use ''to + verb'' (Passive-এ to + verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The news ______ true.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'were', 'have'],
              0,
              '''News'' looks plural but is singular in English (একবচন) and takes a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He spends his time ______ novels.',
              ARRAY['read', 'to read', 'reading', 'reads'],
              2,
              'After ''spend time'', we use a gerund (সময় কাটানো অর্থে gerund)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'If I were you, I ______ accept the offer.',
              ARRAY['will', 'would', 'shall', 'can'],
              1,
              'In unreal conditional sentences (অবাস্তব শর্ত), ''would'' is used in the main clause.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He advised me ______ hard.',
              ARRAY['work', 'to work', 'working', 'worked'],
              1,
              'After ''advise'', we use ''object + to + verb'' (পরামর্শ দেওয়া অর্থে to + verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The cattle ______ grazing in the field.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'are', 'was'],
              2,
              '''Cattle'' is a plural noun (বহুবচন) and always takes a plural verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He has given up ______.',
              ARRAY['smoke', 'to smoke', 'smoking', 'smoked'],
              2,
              'After ''give up'', we use a gerund (পরিত্যাগ করা অর্থে gerund)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I would rather die than ______.',
              ARRAY['to beg', 'beg', 'begging', 'begs'],
              1,
              'After ''would rather...than'', we use the base form of the verb (বেস ফর্ম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He insisted on ______ there.',
              ARRAY['go', 'to go', 'going', 'went'],
              2,
              'After ''insist on'', we use a gerund (জোর দেওয়া অর্থে on + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The scenery of this place ______ charming.',
              ARRAY['are', 'were', 'is', 'have'],
              2,
              '''Scenery'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য) and takes a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He came home after the sun ______.',
              ARRAY['rise', 'rose', 'had risen', 'rises'],
              2,
              'The sun rose first, then he came. Earlier past action takes past perfect (আগের কাজ past perfect)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'They ______ the work by next week.',
              ARRAY['will finish', 'will have finished', 'finish', 'finished'],
              1,
              '''By next week'' indicates future perfect tense (ভবিষ্যতে সম্পন্ন কাজ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is fond of ______ poetry.',
              ARRAY['recite', 'reciting', 'recites', 'to recite'],
              1,
              'After prepositions (of, in, at, etc.), we use a gerund (ing যুক্ত verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Mathematics ______ my favorite subject.',
              ARRAY['are', 'were', 'is', 'have'],
              2,
              'Subjects ending in ''ics'' (Mathematics, Physics) are singular (একবচন) in English.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He came here ______ me.',
              ARRAY['see', 'to see', 'seeing', 'saw'],
              1,
              'Infinitive of purpose (উদ্দেশ্য) uses ''to + verb''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ in the river for two hours.',
              ARRAY['swam', 'has been swimming', 'is swimming', 'was swimming'],
              1,
              '''For two hours'' suggests duration up to now. Present perfect continuous (সময়সীমাসহ চলমান কাজ) is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He was angry and ______ the room.',
              ARRAY['leave', 'left', 'leaves', 'has left'],
              1,
              'Two past actions joined by ''and'' should be in the same tense (একই tense). ''Was'' is past, so ''left'' is past.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'She said that she ______ help me.',
              ARRAY['will', 'would', 'shall', 'can'],
              1,
              'In indirect speech, if the reporting verb is past (said), ''will'' changes to ''would'' (Narration-এর নিয়ম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He would not go, ______ he?',
              ARRAY['would', 'wouldn''t', 'will', 'did'],
              0,
              'The sentence is negative (would not), so the question tag (ট্যাগ) must be positive ''would''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'We shall wait here until he ______ back.',
              ARRAY['come', 'comes', 'came', 'will come'],
              1,
              'In time clauses with ''until/when/as soon as'', present tense is used for future meaning (ভবিষ্যৎ অর্থে বর্তমান)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is too weak ______.',
              ARRAY['walk', 'walking', 'to walk', 'walked'],
              2,
              '''Too + adjective + to + verb'' structure means ''অত্যধিক...যে...না''।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Neither Rina nor Rima ______ present.',
              ARRAY['are', 'were', 'is', 'have'],
              2,
              'With ''neither...nor'', the verb agrees with the nearest subject (সন্নিহিত subject). ''Rima'' is singular, so ''is''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'By the next year, he ______ his degree.',
              ARRAY['will complete', 'completes', 'will have completed', 'completed'],
              2,
              '''By the next year'' indicates future perfect tense (ভবিষ্যতে একটি নির্দিষ্ট সময়ের মধ্যে সম্পন্ন কাজ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The committee ______ issued its report.',
              ARRAY['have', 'has', 'are', 'were'],
              1,
              'When a collective noun (সমষ্টিবাচক বিশেষ্য) like ''committee'' acts as a single unit, it takes a singular verb. Here, ''its'' indicates unity.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He refrained ______ any further comments.',
              ARRAY['to make', 'making', 'from making', 'make'],
              2,
              'The verb ''refrain'' is always followed by the preposition ''from'' and then a gerund (বিরত থাকা অর্থে from + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It is I who ______ to blame.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'are', 'were'],
              1,
              'In a relative clause, the verb agrees with the antecedent (পূর্ববর্তী পদ) of ''who''. The antecedent is ''I'', so ''am'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The boy along with his friends ______ coming.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              'When subjects are joined by ''along with/together with'', the verb agrees with the first subject (প্রথম subject অনুযায়ী verb)। Here, ''boy'' is singular.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He talks as if he ______ a fool.',
              ARRAY['is', 'was', 'were', 'has been'],
              2,
              'After ''as if/as though'' expressing an unreal situation (অবাস্তব অবস্থা), ''were'' is used for all persons.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I don''t know why he ______ to me now.',
              ARRAY['lie', 'lies', 'is lying', 'has lied'],
              2,
              '''Now'' indicates present continuous tense. The action is happening at the moment of speaking (এখন ঘটছে)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The man and the woman ______ honest.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'are', 'was'],
              2,
              'Two singular subjects joined by ''and'' form a plural subject and take a plural verb (দুটি একবচন = বহুবচন)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Bread and butter ______ what he wants.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'were', 'have'],
              0,
              'When two nouns joined by ''and'' express a single idea or unit (একটি ধারণা), they take a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The novel, including all its sequels, ______ interesting.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              'Phrases like ''including, together with, as well as'' do not affect the number of the subject. The main subject ''novel'' is singular.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He insisted on ______ to the doctor.',
              ARRAY['go', 'going', 'to go', 'went'],
              1,
              'After ''insist on'', we use a gerund (verb + ing) because ''on'' is a preposition (জোর দেওয়া অর্থে on + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'She has been working here ______ 2010.',
              ARRAY['since', 'for', 'from', 'ago'],
              0,
              '''Since'' is used with a specific point in time (2010) to indicate the starting point of an action (নির্দিষ্ট সময়ের শুরু)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I saw him ______ the street.',
              ARRAY['cross', 'crossed', 'to cross', 'was crossing'],
              0,
              'After verbs of perception (see, hear, watch), we use the base form (bare infinitive) to describe a complete action (সম্পূর্ণ কাজ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He died ______ cholera.',
              ARRAY['from', 'of', 'by', 'with'],
              1,
              '''Die of'' is used for diseases (রোগে মরা). ''Die from'' is used for external causes like injury.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The news ______ at noon every day.',
              ARRAY['broadcast', 'is broadcast', 'are broadcast', 'were broadcast'],
              1,
              'The news is broadcast (by someone). This is passive voice (কর্মবাচ্য). ''News'' is singular, so ''is'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ smoke, but now he has given it up.',
              ARRAY['used to', 'is used to', 'was used to', 'use to'],
              0,
              '''Used to'' (অতীত অভ্যাস) expresses a past habit that no longer continues in the present.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Each of the students ______ done their homework.',
              ARRAY['have', 'has', 'are', 'were'],
              1,
              'After ''each of'', the verb is always singular (has) even though it sounds plural. (Each of + plural noun + singular verb)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The poor ______ looked down upon by the rich.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'was', 'has'],
              1,
              'When ''The + adjective'' represents a class of people (দরিদ্র শ্রেণী), it takes a plural verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He said that he ______ go to Dhaka the next day.',
              ARRAY['will', 'would', 'shall', 'can'],
              1,
              'In indirect speech, when the reporting verb (said) is past, ''will'' changes to ''would'' (Narration-এর নিয়ম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I wish I ______ a millionaire.',
              ARRAY['am', 'was', 'were', 'have been'],
              2,
              'After ''wish'', we use the subjunctive mood (were) to express an unreal or impossible desire (অবাস্তব ইচ্ছা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It''s time you ______ to bed.',
              ARRAY['go', 'went', 'have gone', 'will go'],
              1,
              'After ''It''s time / It''s high time'', we use past tense to indicate something that should be done now (এখনই করা উচিত)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The cattle ______ grazing in the field.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'are', 'was'],
              2,
              '''Cattle'' is a plural noun (গবাদি পশু বহুবচনে) and always takes a plural verb in English.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He prevented me ______ entering the room.',
              ARRAY['from', 'to', 'for', 'in'],
              0,
              'The correct structure is ''prevent someone from doing something'' (কাউকে কিছু করতে বাধা দেওয়া)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'She ______ in music since childhood.',
              ARRAY['interested', 'is interested', 'was interested', 'has been interested'],
              3,
              '''Since childhood'' indicates a state that started in the past and continues to the present. Present perfect tense is used.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The Principal, with his staff, ______ present.',
              ARRAY['are', 'were', 'is', 'have'],
              2,
              'When ''with'' joins two subjects, the verb agrees with the first subject (প্রথম subject অনুযায়ী verb)। Here, ''Principal'' is singular.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I don''t mind ______ the dish.',
              ARRAY['cook', 'to cook', 'cooking', 'cooked'],
              2,
              'After ''mind'', we always use a gerund (verb + ing) (আপত্তি থাকা অর্থে mind + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He would rather starve than ______.',
              ARRAY['to steal', 'steal', 'stealing', 'stole'],
              1,
              'After ''would rather...than'', we use the base form of the verb (বেস ফর্ম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The teacher advised us ______ hard.',
              ARRAY['read', 'reading', 'to read', 'reads'],
              2,
              'After ''advise'', we use ''object + to + verb'' (কাউকে কিছু করতে পরামর্শ দেওয়া)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'No one ______ what happened to him.',
              ARRAY['know', 'knows', 'are knowing', 'have known'],
              1,
              '''No one'' is an indefinite pronoun (অনির্দিষ্ট সর্বনাম) that is always singular and takes a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He confessed that he ______ guilty.',
              ARRAY['is', 'has been', 'was', 'were'],
              2,
              'In indirect speech, when the reporting verb (confessed) is past, the verb in the subordinate clause usually becomes past (Narration-এর নিয়ম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The work ______ by next month.',
              ARRAY['will be completed', 'will complete', 'completes', 'completed'],
              0,
              '''By next month'' indicates future time, and the work will be done by someone (passive voice). Future passive structure: will be + past participle.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I had my watch ______ yesterday.',
              ARRAY['repair', 'repaired', 'repairing', 'to repair'],
              1,
              'In causative structure (কাজ করানো), ''have + object + past participle'' means to get something done by someone else.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is not used to ______ up early.',
              ARRAY['get', 'gets', 'getting', 'got'],
              2,
              '''Used to'' (অভ্যস্ত) is followed by a gerund when it means ''accustomed to''. Here ''to'' is a preposition.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Fortune ______ the brave.',
              ARRAY['favour', 'favours', 'favoured', 'is favouring'],
              1,
              'This is a proverb (প্রবাদ) expressing a general truth. Present indefinite tense is used.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I ______ him for a long time.',
              ARRAY['know', 'knew', 'have known', 'am knowing'],
              2,
              '''For a long time'' indicates a period continuing up to the present. Present perfect tense (বর্তমান পর্যন্ত) is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He jumped ______ the river.',
              ARRAY['in', 'into', 'to', 'onto'],
              1,
              '''Into'' (এর ভিতরে) is used with verbs of motion to show entry from outside to inside.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'They ______ playing since 4 pm.',
              ARRAY['are', 'were', 'have been', 'had been'],
              2,
              '''Since 4 pm'' indicates a continuous action from past to present. Present perfect continuous is used.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The police ______ caught the thief.',
              ARRAY['has', 'have', 'is', 'was'],
              1,
              '''Police'' is a collective noun that is always plural in English and takes a plural verb (পুলিশ সর্বদা বহুবচন)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is looking for a job ______.',
              ARRAY['at present', 'every day', 'last week', 'tomorrow'],
              0,
              '''At present'' (বর্তমানে) indicates present continuous tense, which matches the structure ''is looking''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The girl ______ the piano well.',
              ARRAY['play', 'plays', 'are playing', 'have played'],
              1,
              'This sentence describes a skill or ability (দক্ষতা), which is best expressed in present indefinite tense. ''Girl'' is singular.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'If he comes, I ______ him.',
              ARRAY['meet', 'will meet', 'would meet', 'met'],
              1,
              'In first conditional (শর্তসাপেক্ষ বর্তমান), the structure is: If + present, subject + will + verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He was seen ______ the bank.',
              ARRAY['enter', 'entered', 'to enter', 'enters'],
              2,
              'In passive voice, after verbs like ''see'', we use ''to + verb'' (Passive-এ to + verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The committee ______ divided in their opinions.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'has', 'was'],
              1,
              'When a collective noun shows individual action (পৃথক মতামত), it takes a plural verb. Here, ''their'' indicates individuality.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He died ______ overeating.',
              ARRAY['from', 'of', 'for', 'with'],
              1,
              '''Die of'' is used for internal causes like hunger, disease, or overeating. ''Die from'' is for external causes.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The scenery of Cox''s Bazar ______ beautiful.',
              ARRAY['are', 'were', 'is', 'have'],
              2,
              '''Scenery'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য বিশেষ্য) and always takes a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He insisted that he ______ go.',
              ARRAY['will', 'would', 'should', 'can'],
              2,
              'After ''insist'' (জোর দেওয়া) in a clause, we often use ''should'' or the subjunctive (base form) in formal English.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Let me ______ the truth.',
              ARRAY['know', 'to know', 'knowing', 'known'],
              0,
              'After ''let'', we use the base form of the verb (bare infinitive) without ''to'' (Let-এর পরে verb-এর base form)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'She ______ here since 1990.',
              ARRAY['lived', 'has lived', 'is living', 'was living'],
              1,
              '''Since 1990'' indicates an action that started in the past and continues to the present. Present perfect tense is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He talked as though he ______ mad.',
              ARRAY['is', 'was', 'were', 'has been'],
              2,
              'After ''as though'' expressing an unreal situation (অবাস্তব অবস্থা), ''were'' is used for all persons.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'No sooner had he seen me than he ______ away.',
              ARRAY['run', 'ran', 'runs', 'has run'],
              1,
              'In ''No sooner...than'' structure, the verb after ''than'' is usually in simple past tense (অতীতকাল)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The United Nations ______ founded in 1945.',
              ARRAY['were', 'was', 'have', 'are'],
              1,
              'Names of organizations (সংস্থার নাম) like ''The United Nations'' are singular and take a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I don''t know why he ______ absent yesterday.',
              ARRAY['is', 'was', 'has been', 'were'],
              1,
              '''Yesterday'' indicates past time, so past indefinite tense ''was'' is correct (গতকাল অতীতকাল নির্দেশ করে)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He spends a lot of time ______ TV.',
              ARRAY['watch', 'to watch', 'watching', 'watches'],
              2,
              'After ''spend time'', we use a gerund (সময় কাটানো অর্থে gerund) to show the activity.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The rich ______ not always happy.',
              ARRAY['is', 'am', 'are', 'was'],
              2,
              'When ''The + adjective'' represents a group of people (শ্রেণী), it takes a plural verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He has given up ______ cigarettes.',
              ARRAY['smoke', 'to smoke', 'smoking', 'smoked'],
              2,
              'After phrasal verbs like ''give up'', we use a gerund (ছেড়ে দেওয়া অর্থে gerund)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The boy stopped ______ when he saw me.',
              ARRAY['to cry', 'crying', 'cry', 'cried'],
              1,
              '''Stop + gerund'' means to cease an action (কাজ করা বন্ধ করে দেওয়া)। ''Stop + infinitive'' means to pause for another action.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The company ______ a new product next month.',
              ARRAY['launch', 'launches', 'will launch', 'launched'],
              2,
              '''Next month'' indicates future time, so future indefinite tense ''will launch'' is correct (আগামী মাস ভবিষ্যৎ নির্দেশ করে)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is interested in ______ novels.',
              ARRAY['write', 'writing', 'writes', 'to write'],
              1,
              'After prepositions like ''in'', we use a gerund (verb + ing) (Preposition-এর পরে gerund বসে)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The jury ______ divided in their opinion.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'has', 'was'],
              1,
              'When a collective noun (যেমন jury) indicates individual members, it takes a plural verb. ''Their'' shows individuality.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'If he had tried, he ______ succeeded.',
              ARRAY['would have', 'will have', 'has', 'had'],
              0,
              'In third conditional (অতীতের অবাস্তব শর্ত), structure: If + past perfect, would have + past participle.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He told me that he ______ me the next day.',
              ARRAY['will meet', 'would meet', 'meets', 'met'],
              1,
              'In indirect speech, when reporting verb is past, ''will'' changes to ''would'' (Narration-এর নিয়ম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ a book when I entered the room.',
              ARRAY['read', 'reads', 'was reading', 'has read'],
              2,
              'When one past action was in progress and another interrupted it, past continuous tense is used (চলমান অতীত কাজ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Neither of the two boys ______ guilty.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              'After ''neither of/either of'', the verb is always singular (একবচন)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is looking forward to ______ his parents.',
              ARRAY['meet', 'meeting', 'met', 'have met'],
              1,
              '''Look forward to'' is a phrase where ''to'' is a preposition, so it takes a gerund (ing যুক্ত verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The water ______ for two hours.',
              ARRAY['is boiling', 'has been boiling', 'was boiling', 'boils'],
              1,
              '''For two hours'' indicates duration up to now. Present perfect continuous (সময়সীমাসহ চলমান কাজ) is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He was made ______ the whole night.',
              ARRAY['work', 'to work', 'working', 'worked'],
              1,
              'In passive voice, after ''made'', we use ''to + verb'' (Passive-এ to + verb)। Active: They made him work.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Many a man ______ died in the war.',
              ARRAY['have', 'has', 'are', 'were'],
              1,
              '''Many a'' is always followed by a singular noun and singular verb (Many a + singular noun + singular verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He was accused of ______ the money.',
              ARRAY['steal', 'stealing', 'stole', 'to steal'],
              1,
              'After prepositions like ''of'', we use a gerund (অভিযুক্ত অর্থে of + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The patient had died before the doctor ______.',
              ARRAY['arrive', 'arrived', 'had arrived', 'arrives'],
              1,
              'After past perfect in main clause, the ''before'' clause takes simple past (Past perfect-এর পরে before + past indefinite)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is not accustomed to ______ in public.',
              ARRAY['speak', 'speaking', 'spoke', 'speaks'],
              1,
              '''Accustomed to'' is followed by a gerund (অভ্যস্ত অর্থে to + ing) because ''to'' is a preposition here.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The furniture ______ very expensive.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              '''Furniture'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য বিশেষ্য) and takes a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He would rather die than ______ the truth.',
              ARRAY['to tell', 'tell', 'telling', 'told'],
              1,
              'After ''would rather...than'', we use the base form of the verb (বেস ফর্ম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The boy along with his mother ______ present.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              'When subjects are joined by ''along with'', the verb agrees with the first subject (প্রথম subject অনুযায়ী verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is good at ______ stories.',
              ARRAY['tell', 'telling', 'tells', 'to tell'],
              1,
              'After prepositions like ''at'', we use a gerund (দক্ষতা অর্থে at + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I will phone you when I ______ the news.',
              ARRAY['get', 'will get', 'got', 'have got'],
              0,
              'In time clauses with ''when/after/before'', present tense is used for future meaning (সময়সূচক clause-এ ভবিষ্যৎ অর্থে present)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The play ______ before we reached the hall.',
              ARRAY['started', 'had started', 'has started', 'was starting'],
              1,
              'The play started first, then we reached. Earlier past action takes past perfect (আগের কাজ past perfect)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He told a lie ______ punishment.',
              ARRAY['avoid', 'to avoid', 'avoiding', 'avoided'],
              1,
              'Infinitive of purpose (উদ্দেশ্য অর্থে) uses ''to + verb'' to explain why something was done.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Either he or I ______ to blame.',
              ARRAY['am', 'is', 'are', 'were'],
              0,
              'With ''either-or'', the verb agrees with the nearest subject (সন্নিহিত subject)। Here, ''I'' is nearest, so ''am''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He was seen ______ the road.',
              ARRAY['cross', 'crossed', 'to cross', 'crossing'],
              2,
              'In passive voice, after verbs of perception, we use ''to + verb'' (Passive-এ to + verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The police ______ searching for the thief.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'was', 'has'],
              1,
              '''Police'' is a collective noun that is always plural in English and takes a plural verb (পুলিশ সর্বদা বহুবচন)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It is high time we ______ for the exam.',
              ARRAY['prepare', 'prepared', 'have prepared', 'will prepare'],
              1,
              'After ''It is high time'', we use past tense (অতীতকাল) to indicate something that should be done now.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ here for twenty years by next March.',
              ARRAY['will work', 'will have been working', 'works', 'worked'],
              1,
              '''By next March'' with ''for twenty years'' indicates future perfect continuous tense (ভবিষ্যতে চলমান কাজের সময়কাল)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I wish I ______ accept the offer.',
              ARRAY['can', 'could', 'will', 'may'],
              1,
              'After ''wish'', we use past forms (could) to express a regret about present inability (অক্ষমতার অনুশোচনা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The book, including all the chapters, ______ interesting.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              'Phrases like ''including'' do not affect the subject. The main subject ''book'' is singular, so verb is singular.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He has been suffering from fever ______ Monday.',
              ARRAY['since', 'for', 'from', 'ago'],
              0,
              '''Monday'' is a specific point in time. ''Since'' is used with a point of time (নির্দিষ্ট সময়ের শুরু বোঝাতে)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He insisted ______ there immediately.',
              ARRAY['to go', 'on going', 'go', 'went'],
              1,
              '''Insist'' is followed by ''on + gerund'' (জোর দেওয়া অর্থে on + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The news ______ at 9 pm every day.',
              ARRAY['is broadcast', 'are broadcast', 'broadcast', 'broadcasts'],
              0,
              'The news is broadcast (by someone). This is passive voice. ''News'' is singular, so ''is'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He would not do it, ______ he?',
              ARRAY['would', 'wouldn''t', 'will', 'did'],
              0,
              'The sentence is negative (would not), so the question tag (ট্যাগ প্রশ্ন) must be positive ''would''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Two miles ______ a long distance.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              'Expressions of distance (দূরত্ব) are treated as a single unit and take a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is looking forward to ______ his uncle.',
              ARRAY['meet', 'meeting', 'met', 'have met'],
              1,
              '''Look forward to'' is a phrase where ''to'' is a preposition, so it takes a gerund (ing যুক্ত verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The cattle ______ grazing in the field.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'was', 'has'],
              1,
              '''Cattle'' is a plural noun (গবাদি পশু বহুবচনে) and always takes a plural verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He died ______ overeating.',
              ARRAY['from', 'of', 'by', 'with'],
              1,
              '''Die of'' is used for internal causes like overeating, disease, etc. (অভ্যন্তরীণ কারণে মৃত্যু)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'She ______ in Dhaka for ten years.',
              ARRAY['lived', 'has been living', 'is living', 'was living'],
              1,
              '''For ten years'' indicates duration. If she still lives there, present perfect continuous (চলমান বর্তমান) is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He talks as if he ______ a leader.',
              ARRAY['is', 'was', 'were', 'has been'],
              2,
              'After ''as if'' expressing an unreal situation (অবাস্তব অবস্থা), ''were'' is used for all persons.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'No one ______ the secret except her.',
              ARRAY['know', 'knows', 'are knowing', 'have known'],
              1,
              '''No one'' is an indefinite pronoun (অনির্দিষ্ট সর্বনাম) that is always singular.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He had his house ______ last year.',
              ARRAY['paint', 'painted', 'painting', 'to paint'],
              1,
              'In causative structure (কাজ করানো), ''have + object + past participle'' means to get something done.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'If I were you, I ______ not do it.',
              ARRAY['will', 'would', 'shall', 'can'],
              1,
              'In unreal conditional sentences (অবাস্তব শর্ত), ''would'' is used in the main clause.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The scenery of this place ______ very charming.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              '''Scenery'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য বিশেষ্য) and takes a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is used to ______ in a joint family.',
              ARRAY['live', 'living', 'lives', 'lived'],
              1,
              '''Used to'' (অভ্যস্ত) is followed by a gerund when it means ''accustomed to''. Here ''to'' is a preposition.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The committee ______ issued its report.',
              ARRAY['have', 'has', 'are', 'were'],
              1,
              'When a collective noun (সমষ্টিবাচক বিশেষ্য) acts as a single unit, it takes a singular verb. ''Its'' indicates unity.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He refrained ______ any further comments.',
              ARRAY['to make', 'making', 'from making', 'make'],
              2,
              'The verb ''refrain'' is always followed by the preposition ''from'' and then a gerund (বিরত থাকা অর্থে from + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The boy stopped ______ when he saw his mother.',
              ARRAY['to cry', 'crying', 'cry', 'cried'],
              1,
              '''Stop + gerund'' means to cease an action (কাজ বন্ধ করা). He was crying and then stopped.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is looking for a job ______.',
              ARRAY['at present', 'every day', 'last week', 'tomorrow'],
              0,
              '''At present'' (বর্তমানে) indicates present continuous tense, which matches ''is looking''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The jury ______ unanimous in its decision.',
              ARRAY['was', 'were', 'have', 'are'],
              0,
              'When a collective noun (সমষ্টিবাচক বিশেষ্য) acts as a single unit, it takes a singular verb. ''Its'' indicates unity.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He was accused of ______ the money.',
              ARRAY['steal', 'stealing', 'stole', 'to steal'],
              1,
              'After preposition ''of'', we use a gerund (অভিযুক্ত অর্থে of + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ here since 1995.',
              ARRAY['lived', 'has lived', 'is living', 'was living'],
              1,
              '''Since 1995'' indicates an action that started in the past and continues to the present. Present perfect tense is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He talks as though he ______ a scholar.',
              ARRAY['is', 'was', 'were', 'has been'],
              2,
              'After ''as though'' expressing an unreal situation (অবাস্তব অবস্থা), ''were'' is used for all persons.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The United Nations ______ its headquarters in New York.',
              ARRAY['have', 'has', 'are', 'were'],
              1,
              'Names of organizations (সংস্থার নাম) like ''The United Nations'' are singular and take a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He insisted that he ______ go there.',
              ARRAY['will', 'would', 'should', 'can'],
              2,
              'After ''insist'' (জোর দেওয়া) in a clause, we often use ''should'' in formal English.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I don''t know why he ______ to me now.',
              ARRAY['lie', 'lies', 'is lying', 'has lied'],
              2,
              '''Now'' indicates present continuous tense. The action is happening at the moment of speaking (এখন ঘটছে)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The poet and the philosopher ______ dead.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'was', 'has'],
              0,
              'Here, ''the poet and the philosopher'' refers to two different persons (দুই ভিন্ন ব্যক্তি) because ''the'' is used before both. So plural verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He was made ______ the work again.',
              ARRAY['do', 'to do', 'doing', 'did'],
              1,
              'In passive voice, after ''made'', we use ''to + verb'' (Passive-এ to + verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The cattle ______ grazing in the field.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'was', 'has'],
              1,
              '''Cattle'' is a plural noun (গবাদি পশু বহুবচনে) and always takes a plural verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is good at ______ stories.',
              ARRAY['tell', 'telling', 'tells', 'to tell'],
              1,
              'After prepositions like ''at'', we use a gerund (দক্ষতা অর্থে at + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I will call you when I ______ the result.',
              ARRAY['get', 'will get', 'got', 'have got'],
              0,
              'In time clauses with ''when/after/before'', present tense is used for future meaning (সময়সূচক clause-এ ভবিষ্যৎ অর্থে present)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He died ______ cholera.',
              ARRAY['from', 'of', 'by', 'with'],
              1,
              '''Die of'' is used for diseases (রোগে মরা). ''Die from'' is used for external causes.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The boy along with his friends ______ present.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              'When subjects are joined by ''along with'', the verb agrees with the first subject (প্রথম subject অনুযায়ী verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He spends a lot of time ______ mobile games.',
              ARRAY['play', 'to play', 'playing', 'plays'],
              2,
              'After ''spend time'', we use a gerund (সময় কাটানো অর্থে gerund) to show the activity.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He would rather starve than ______.',
              ARRAY['to steal', 'steal', 'stealing', 'stole'],
              1,
              'After ''would rather...than'', we use the base form of the verb (বেস ফর্ম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The police ______ arrested the culprit.',
              ARRAY['has', 'have', 'is', 'was'],
              1,
              '''Police'' is a collective noun that is always plural in English and takes a plural verb (পুলিশ সর্বদা বহুবচন)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'It is time you ______ home.',
              ARRAY['go', 'went', 'have gone', 'will go'],
              1,
              'After ''It is time'', we use past tense (অতীতকাল) to indicate something that should be done now.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He was seen ______ the house.',
              ARRAY['enter', 'entered', 'to enter', 'enters'],
              2,
              'In passive voice, after verbs of perception, we use ''to + verb'' (Passive-এ to + verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Many a student ______ failed in the exam.',
              ARRAY['have', 'has', 'are', 'were'],
              1,
              '''Many a'' is always followed by a singular noun and singular verb (Many a + singular noun + singular verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is not accustomed to ______ in public.',
              ARRAY['speak', 'speaking', 'spoke', 'speaks'],
              1,
              '''Accustomed to'' is followed by a gerund (অভ্যস্ত অর্থে to + ing) because ''to'' is a preposition here.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The furniture ______ been repaired.',
              ARRAY['have', 'has', 'are', 'were'],
              1,
              '''Furniture'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য বিশেষ্য) and takes a singular verb ''has''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'If he had studied, he ______ passed.',
              ARRAY['would have', 'will have', 'has', 'had'],
              0,
              'In third conditional (অতীতের অবাস্তব শর্ত), structure: If + past perfect, would have + past participle.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He told me that he ______ come the next day.',
              ARRAY['will', 'would', 'shall', 'can'],
              1,
              'In indirect speech, when reporting verb is past, ''will'' changes to ''would'' (Narration-এর নিয়ম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ a letter when I entered his room.',
              ARRAY['wrote', 'was writing', 'has written', 'writes'],
              1,
              'When one past action was in progress and another interrupted it, past continuous tense is used (চলমান অতীত কাজ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Neither of the two candidates ______ suitable.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              'After ''neither of/either of'', the verb is always singular (একবচন)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is looking forward to ______ his parents.',
              ARRAY['meet', 'meeting', 'met', 'have met'],
              1,
              '''Look forward to'' is a phrase where ''to'' is a preposition, so it takes a gerund (ing যুক্ত verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The water ______ for two hours.',
              ARRAY['boils', 'has been boiling', 'is boiling', 'was boiling'],
              1,
              '''For two hours'' indicates duration up to now. Present perfect continuous (সময়সীমাসহ চলমান কাজ) is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The patient died before the doctor ______.',
              ARRAY['arrived', 'had arrived', 'arrives', 'has arrived'],
              0,
              'After ''before'', when the main clause is past perfect, the ''before'' clause takes simple past (Past perfect-এর পরে before + past indefinite)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is fond of ______ poetry.',
              ARRAY['recite', 'reciting', 'recites', 'to recite'],
              1,
              'After prepositions (of, in, at, etc.), we use a gerund (ing যুক্ত verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The Principal, with his staff, ______ present.',
              ARRAY['are', 'were', 'is', 'have'],
              2,
              'When ''with'' joins two subjects, the verb agrees with the first subject (প্রথম subject অনুযায়ী verb)। Here, ''Principal'' is singular.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He has given up ______.',
              ARRAY['smoke', 'to smoke', 'smoking', 'smoked'],
              2,
              'After ''give up'', we use a gerund (পরিত্যাগ করা অর্থে gerund)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I wish I ______ a bird.',
              ARRAY['am', 'was', 'were', 'have been'],
              2,
              'After ''wish'', we use the subjunctive mood (were) to express an unreal or impossible desire (অবাস্তব ইচ্ছা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He refrained ______ any further questions.',
              ARRAY['to ask', 'asking', 'from asking', 'ask'],
              2,
              'The verb ''refrain'' is always followed by the preposition ''from'' and then a gerund (বিরত থাকা অর্থে from + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The scenery of this place ______ charming.',
              ARRAY['are', 'were', 'is', 'have'],
              2,
              '''Scenery'' is an uncountable noun (অগণনাযোগ্য) and takes a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He ______ here for twenty years by next December.',
              ARRAY['will work', 'will have been working', 'works', 'worked'],
              1,
              '''By next December'' with ''for twenty years'' indicates future perfect continuous tense (ভবিষ্যতে চলমান কাজের সময়কাল)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'I don''t mind ______ late at night.',
              ARRAY['work', 'to work', 'working', 'worked'],
              2,
              'After ''mind'', we always use a gerund (verb + ing) (আপত্তি থাকা অর্থে mind + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He talked as if he ______ everything.',
              ARRAY['knows', 'knew', 'has known', 'is knowing'],
              1,
              'After ''as if'' expressing an unreal situation (অবাস্তব অবস্থা), past tense is used.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The number of students ______ increasing day by day.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'were', 'have'],
              0,
              '''The number of'' is followed by a plural noun but takes a singular verb. (''The number of'' -এর পরে singular verb হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'A number of students ______ present in the class.',
              ARRAY['is', 'was', 'are', 'has'],
              2,
              '''A number of'' means ''many'' and takes a plural verb. (''A number of'' অর্থ ''অনেক'' এবং plural verb হয়)'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He insisted on ______ there immediately.',
              ARRAY['go', 'going', 'to go', 'went'],
              1,
              'After ''insist on'', we use a gerund (verb + ing) because ''on'' is a preposition (জোর দেওয়া অর্থে on + ing)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The news ______ at 8 pm every day.',
              ARRAY['is broadcast', 'are broadcast', 'broadcast', 'broadcasts'],
              0,
              'The news is broadcast (by someone). This is passive voice. ''News'' is singular, so ''is'' is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He would not come, ______ he?',
              ARRAY['would', 'wouldn''t', 'will', 'did'],
              0,
              'The sentence is negative (would not), so the question tag (ট্যাগ প্রশ্ন) must be positive ''would''.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'Five miles ______ a long way to walk.',
              ARRAY['are', 'is', 'were', 'have'],
              1,
              'Expressions of distance (দূরত্ব) are treated as a single unit and take a singular verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He is looking forward to ______ his uncle.',
              ARRAY['meet', 'meeting', 'met', 'have met'],
              1,
              '''Look forward to'' is a phrase where ''to'' is a preposition, so it takes a gerund (ing যুক্ত verb)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'The cattle ______ grazing in the field.',
              ARRAY['is', 'are', 'was', 'has'],
              1,
              '''Cattle'' is a plural noun (গবাদি পশু বহুবচনে) and always takes a plural verb.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'He died ______ overeating.',
              ARRAY['from', 'of', 'by', 'with'],
              1,
              '''Die of'' is used for internal causes like overeating, disease, etc. (অভ্যন্তরীণ কারণে মৃত্যু)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Right Form Of Verb',
              'She ______ in Chittagong for ten years.',
              ARRAY['lived', 'has been living', 'is living', 'was living'],
              1,
              '''For ten years'' indicates duration. If she still lives there, present perfect continuous (চলমান বর্তমান) is correct.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which of the following is the most appropriate synonym for the word ''Abhor''?',
              ARRAY['Love', 'Hate', 'Admire', 'Enjoy'],
              1,
              '''Abhor'' (ঘৃণা করা) means to hate something intensely. Its synonyms are detest (ঘৃণা করা), loathe (ঘৃণা করা), despise (অবজ্ঞা করা), and abominate (ঘৃণা করা). Antonyms are love (ভালোবাসা), admire (প্রশংসা করা), adore (পূজা করা), and cherish (লালন করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Benevolent''?',
              ARRAY['Cruel', 'Kind', 'Mean', 'Strict'],
              1,
              '''Benevolent'' (সদাশয়) means well-meaning and kindly. Its synonyms are kind (সদয়), generous (উদার), compassionate (দয়ালু), and humane (মানবিক). Antonyms are cruel (নিষ্ঠুর), malevolent (বিদ্বেষপরায়ণ), unkind (অদয়ালু), and harsh (কঠোর).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Broad'' is:',
              ARRAY['Wide', 'Narrow', 'Extensive', 'Large'],
              1,
              '''Broad'' (প্রশস্ত) means wide or large. Its synonyms are wide (প্রশস্ত), expansive (বিস্তৃত), vast (বিশাল), and extensive (ব্যাপক). Its antonyms are narrow (সংকীর্ণ), limited (সীমিত), restricted (সীমাবদ্ধ), and slender (ক্ষীণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Candid''?',
              ARRAY['Secretive', 'Reserved', 'Outspoken', 'Deceptive'],
              2,
              '''Candid'' (অকপট/মনখোলা) means truthful and straightforward. Its synonyms are outspoken (অকপট), frank (স্পষ্টবাদী), honest (সৎ), and blunt (সরাসরি). Antonyms are secretive (গোপনীয়), reserved (সংযত), deceitful (প্রতারক), and insincere (অকৃত্রিম নয় এমন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the antonym of ''Accept''?',
              ARRAY['Receive', 'Reject', 'Agree', 'Admit'],
              1,
              '''Accept'' (গ্রহণ করা) means to agree to receive something. Its synonyms are receive (গ্রহণ করা), agree (সম্মত হওয়া), admit (স্বীকার করা), and embrace (অংশীদার করা). Its antonyms are reject (প্রত্যাখ্যান করা), refuse (অস্বীকার করা), decline (বাতিল করা), and deny (অস্বীকার করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The synonym of ''Significant'' is:',
              ARRAY['Minor', 'Trivial', 'Important', 'Insignificant'],
              2,
              '''Significant'' (গুরুত্বপূর্ণ) means sufficiently great or important. Its synonyms are important (গুরুত্বপূর্ণ), major (প্রধান), meaningful (অর্থপূর্ণ), and considerable (উল্লেখযোগ্য). Antonyms are insignificant (নগণ্য), minor (গৌণ), trivial (তুচ্ছ), and unimportant (অগুরুত্বপূর্ণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the antonym of ''Precious''?',
              ARRAY['Valuable', 'Costly', 'Valueless', 'Dear'],
              2,
              '''Precious'' (মূল্যবান) means of great value. Its synonyms are valuable (মূল্যবান), costly (ব্যয়বহুল), dear (প্রিয়), and prized (মূল্যবান). Its antonyms are valueless (মূল্যহীন), worthless (অকিঞ্চিতকর), cheap (সস্তা), and insignificant (নগণ্য).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The synonym of ''Alleviate'' is:',
              ARRAY['Aggravate', 'Worsen', 'Abate', 'Intensify'],
              2,
              '''Alleviate'' (উপশম করা) means to make suffering less severe. Its synonyms are abate (কমানো), relieve (উপশম করা), lessen (হ্রাস করা), and mitigate (লাঘব করা). Antonyms are aggravate (বাড়িয়ে তোলা), worsen (খারাপ করা), intensify (তীব্র করা), and increase (বৃদ্ধি করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which is the antonym of ''Major''?',
              ARRAY['Main', 'Important', 'Minor', 'Greater'],
              2,
              '''Major'' (প্রধান) means important or serious. Its synonyms are main (প্রধান), important (গুরুত্বপূর্ণ), significant (গুরুত্বপূর্ণ), and chief (প্রধান). Its antonyms are minor (গৌণ), unimportant (অগুরুত্বপূর্ণ), insignificant (নগণ্য), and lesser (কম গুরুত্বপূর্ণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Articulate''?',
              ARRAY['Unclear', 'Mumbled', 'Intelligible', 'Vague'],
              2,
              '''Articulate'' (স্পষ্ট) means able to express thoughts clearly. Its synonyms are intelligible (স্পষ্ট), eloquent (বাকপটু), fluent (সাবলীল), and coherent (সুসংহত). Antonyms are unclear (অস্পষ্ট), mumbled (বিড়বিড় করা), vague (অস্পষ্ট), and unintelligible (অবোধ্য).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Include'' is:',
              ARRAY['Contain', 'Comprise', 'Exclude', 'Involve'],
              2,
              '''Include'' (অন্তর্ভুক্ত করা) means to comprise as part of a whole. Its synonyms are contain (ধারণ করা), comprise (গঠিত হওয়া), involve (জড়িত করা), and encompass (বেষ্টন করা). Its antonyms are exclude (বাদ দেওয়া), omit (বর্জন করা), leave out (বাদ দেওয়া), and eliminate (বাদ দেওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Genuine''?',
              ARRAY['Fake', 'Artificial', 'Authentic', 'Counterfeit'],
              2,
              '''Genuine'' (খাঁটি) means truly what it is said to be. Its synonyms are authentic (প্রকৃত), real (বাস্তব), true (সত্য), and legitimate (বৈধ). Antonyms are fake (নকল), artificial (কৃত্রিম), counterfeit (জাল), and false (মিথ্যা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Succeed'' is:',
              ARRAY['Prosper', 'Triumph', 'Fail', 'Achieve'],
              2,
              '''Succeed'' (সফল হওয়া) means to achieve a goal. Its synonyms are prosper (উন্নতি করা), triumph (জয়লাভ করা), achieve (অর্জন করা), and flourish (বৃদ্ধি পাওয়া). Its antonyms are fail (ব্যর্থ হওয়া), lose (হারা), fall short (অকৃতকার্য হওয়া), and miss (ব্যর্থ হওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Ambiguous''?',
              ARRAY['Clear', 'Unclear', 'Obvious', 'Definite'],
              1,
              '''Ambiguous'' (অস্পষ্ট) means open to more than one interpretation. Its synonyms are unclear (অস্পষ্ট), vague (অস্পষ্ট), doubtful (সন্দেহজনক), and equivocal (দ্ব্যর্থক). Antonyms are clear (পরিষ্কার), obvious (সুস্পষ্ট), definite (নির্দিষ্ট), and explicit (স্পষ্ট).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Narrow'' is:',
              ARRAY['Slender', 'Limited', 'Broad', 'Tight'],
              2,
              '''Narrow'' (সংকীর্ণ) means of small width. Its synonyms are slender (ক্ষীণ), limited (সীমিত), tight (আঁটসাঁট), and confined (সীমাবদ্ধ). Its antonyms are broad (প্রশস্ত), wide (প্রশস্ত), expansive (বিস্তৃত), and spacious (বিশাল).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which is the synonym of ''Frustrate''?',
              ARRAY['Aid', 'Assist', 'Thwart', 'Encourage'],
              2,
              '''Frustrate'' (বিফল করা) means to prevent from achieving a goal. Its synonyms are thwart (বিফল করা), foil (ব্যর্থ করা), hinder (বাধা দেওয়া), and baffle (ব্যাহত করা). Antonyms are aid (সাহায্য করা), assist (সহায়তা করা), encourage (উৎসাহিত করা), and support (সমর্থন করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Ancient'' is:',
              ARRAY['Old', 'Aged', 'Modern', 'Antique'],
              2,
              '''Ancient'' (প্রাচীন) means belonging to the very distant past. Its synonyms are old (পুরাতন), aged (বৃদ্ধ), antique (প্রাচীন), and archaic (প্রাচীন). Its antonyms are modern (আধুনিক), new (নতুন), recent (সাম্প্রতিক), and contemporary (সমসাময়িক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Aboriginal''?',
              ARRAY['Foreign', 'Immigrant', 'Native', 'Modern'],
              2,
              '''Aboriginal'' (আদিম/আদিবাসী) means inhabiting or existing in a land from the earliest times. Its synonyms are native (স্থানীয়), indigenous (আদিবাসী), primitive (আদিম), and original (আদি). Antonyms are foreign (বিদেশী), immigrant (অভিবাসী), alien (বিদেশী), and modern (আধুনিক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The synonym of ''Barren'' is:',
              ARRAY['Fertile', 'Productive', 'Sterile', 'Rich'],
              2,
              '''Barren'' (অনুর্বর) means too poor to produce much vegetation. Its synonyms are sterile (অনুর্বর), infertile (অনুর্বর), unproductive (অফলপ্রসূ), and arid (শুষ্ক). Antonyms are fertile (উর্বর), productive (উৎপাদনশীল), rich (সমৃদ্ধ), and fruitful (ফলপ্রসূ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the antonym of ''Expand''?',
              ARRAY['Enlarge', 'Increase', 'Contract', 'Extend'],
              2,
              '''Expand'' (বিস্তৃত করা) means to become or make larger. Its synonyms are enlarge (বড় করা), increase (বৃদ্ধি করা), extend (প্রসারিত করা), and swell (ফুলে ওঠা). Its antonyms are contract (সংকুচিত করা), shrink (সঙ্কুচিত হওয়া), compress (চাপ দেওয়া), and condense (সংক্ষিপ্ত করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Hostile''?',
              ARRAY['Friendly', 'Unfriendly', 'Kind', 'Warm'],
              1,
              '''Hostile'' (বিরোধী) means unfriendly or antagonistic. Its synonyms are unfriendly (অবন্ধুসুলভ), antagonistic (বিরোধী), aggressive (আক্রমণাত্মক), and belligerent (যুদ্ধপ্রিয়). Antonyms are friendly (বন্ধুত্বপূর্ণ), kind (সদয়), warm (উষ্ণ), and amicable (সৌহার্দ্যপূর্ণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Polite'' is:',
              ARRAY['Courteous', 'Respectful', 'Rude', 'Mannerly'],
              2,
              '''Polite'' (ভদ্র) means having good manners. Its synonyms are courteous (বিনয়ী), respectful (শ্রদ্ধাশীল), mannerly (সভ্য), and gracious (সদয়). Its antonyms are rude (অভদ্র), impolite (অভদ্র), discourteous (অবিনয়ী), and disrespectful (অশ্রদ্ধাশীল).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Courageous''?',
              ARRAY['Cowardly', 'Fearful', 'Brave', 'Timid'],
              2,
              '''Courageous'' (সাহসী) means not deterred by danger or pain. Its synonyms are brave (সাহসী), fearless (নির্ভীক), valiant (বীর), and daring (সাহসিক). Antonyms are cowardly (কাপুরুষ), fearful (ভীত), timid (ভীরু), and weak (দুর্বল).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Famous'' is:',
              ARRAY['Renowned', 'Celebrated', 'Unknown', 'Prominent'],
              2,
              '''Famous'' (বিখ্যাত) means known about by many people. Its synonyms are renowned (সুপ্রসিদ্ধ), celebrated (প্রখ্যাত), prominent (প্রধান), and eminent (বিশিষ্ট). Its antonyms are unknown (অজানা), obscure (অস্পষ্ট/অখ্যাত), anonymous (নামহীন), and nameless (নামবিহীন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Tranquil''?',
              ARRAY['Agitated', 'Restless', 'Calm', 'Disturbed'],
              2,
              '''Tranquil'' (শান্ত) means free from disturbance. Its synonyms are calm (শান্ত), peaceful (শান্তিপূর্ণ), serene (নিশ্চিন্ত), and quiet (নীরব). Antonyms are agitated (উত্তেজিত), restless (অস্থির), disturbed (বিক্ষুব্ধ), and chaotic (বিশৃঙ্খল).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Artificial'' is:',
              ARRAY['Synthetic', 'Fake', 'Natural', 'Manufactured'],
              2,
              '''Artificial'' (কৃত্রিম) means made or produced by human beings. Its synonyms are synthetic (কৃত্রিম), fake (নকল), man-made (মানবসৃষ্ট), and false (মিথ্যা). Its antonyms are natural (প্রাকৃতিক), real (বাস্তব), genuine (খাঁটি), and authentic (প্রকৃত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Abundant''?',
              ARRAY['Scarce', 'Plentiful', 'Rare', 'Limited'],
              1,
              '''Abundant'' (প্রচুর) means existing in large quantities. Its synonyms are plentiful (প্রচুর), ample (যথেষ্ট), copious (প্রচুর), and lavish (উদার). Antonyms are scarce (দুর্লভ), rare (বিরল), limited (সীমিত), and insufficient (অপর্যাপ্ত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Ascend'' is:',
              ARRAY['Rise', 'Climb', 'Descend', 'Soar'],
              2,
              '''Ascend'' (আরোহণ করা) means to go up or climb. Its synonyms are rise (ওঠা), climb (ওঠা), mount (আরোহণ করা), and soar (উড়া). Its antonyms are descend (নামা), drop (পড়া), fall (পতন), and decline (হ্রাস পাওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Brief''?',
              ARRAY['Long', 'Extended', 'Short', 'Prolonged'],
              2,
              '''Brief'' (সংক্ষিপ্ত) means of short duration. Its synonyms are short (সংক্ষিপ্ত), concise (সংক্ষিপ্ত), succinct (সংক্ষিপ্ত), and terse (সংক্ষিপ্ত). Antonyms are long (দীর্ঘ), extended (বর্ধিত), prolonged (দীর্ঘায়িত), and lengthy (দীর্ঘ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Bold'' is:',
              ARRAY['Fearless', 'Brave', 'Timid', 'Daring'],
              2,
              '''Bold'' (সাহসী) means showing courage. Its synonyms are fearless (নির্ভীক), brave (সাহসী), daring (সাহসিক), and audacious (দুঃসাহসী). Its antonyms are timid (ভীরু), cowardly (কাপুরুষ), shy (লাজুক), and meek (নম্র).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Captivate''?',
              ARRAY['Repel', 'Charm', 'Disgust', 'Offend'],
              1,
              '''Captivate'' (মোহিত করা) means to attract and hold interest. Its synonyms are charm (মুগ্ধ করা), fascinate (মোহিত করা), enchant (মন্ত্রমুগ্ধ করা), and allure (প্রলুব্ধ করা). Antonyms are repel (বিতাড়িত করা), disgust (বিরক্তি সৃষ্টি করা), offend (অপমান করা), and revolt (বিদ্রোহ করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Complex'' is:',
              ARRAY['Complicated', 'Simple', 'Intricate', 'Difficult'],
              1,
              '''Complex'' (জটিল) means consisting of many different parts. Its synonyms are complicated (জটিল), intricate (জটিল), involved (জড়িত), and elaborate (বিস্তারিত). Its antonyms are simple (সরল), easy (সহজ), straightforward (সরাসরি), and uncomplicated (অজটিল).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Diligent''?',
              ARRAY['Lazy', 'Hardworking', 'Idle', 'Inactive'],
              1,
              '''Diligent'' (পরিশ্রমী) means showing care and effort. Its synonyms are hardworking (পরিশ্রমী), industrious (শ্রমশীল), assiduous (অধ্যবসায়ী), and meticulous (সতর্ক). Antonyms are lazy (অলস), idle (অলস), inactive (নিষ্ক্রিয়), and negligent (অবহেলাকারী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Emigrate'' is:',
              ARRAY['Leave', 'Depart', 'Immigrate', 'Abandon'],
              2,
              '''Emigrate'' (অভিবাসন করা - নিজ দেশ ত্যাগ করা) means to leave one''s country to settle in another. Its synonyms are migrate (স্থানান্তরিত হওয়া), relocate (পুনর্বাসিত হওয়া), and move abroad (বিদেশে চলে যাওয়া). Its antonym is immigrate (অভিবাসন করা - অন্য দেশে বসবাস করতে আসা). Related terms: leave (ত্যাগ করা) and depart (চলে যাওয়া) are not direct antonyms.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Fragile''?',
              ARRAY['Strong', 'Delicate', 'Tough', 'Sturdy'],
              1,
              '''Fragile'' (ভঙ্গুর) means easily broken or damaged. Its synonyms are delicate (সূক্ষ্ম/ভঙ্গুর), breakable (ভাঙনযোগ্য), brittle (ভঙ্গুর), and weak (দুর্বল). Antonyms are strong (শক্তিশালী), tough (কঠিন), sturdy (মজবুত), and durable (টেকসই).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Gloomy'' is:',
              ARRAY['Dark', 'Cheerful', 'Sad', 'Dismal'],
              1,
              '''Gloomy'' (অন্ধকার/বিষণ্ণ) means dark or sad. Its synonyms are dark (অন্ধকার), dismal (বিষণ্ণ), sad (দুঃখিত), and depressing (হতাশাজনক). Antonyms are cheerful (প্রফুল্ল), bright (উজ্জ্বল), happy (খুশি), and joyous (আনন্দিত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Hinder''?',
              ARRAY['Aid', 'Obstruct', 'Assist', 'Facilitate'],
              1,
              '''Hinder'' (বাধা দেওয়া) means to make it difficult for something to happen. Its synonyms are obstruct (বাধা দেওয়া), impede (বাধা দেওয়া), prevent (প্রতিরোধ করা), and block (অবরোধ করা). Antonyms are aid (সাহায্য করা), assist (সহায়তা করা), facilitate (সহজতর করা), and help (সাহায্য করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Import'' is:',
              ARRAY['Bring in', 'Introduce', 'Export', 'Land'],
              2,
              '''Import'' (আমদানি করা) means to bring goods into a country. Its synonyms are bring in (আনা), introduce (প্রবর্তন করা), and land (আনা). Its antonyms are export (রপ্তানি করা), send out (পাঠানো), and sell abroad (বিদেশে বিক্রি করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Jubilant''?',
              ARRAY['Sad', 'Joyful', 'Mournful', 'Gloomy'],
              1,
              '''Jubilant'' (আনন্দিত) means feeling great happiness. Its synonyms are joyful (আনন্দিত), overjoyed (অতিশয় আনন্দিত), elated (উল্লসিত), and ecstatic (পরমানন্দিত). Antonyms are sad (দুঃখিত), mournful (শোকাহত), gloomy (বিষণ্ণ), and depressed (হতাশ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Knowledge'' is:',
              ARRAY['Wisdom', 'Ignorance', 'Understanding', 'Awareness'],
              1,
              '''Knowledge'' (জ্ঞান) means facts, information, and skills acquired. Its synonyms are wisdom (প্রজ্ঞা), understanding (বোধগম্যতা), awareness (সচেতনতা), and erudition (পাণ্ডিত্য). Its antonyms are ignorance (অজ্ঞতা), illiteracy (নিরক্ষরতা), and unawareness (অজ্ঞানতা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Lethal''?',
              ARRAY['Harmless', 'Deadly', 'Safe', 'Beneficial'],
              1,
              '''Lethal'' (মারাত্মক) means sufficient to cause death. Its synonyms are deadly (মারাত্মক), fatal (প্রাণঘাতী), mortal (নশ্বর), and poisonous (বিষাক্ত). Antonyms are harmless (ক্ষতিকর নয়), safe (নিরাপদ), beneficial (উপকারী), and wholesome (স্বাস্থ্যকর).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Mature'' is:',
              ARRAY['Adult', 'Ripe', 'Immature', 'Grown'],
              2,
              '''Mature'' (পরিপক্ক) means fully developed. Its synonyms are adult (প্রাপ্তবয়স্ক), grown (বড় হওয়া), ripe (পাকা), and seasoned (অভিজ্ঞ). Its antonyms are immature (অপরিপক্ক), childish (শিশুসুলভ), inexperienced (অনভিজ্ঞ), and young (তরুণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Notify''?',
              ARRAY['Hide', 'Inform', 'Conceal', 'Suppress'],
              1,
              '''Notify'' (জানানো) means to inform someone. Its synonyms are inform (জানানো), tell (বলা), advise (পরামর্শ দেওয়া), and alert (সতর্ক করা). Antonyms are hide (লুকানো), conceal (গোপন করা), suppress (চাপা দেওয়া), and withhold (আটকে রাখা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Optimistic'' is:',
              ARRAY['Hopeful', 'Positive', 'Pessimistic', 'Confident'],
              2,
              '''Optimistic'' (আশাবাদী) means hopeful about the future. Its synonyms are hopeful (আশাবাদী), positive (ইতিবাচক), confident (আত্মবিশ্বাসী), and cheerful (প্রফুল্ল). Its antonyms are pessimistic (হতাশাবাদী), negative (নেতিবাচক), gloomy (বিষণ্ণ), and despairing (হতাশ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Permanent''?',
              ARRAY['Temporary', 'Everlasting', 'Short-lived', 'Momentary'],
              1,
              '''Permanent'' (স্থায়ী) means lasting for a long time. Its synonyms are everlasting (চিরস্থায়ী), perpetual (অবিরাম), enduring (টেকসই), and constant (অপরিবর্তনীয়). Antonyms are temporary (অস্থায়ী), short-lived (স্বল্পস্থায়ী), momentary (ক্ষণস্থায়ী), and transient (অস্থায়ী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Quiet'' is:',
              ARRAY['Silent', 'Calm', 'Noisy', 'Peaceful'],
              2,
              '''Quiet'' (শান্ত/নীরব) means making little or no noise. Its synonyms are silent (নীরব), calm (শান্ত), peaceful (শান্তিপূর্ণ), and still (স্থির). Its antonyms are noisy (কোলাহলপূর্ণ), loud (উচ্চৈঃস্বরে), boisterous (উদ্বেল), and turbulent (অস্থির).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Reluctant''?',
              ARRAY['Willing', 'Eager', 'Unwilling', 'Ready'],
              2,
              '''Reluctant'' (অনিচ্ছুক) means unwilling and hesitant. Its synonyms are unwilling (অনিচ্ছুক), hesitant (দ্বিধাগ্রস্ত), disinclined (অপ্রবৃত্ত), and averse (বিমুখ). Antonyms are willing (ইচ্ছুক), eager (আগ্রহী), ready (প্রস্তুত), and keen (আগ্রহী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Stable'' is:',
              ARRAY['Steady', 'Unstable', 'Fixed', 'Secure'],
              1,
              '''Stable'' (স্থিতিশীল) means firmly fixed and not likely to change. Its synonyms are steady (স্থির), fixed (স্থির), secure (নিরাপদ), and balanced (সুষম). Its antonyms are unstable (অস্থিতিশীল), unsteady (অস্থির), wobbly (টলোমলো), and shaky (কাঁপুনি).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Transparent''?',
              ARRAY['Opaque', 'Clear', 'Cloudy', 'Murky'],
              1,
              '''Transparent'' (স্বচ্ছ) means allowing light to pass through. Its synonyms are clear (পরিষ্কার), see-through (স্বচ্ছ), translucent (আলোক প্রেরক), and crystalline (স্ফটিকের মত). Antonyms are opaque (অস্বচ্ছ), cloudy (মেঘলা), murky (অন্ধকার), and hazy (কুয়াশাচ্ছন্ন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Unity'' is:',
              ARRAY['Harmony', 'Division', 'Oneness', 'Union'],
              1,
              '''Unity'' (ঐক্য) means the state of being joined together. Its synonyms are harmony (সম্প্রীতি), oneness (একতা), union (মিলন), and solidarity (সংহতি). Its antonyms are division (বিভাজন), disunity (অনৈক্য), separation (পৃথকীকরণ), and conflict (দ্বন্দ্ব).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Vacant''?',
              ARRAY['Occupied', 'Empty', 'Filled', 'Crowded'],
              1,
              '''Vacant'' (খালি) means not occupied. Its synonyms are empty (খালি), unoccupied (অধিকৃত নয়), void (শূন্য), and unfilled (অপূর্ণ). Antonyms are occupied (অধিকৃত), filled (পূর্ণ), crowded (ভিড়), and engaged (ব্যবহৃত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Wealthy'' is:',
              ARRAY['Rich', 'Affluent', 'Poor', 'Prosperous'],
              2,
              '''Wealthy'' (ধনী) means having great wealth. Its synonyms are rich (ধনী), affluent (সমৃদ্ধ), prosperous (উন্নতিশীল), and well-off (স্বচ্ছল). Its antonyms are poor (দরিদ্র), impoverished (নিঃস্ব), needy (অভাবী), and destitute (নিঃস্ব).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Yield''?',
              ARRAY['Resist', 'Surrender', 'Oppose', 'Withstand'],
              1,
              '''Yield'' (আত্মসমর্পণ করা/উৎপাদন করা) can mean to surrender or produce. Its synonyms for surrender are surrender (আত্মসমর্পণ করা), submit (বশ্যতা স্বীকার করা), give in (হার মানা), and succumb (পরাস্ত হওয়া). Antonyms are resist (প্রতিরোধ করা), oppose (বিরোধিতা করা), withstand (সহ্য করা), and fight (লড়াই করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Zenith'' is:',
              ARRAY['Peak', 'Summit', 'Nadir', 'Apex'],
              2,
              '''Zenith'' (চরম শিখর) means the highest point. Its synonyms are peak (শিখর), summit (চূড়া), apex (অগ্রভাগ), and climax (চরম বিন্দু). Its antonym is nadir (নিম্নতম বিন্দু), meaning the lowest point.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Absolve''?',
              ARRAY['Blame', 'Forgive', 'Accuse', 'Condemn'],
              1,
              '''Absolve'' (মুক্তি দেওয়া) means to declare free from guilt. Its synonyms are forgive (ক্ষমা করা), pardon (মাফ করা), exonerate (নির্দোষ প্রমাণ করা), and acquit (খালাস দেওয়া). Antonyms are blame (দোষারোপ করা), accuse (অভিযুক্ত করা), condemn (দোষী সাব্যস্ত করা), and convict (দোষী সাব্যস্ত করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Boast'' is:',
              ARRAY['Brag', 'Show off', 'Belittle', 'Vaunt'],
              2,
              '''Boast'' (অহংকার করা) means to talk with pride. Its synonyms are brag (অহংকার করা), show off (দেখানো), vaunt (প্রশংসা করা), and crow (গর্ব করা). Its antonyms are belittle (ছোট করা), deprecate (অবমূল্যায়ন করা), disparage (অপমান করা), and underrate (অবমূল্যায়ন করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Captivity''?',
              ARRAY['Freedom', 'Liberty', 'Imprisonment', 'Independence'],
              2,
              '''Captivity'' (বন্দীত্ব) means the condition of being imprisoned. Its synonyms are imprisonment (কারাবাস), confinement (আটক), incarceration (কারারুদ্ধকরণ), and custody (হেফাজত). Antonyms are freedom (স্বাধীনতা), liberty (স্বাধীনতা), independence (স্বাধীনতা), and release (মুক্তি).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Deficit'' is:',
              ARRAY['Shortage', 'Lack', 'Surplus', 'Dearth'],
              2,
              '''Deficit'' (ঘাটতি) means the amount by which something is too small. Its synonyms are shortage (ঘাটতি), lack (অভাব), dearth (স্বল্পতা), and insufficiency (অপ্রতুলতা). Its antonyms are surplus (উদ্বৃত্ত), excess (অতিরিক্ত), abundance (প্রাচুর্য), and plenty (প্রচুরতা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Eager''?',
              ARRAY['Reluctant', 'Unwilling', 'Keen', 'Apathetic'],
              2,
              '''Eager'' (আগ্রহী) means strongly wanting to do something. Its synonyms are keen (আগ্রহী), enthusiastic (উৎসাহী), avid (আগ্রহী), and zealous (সোৎসাহী). Antonyms are reluctant (অনিচ্ছুক), unwilling (অনিচ্ছুক), apathetic (উদাসীন), and indifferent (নিরপেক্ষ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Formal'' is:',
              ARRAY['Official', 'Ceremonial', 'Informal', 'Conventional'],
              2,
              '''Formal'' (আনুষ্ঠানিক) means done in accordance with rules. Its synonyms are official (সরকারী), ceremonial (আনুষ্ঠানিক), conventional (প্রচলিত), and proper (যথাযথ). Its antonyms are informal (অনানুষ্ঠানিক), casual (নৈমিত্তিক), relaxed (শিথিল), and unofficial (অননুমোদিত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Gather''?',
              ARRAY['Scatter', 'Disperse', 'Collect', 'Separate'],
              2,
              '''Gather'' (একত্র করা) means to bring together. Its synonyms are collect (সংগ্রহ করা), assemble (একত্রিত করা), accumulate (পুঞ্জীভূত করা), and congregate (সমবেত হওয়া). Antonyms are scatter (ছড়িয়ে দেওয়া), disperse (বিচ্ছুরিত করা), separate (পৃথক করা), and distribute (বিতরণ করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Honor'' is:',
              ARRAY['Respect', 'Esteem', 'Disgrace', 'Revere'],
              2,
              '''Honor'' (সম্মান) means high respect. Its synonyms are respect (সম্মান), esteem (শ্রদ্ধা), reverence (গভীর শ্রদ্ধা), and admiration (প্রশংসা). Its antonyms are disgrace (অপমান), dishonor (অসম্মান), shame (লজ্জা), and contempt (অবজ্ঞা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Immense''?',
              ARRAY['Tiny', 'Huge', 'Small', 'Minute'],
              1,
              '''Immense'' (বিশাল) means extremely large. Its synonyms are huge (বিশাল), enormous (প্রচণ্ড), gigantic (দৈত্যাকার), and vast (বিস্তীর্ণ). Antonyms are tiny (ক্ষুদ্র), small (ছোট), minute (অতি ক্ষুদ্র), and microscopic (অণুবীক্ষণিক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Junior'' is:',
              ARRAY['Younger', 'Inferior', 'Senior', 'Subordinate'],
              2,
              '''Junior'' (কনিষ্ঠ) means younger or lower in rank. Its synonyms are younger (তরুণ), inferior (নিম্নতর), subordinate (অধস্তন), and lesser (কম). Its antonyms are senior (বরিষ্ঠ), older (বয়স্ক), superior (উর্ধ্বতন), and major (প্রধান).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Kindle''?',
              ARRAY['Extinguish', 'Quench', 'Ignite', 'Douse'],
              2,
              '''Kindle'' (জ্বালানো) means to light or set on fire. Its synonyms are ignite (জ্বালানো), light (আলো দেওয়া), inflame (জ্বালানো), and arouse (উদ্দীপ্ত করা). Antonyms are extinguish (নিভানো), quench (নির্বাপিত করা), douse (জল দেওয়া), and smother (চাপা দেওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Lengthen'' is:',
              ARRAY['Extend', 'Prolong', 'Shorten', 'Elongate'],
              2,
              '''Lengthen'' (দীর্ঘ করা) means to make longer. Its synonyms are extend (বাড়ানো), prolong (দীর্ঘায়িত করা), elongate (প্রলম্বিত করা), and stretch (প্রসারিত করা). Its antonyms are shorten (ছোট করা), curtail (কমানো), abbreviate (সংক্ষিপ্ত করা), and truncate (কেটে ফেলা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Mend''?',
              ARRAY['Break', 'Repair', 'Damage', 'Ruin'],
              1,
              '''Mend'' (মেরামত করা) means to repair something. Its synonyms are repair (মেরামত করা), fix (ঠিক করা), restore (পুনরুদ্ধার করা), and patch (জোড়া দেওয়া). Antonyms are break (ভাঙ্গা), damage (ক্ষতি করা), ruin (ধ্বংস করা), and destroy (বিনষ্ট করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Native'' is:',
              ARRAY['Indigenous', 'Domestic', 'Foreign', 'Local'],
              2,
              '''Native'' (স্থানীয়) means associated with the place of one''s birth. Its synonyms are indigenous (আদিবাসী), local (স্থানীয়), domestic (দেশীয়), and original (আদি). Its antonyms are foreign (বিদেশী), alien (বিদেশী), immigrant (অভিবাসী), and exotic (বিদেশী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Obvious''?',
              ARRAY['Hidden', 'Clear', 'Concealed', 'Vague'],
              1,
              '''Obvious'' (সুস্পষ্ট) means easily perceived. Its synonyms are clear (পরিষ্কার), evident (স্পষ্ট), apparent (প্রকাশ্য), and distinct (স্বতন্ত্র). Antonyms are hidden (লুকানো), concealed (গোপন), vague (অস্পষ্ট), and obscure (অস্পষ্ট).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Public'' is:',
              ARRAY['Open', 'Private', 'General', 'Common'],
              1,
              '''Public'' (সর্বজনীন) means open to everyone. Its synonyms are open (খোলা), general (সাধারণ), common (সাধারণ), and communal (গণ-). Its antonyms are private (ব্যক্তিগত), personal (ব্যক্তিগত), confidential (গোপনীয়), and secret (গোপন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Question''?',
              ARRAY['Answer', 'Interrogate', 'Reply', 'Respond'],
              1,
              '''Question'' (প্রশ্ন করা) means to ask. Its synonyms are interrogate (জিজ্ঞাসাবাদ করা), inquire (জিজ্ঞাসা করা), query (প্রশ্ন করা), and quiz (পরীক্ষা করা). Antonyms are answer (উত্তর দেওয়া), reply (জবাব দেওয়া), respond (সাড়া দেওয়া), and rejoin (প্রত্যুত্তর দেওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Rapid'' is:',
              ARRAY['Fast', 'Quick', 'Slow', 'Swift'],
              2,
              '''Rapid'' (দ্রুত) means happening quickly. Its synonyms are fast (দ্রুত), quick (দ্রুত), swift (দ্রুত), and speedy (শীঘ্র). Its antonyms are slow (ধীর), sluggish (মন্থর), leisurely (আরামদায়ক), and gradual (ধীরে ধীরে).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Secure''?',
              ARRAY['Safe', 'Unsafe', 'Vulnerable', 'Risky'],
              0,
              '''Secure'' (নিরাপদ) means safe from danger. Its synonyms are safe (নিরাপদ), protected (সুরক্ষিত), guarded (রক্ষিত), and sheltered (আশ্রিত). Antonyms are unsafe (অনিরাপদ), vulnerable (অরক্ষিত), risky (ঝুঁকিপূর্ণ), and exposed (উন্মুক্ত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Truth'' is:',
              ARRAY['Fact', 'Reality', 'Lie', 'Verity'],
              2,
              '''Truth'' (সত্য) means that which is true. Its synonyms are fact (সত্য), reality (বাস্তবতা), verity (সত্যতা), and accuracy (নির্ভুলতা). Its antonyms are lie (মিথ্যা), falsehood (মিথ্যা), untruth (অসত্য), and deception (প্রতারণা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Under''?',
              ARRAY['Above', 'Below', 'Over', 'Upon'],
              1,
              '''Under'' (নীচে) means extending directly below. Its synonyms are below (নীচে), beneath (নিম্নে), underneath (নিচে), and lower (নিম্নতর). Antonyms are above (উপরে), over (উপরে), higher (উচ্চতর), and beyond (বাইরে).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Victory'' is:',
              ARRAY['Triumph', 'Conquest', 'Defeat', 'Success'],
              2,
              '''Victory'' (জয়) means success in a contest. Its synonyms are triumph (জয়), conquest (বিজয়), success (সাফল্য), and win (জয়). Its antonyms are defeat (পরাজয়), loss (ক্ষতি), failure (ব্যর্থতা), and downfall (পতন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Whole''?',
              ARRAY['Part', 'Entire', 'Partial', 'Fraction'],
              1,
              '''Whole'' (সমগ্র) means all of something. Its synonyms are entire (সম্পূর্ণ), total (মোট), full (পূর্ণ), and complete (সম্পূর্ণ). Antonyms are part (অংশ), partial (আংশিক), fraction (ভগ্নাংশ), and segment (খণ্ড).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Young'' is:',
              ARRAY['Youthful', 'Old', 'Juvenile', 'Immature'],
              1,
              '''Young'' (তরুণ) means having lived for a short time. Its synonyms are youthful (তরুণ), juvenile (কিশোর), immature (অপরিণত), and adolescent (কৈশোরের). Its antonyms are old (বৃদ্ধ), aged (বয়স্ক), elderly (প্রবীণ), and ancient (প্রাচীন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Zeal''?',
              ARRAY['Apathy', 'Enthusiasm', 'Indifference', 'Lethargy'],
              1,
              '''Zeal'' (আগ্রহ/উদ্দীপনা) means great energy in pursuit of a cause. Its synonyms are enthusiasm (উৎসাহ), passion (আবেগ), fervor (উদ্দীপনা), and ardor (প্রবল ইচ্ছা). Antonyms are apathy (উদাসীনতা), indifference (নিরপেক্ষতা), lethargy (অলসতা), and sluggishness (মন্থরতা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Active'' is:',
              ARRAY['Energetic', 'Lively', 'Inactive', 'Vigorous'],
              2,
              '''Active'' (সক্রিয়) means engaging in action. Its synonyms are energetic (উদ্যমী), lively (প্রাণবন্ত), vigorous (সবল), and dynamic (গতিশীল). Its antonyms are inactive (নিষ্ক্রিয়), idle (অলস), passive (প্যাসিভ), and dormant (সুপ্ত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Blend''?',
              ARRAY['Separate', 'Mix', 'Divide', 'Part'],
              1,
              '''Blend'' (মিশ্রিত করা) means to mix together. Its synonyms are mix (মেশানো), combine (একত্র করা), merge (একীভূত করা), and fuse (সংযুক্ত করা). Antonyms are separate (পৃথক করা), divide (ভাগ করা), part (আলাদা করা), and split (ভাগ করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Careful'' is:',
              ARRAY['Cautious', 'Watchful', 'Careless', 'Attentive'],
              2,
              '''Careful'' (সতর্ক) means taking care to avoid harm. Its synonyms are cautious (সতর্ক), watchful (সতর্ক), attentive (মনোযোগী), and prudent (বিবেচক). Its antonyms are careless (অসতর্ক), reckless (বেপরোয়া), negligent (অবহেলাকারী), and heedless (অমনোযোগী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Danger''?',
              ARRAY['Safety', 'Risk', 'Security', 'Protection'],
              1,
              '''Danger'' (বিপদ) means the possibility of harm. Its synonyms are risk (ঝুঁকি), peril (সংকট), hazard (বিপত্তি), and threat (হুমকি). Antonyms are safety (নিরাপত্তা), security (নিরাপত্তা), protection (সুরক্ষা), and certainty (নিশ্চয়তা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Easy'' is:',
              ARRAY['Simple', 'Difficult', 'Effortless', 'Light'],
              1,
              '''Easy'' (সহজ) means achieved without great effort. Its synonyms are simple (সরল), effortless (অনায়াস), light (হালকা), and uncomplicated (অজটিল). Its antonyms are difficult (কঠিন), hard (কঠিন), challenging (চ্যালেঞ্জিং), and arduous (দুরূহ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Foolish''?',
              ARRAY['Wise', 'Silly', 'Intelligent', 'Clever'],
              1,
              '''Foolish'' (মূর্খ) means lacking good sense. Its synonyms are silly (বোকা), stupid (মূর্খ), unwise (অবিবেচক), and absurd (অযৌক্তিক). Antonyms are wise (জ্ঞানী), intelligent (বুদ্ধিমান), clever (চতুর), and smart (চালাক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Generous'' is:',
              ARRAY['Charitable', 'Benevolent', 'Stingy', 'Magnanimous'],
              2,
              '''Generous'' (উদার) means showing readiness to give. Its synonyms are charitable (দানশীল), benevolent (সদাশয়), magnanimous (মহানুভব), and liberal (উদার). Its antonyms are stingy (কৃপণ), miserly (কৃপণ), selfish (স্বার্থপর), and greedy (লোভী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Hungry''?',
              ARRAY['Full', 'Starving', 'Satisfied', 'Stuffed'],
              1,
              '''Hungry'' (ক্ষুধার্ত) means feeling a need to eat. Its synonyms are starving (ক্ষুধার্ত), famished (ক্ষুধার্ত), ravenous (খিদে পাওয়া), and empty (খালি). Antonyms are full (ভরা), satisfied (সন্তুষ্ট), stuffed (ঠাসা), and sated (পরিতৃপ্ত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Interesting'' is:',
              ARRAY['Engaging', 'Fascinating', 'Boring', 'Captivating'],
              2,
              '''Interesting'' (আকর্ষণীয়) means arousing curiosity. Its synonyms are engaging (মনোরম), fascinating (মুগ্ধকর), captivating (চিত্তাকর্ষক), and intriguing (কৌতূহলোদ্দীপক). Its antonyms are boring (বিরক্তিকর), dull (নীরস), uninteresting (অরুচিকর), and tedious (ক্লান্তিকর).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Join''?',
              ARRAY['Separate', 'Connect', 'Detach', 'Divide'],
              1,
              '''Join'' (যোগদান করা) means to connect or link. Its synonyms are connect (সংযোগ করা), link (যুক্ত করা), attach (সংযুক্ত করা), and unite (একত্র করা). Antonyms are separate (পৃথক করা), detach (আলাদা করা), divide (ভাগ করা), and disconnect (সংযোগ বিচ্ছিন্ন করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Kind'' is:',
              ARRAY['Compassionate', 'Cruel', 'Gentle', 'Tender'],
              1,
              '''Kind'' (সদয়) means having a friendly nature. Its synonyms are compassionate (দয়ালু), gentle (মৃদু), tender (কোমল), and benevolent (সদাশয়). Its antonyms are cruel (নিষ্ঠুর), unkind (অদয়ালু), harsh (কঠোর), and mean (অর্থপূর্ণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Legal''?',
              ARRAY['Illegal', 'Lawful', 'Unlawful', 'Criminal'],
              1,
              '''Legal'' (আইনি) means permitted by law. Its synonyms are lawful (বৈধ), legitimate (বৈধ), permissible (অনুমোদিত), and authorized (অনুমোদিত). Antonyms are illegal (অবৈধ), unlawful (অবৈধ), criminal (অপরাধী), and prohibited (নিষিদ্ধ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Maximum'' is:',
              ARRAY['Greatest', 'Minimum', 'Supreme', 'Utmost'],
              1,
              '''Maximum'' (সর্বোচ্চ) means the greatest possible. Its synonyms are greatest (সর্বশ্রেষ্ঠ), supreme (সর্বোচ্চ), utmost (চরম), and topmost (সর্বোচ্চ). Its antonyms are minimum (সর্বনিম্ন), least (সর্বনিম্ন), lowest (সর্বনিম্ন), and smallest (ছোট).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Necessary''?',
              ARRAY['Optional', 'Essential', 'Unimportant', 'Voluntary'],
              1,
              '''Necessary'' (প্রয়োজনীয়) means required. Its synonyms are essential (অপরিহার্য), vital (অত্যাবশ্যক), indispensable (অনিবার্য), and required (প্রয়োজনীয়). Antonyms are optional (ঐচ্ছিক), unnecessary (অপ্রয়োজনীয়), unimportant (অগুরুত্বপূর্ণ), and voluntary (স্বেচ্ছায়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Often'' is:',
              ARRAY['Frequently', 'Seldom', 'Regularly', 'Usually'],
              1,
              '''Often'' (প্রায়ই) means frequently. Its synonyms are frequently (ঘন ঘন), regularly (নিয়মিত), usually (সাধারণত), and repeatedly (পুনঃপুন)। Its antonyms are seldom (কদাচিৎ), rarely (বিরল), occasionally (মাঝে মধ্যে), and infrequently (অস্বাভাবিকভাবে).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Power''?',
              ARRAY['Weakness', 'Strength', 'Impotence', 'Inability'],
              1,
              '''Power'' (ক্ষমতা) means ability to do something. Its synonyms are strength (শক্তি), force (বল), energy (শক্তি), and might (পরাক্রম). Antonyms are weakness (দুর্বলতা), impotence (অক্ষমতা), inability (অক্ষমতা), and powerlessness (ক্ষমতাহীনতা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Quality'' is:',
              ARRAY['Standard', 'Defect', 'Merit', 'Virtue'],
              1,
              '''Quality'' (গুণ) means a distinctive attribute. Its synonyms are standard (মান), merit (যোগ্যতা), virtue (সদগুণ), and excellence (উৎকর্ষ). Its antonyms are defect (ত্রুটি), flaw (খুঁত), fault (দোষ), and imperfection (অসম্পূর্ণতা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Rich''?',
              ARRAY['Poor', 'Affluent', 'Needy', 'Destitute'],
              1,
              '''Rich'' (ধনী) means having great wealth. Its synonyms are affluent (সমৃদ্ধ), wealthy (ধনী), prosperous (উন্নতিশীল), and opulent (বিলাসবহুল). Antonyms are poor (দরিদ্র), needy (অভাবী), destitute (নিঃস্ব), and impoverished (দরিদ্র).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Sorrow'' is:',
              ARRAY['Grief', 'Joy', 'Sadness', 'Misery'],
              1,
              '''Sorrow'' (দুঃখ) means deep distress. Its synonyms are grief (শোক), sadness (দুঃখ), misery (দুর্দশা), and woe (শোক). Its antonyms are joy (আনন্দ), happiness (সুখ), delight (পরমানন্দ), and pleasure (আনন্দ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Tired''?',
              ARRAY['Energetic', 'Exhausted', 'Fresh', 'Lively'],
              1,
              '''Tired'' (ক্লান্ত) means in need of rest. Its synonyms are exhausted (ক্লান্ত), fatigued (শ্রান্ত), weary (ক্লান্ত), and drained (নিঃশেষিত). Antonyms are energetic (উদ্যমী), fresh (তাজা), lively (প্রাণবন্ত), and active (সক্রিয়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Up'' is:',
              ARRAY['Above', 'Down', 'High', 'Over'],
              1,
              '''Up'' (উপরে) means towards a higher position. Its synonyms are upward (ঊর্ধ্বগামী), higher (উচ্চতর), above (উপরে), and overhead (উপরে). Its antonyms are down (নিচে), downward (নিম্নগামী), below (নীচে), and beneath (নিম্নে).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Adhere''?',
              ARRAY['Detach', 'Separate', 'Stick', 'Loosen'],
              2,
              '''Adhere'' (মেনে চলা/আঁকড়ে থাকা) means to stick firmly. Its synonyms are stick (আটকে থাকা), cling (জড়িয়ে ধরা), comply (মেনে চলা), and follow (অনুসরণ করা). Antonyms are detach (আলাদা করা), separate (পৃথক করা), loosen (ঢিলা করা), and unfasten (খুলে ফেলা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Bitter'' is:',
              ARRAY['Sour', 'Sweet', 'Harsh', 'Acrid'],
              1,
              '''Bitter'' (তিক্ত) means having a sharp taste. Its synonyms are sour (টক), harsh (কঠোর), acrid (উগ্র), and sharp (তীক্ষ্ণ). Its antonyms are sweet (মিষ্টি), pleasant (আনন্দদায়ক), mild (মৃদু), and kind (সদয়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Compel''?',
              ARRAY['Allow', 'Force', 'Permit', 'Encourage'],
              1,
              '''Compel'' (বাধ্য করা) means to force someone to do something. Its synonyms are force (বাধ্য করা), oblige (বাধিত করা), coerce (প্রত্যয় করা), and drive (চালিত করা). Antonyms are allow (অনুমতি দেওয়া), permit (অনুমতি দেওয়া), encourage (উৎসাহিত করা), and persuade (প্ররোচিত করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Deep'' is:',
              ARRAY['Profound', 'Shallow', 'Bottomless', 'Intense'],
              1,
              '''Deep'' (গভীর) means extending far down. Its synonyms are profound (গভীর), bottomless (অতল), intense (তীব্র), and abyssal (গভীর সমুদ্রের). Its antonyms are shallow (অগভীর), superficial (উপরিভাগের), surface (পৃষ্ঠতলের), and flat (সমতল).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Earnest''?',
              ARRAY['Frivolous', 'Sincere', 'Trivial', 'Casual'],
              1,
              '''Earnest'' (গম্ভীর/আন্তরিক) means showing sincere conviction. Its synonyms are sincere (আন্তরিক), serious (গুরুতর), solemn (গম্ভীর), and heartfelt (হৃদয়গ্রাহী). Antonyms are frivolous (অসার), trivial (তুচ্ছ), casual (অনিয়মিত), and insincere (অকৃত্রিম নয়)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Faint'' is:',
              ARRAY['Weak', 'Dim', 'Strong', 'Pale'],
              2,
              '''Faint'' (ম্লান/দুর্বল) means barely perceptible or weak. Its synonyms are weak (দুর্বল), dim (অস্পষ্ট), pale (ফ্যাকাশে), and vague (অস্পষ্ট). Its antonyms are strong (শক্তিশালী), clear (পরিষ্কার), bright (উজ্জ্বল), and distinct (স্বতন্ত্র).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Gratify''?',
              ARRAY['Displease', 'Please', 'Annoy', 'Irritate'],
              1,
              '''Gratify'' (সন্তুষ্ট করা) means to give pleasure. Its synonyms are please (সন্তুষ্ট করা), delight (আনন্দ দেওয়া), satisfy (তৃপ্ত করা), and content (সন্তুষ্ট করা). Antonyms are displease (অসন্তুষ্ট করা), annoy (বিরক্ত করা), irritate (জ্বালাতন করা), and vex (রাগানো)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Harmony'' is:',
              ARRAY['Peace', 'Conflict', 'Unity', 'Concord'],
              1,
              '''Harmony'' (সম্প্রীতি) means agreement or concord. Its synonyms are peace (শান্তি), unity (ঐক্য), concord (সমঝোতা), and accord (চুক্তি). Its antonyms are conflict (দ্বন্দ্ব), discord (কলহ), disagreement (অমিল), and strife (বিবাদ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Imitate''?',
              ARRAY['Create', 'Copy', 'Originate', 'Invent'],
              1,
              '''Imitate'' (অনুকরণ করা) means to copy someone or something. Its synonyms are copy (অনুলিপি করা), mimic (নকল করা), emulate (অনুসরণ করা), and ape (অনুকরণ করা)। Antonyms are create (সৃষ্টি করা), originate (উদ্ভাবন করা), invent (আবিষ্কার করা), and innovate (নতুনত্ব আনা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Junior'' is:',
              ARRAY['Younger', 'Senior', 'Inferior', 'Subordinate'],
              1,
              '''Junior'' (কনিষ্ঠ) means younger or lower in rank. Its synonyms are younger (ছোট), inferior (নিম্ন), subordinate (অধস্তন), and lesser (কম)। Its antonyms are senior (বরিষ্ঠ), older (বড়), superior (উচ্চতর), and major (প্রধান)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Keen''?',
              ARRAY['Dull', 'Sharp', 'Blunt', 'Obtuse'],
              1,
              '''Keen'' (তীক্ষ্ণ/আগ্রহী) means having a sharp edge or great interest. Its synonyms are sharp (তীক্ষ্ণ), eager (আগ্রহী), enthusiastic (উৎসাহী), and acute (গভীর)। Antonyms are dull (ভোঁতা), blunt (ভোঁতা), apathetic (উদাসীন), and indifferent (নিরপেক্ষ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Lament'' is:',
              ARRAY['Mourn', 'Rejoice', 'Grieve', 'Weep'],
              1,
              '''Lament'' (বিলাপ করা) means to express sorrow. Its synonyms are mourn (শোক করা), grieve (দুঃখ করা), weep (কান্না করা), and wail (বিলাপ করা)। Its antonyms are rejoice (আনন্দ করা), celebrate (উদযাপন করা), cheer (উল্লাস করা), and delight (আনন্দিত হওয়া)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Mysterious''?',
              ARRAY['Clear', 'Puzzling', 'Obvious', 'Plain'],
              1,
              '''Mysterious'' (রহস্যময়) means difficult to understand. Its synonyms are puzzling (ধাঁধাঁযুক্ত), enigmatic (হেঁয়ালিপূর্ণ), cryptic (গোপন), and baffling (বিভ্রান্তিকর)। Antonyms are clear (পরিষ্কার), obvious (সুস্পষ্ট), plain (সরল), and understandable (বোধগম্য)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Notable'' is:',
              ARRAY['Prominent', 'Insignificant', 'Eminent', 'Distinguished'],
              1,
              '''Notable'' (উল্লেখযোগ্য) means worthy of attention. Its synonyms are prominent (প্রধান), eminent (বিশিষ্ট), distinguished (বিশিষ্ট), and remarkable (অসাধারণ)। Its antonyms are insignificant (নগণ্য), unknown (অজানা), obscure (অস্পষ্ট), and ordinary (সাধারণ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Obtain''?',
              ARRAY['Lose', 'Get', 'Forfeit', 'Relinquish'],
              1,
              '''Obtain'' (অর্জন করা) means to get something. Its synonyms are get (পাওয়া), acquire (অর্জন করা), gain (লাভ করা), and secure (নিরাপদ করা)। Antonyms are lose (হারানো), forfeit (বাজেয়াপ্ত করা), relinquish (ত্যাগ করা), and surrender (সমর্পণ করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Partial'' is:',
              ARRAY['Biased', 'Impartial', 'Prejudiced', 'One-sided'],
              1,
              '''Partial'' (পক্ষপাতদুষ্ট) means favoring one side. Its synonyms are biased (পক্ষপাতী), prejudiced (পূর্বধারণাপ্রবণ), one-sided (একপেশে), and unfair (অন্যায়)। Its antonyms are impartial (নিরপেক্ষ), unbiased (অপক্ষপাত), fair (ন্যায্য), and neutral (নিরপেক্ষ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Quake''?',
              ARRAY['Shake', 'Stabilize', 'Steady', 'Calm'],
              0,
              '''Quake'' (কাঁপানো) means to shake or tremble. Its synonyms are shake (কাঁপানো), tremble (কম্পিত হওয়া), shudder (শিউরে ওঠা), and vibrate (স্পন্দিত হওয়া)। Antonyms are stabilize (স্থিতিশীল করা), steady (স্থির করা), calm (শান্ত করা), and soothe (প্রশমিত করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Rough'' is:',
              ARRAY['Coarse', 'Smooth', 'Uneven', 'Harsh'],
              1,
              '''Rough'' (রুক্ষ) means having an uneven surface. Its synonyms are coarse (মোটা), uneven (অসম), harsh (কর্কশ), and bumpy (উঁচু-নিচু)। Its antonyms are smooth (মসৃণ), even (সমতল), flat (সমতল), and polished (মসৃণ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Scarce''?',
              ARRAY['Rare', 'Plentiful', 'Abundant', 'Ample'],
              0,
              '''Scarce'' (দুর্লভ) means in short supply. Its synonyms are rare (বিরল), limited (সীমিত), insufficient (অপর্যাপ্ত), and scanty (স্বল্প)। Antonyms are plentiful (প্রচুর), abundant (প্রচুর), ample (যথেষ্ট), and copious (প্রচুর)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Tame'' is:',
              ARRAY['Domestic', 'Wild', 'Gentle', 'Docile'],
              1,
              '''Tame'' (পোষা/নম্র) means domesticated or gentle. Its synonyms are domestic (গৃহপালিত), gentle (মৃদু), docile (বশ্য), and meek (নম্র)। Its antonyms are wild (বন্য), untamed (অদম্য), fierce (হিংস্র), and savage (বর্বর)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Urgent''?',
              ARRAY['Pressing', 'Trivial', 'Unimportant', 'Optional'],
              0,
              '''Urgent'' (জরুরি) means requiring immediate action. Its synonyms are pressing (জরুরি), critical (সংকটপূর্ণ), imperative (অত্যাবশ্যক), and crucial (গুরুত্বপূর্ণ)। Antonyms are trivial (তুচ্ছ), unimportant (অগুরুত্বপূর্ণ), optional (ঐচ্ছিক), and unnecessary (অপ্রয়োজনীয়)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Vague'' is:',
              ARRAY['Clear', 'Hazy', 'Faint', 'Obscure'],
              0,
              '''Vague'' (অস্পষ্ট) means uncertain or unclear. Its synonyms are hazy (ঝাপসা), faint (ম্লান), obscure (অস্পষ্ট), and indefinite (অনির্দিষ্ট)। Its antonyms are clear (পরিষ্কার), definite (নির্দিষ্ট), explicit (স্পষ্ট), and precise (সঠিক)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Wary''?',
              ARRAY['Careless', 'Cautious', 'Reckless', 'Rash'],
              1,
              '''Wary'' (সতর্ক) means feeling caution about possible dangers. Its synonyms are cautious (সতর্ক), careful (সতর্ক), vigilant (জাগ্রত), and alert (সতর্ক)। Antonyms are careless (অসতর্ক), reckless (বেপরোয়া), rash (অবিবেচক), and heedless (অমনোযোগী)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Young'' is:',
              ARRAY['Youthful', 'Old', 'Juvenile', 'Infant'],
              1,
              '''Young'' (তরুণ) means having lived for a short time. Its synonyms are youthful (তরুণ), juvenile (কিশোর), infant (শিশু), and adolescent (কৈশোরের)। Its antonyms are old (বৃদ্ধ), aged (বয়স্ক), elderly (প্রবীণ), and ancient (প্রাচীন)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Zealous''?',
              ARRAY['Apathetic', 'Enthusiastic', 'Indifferent', 'Uninterested'],
              1,
              '''Zealous'' (উদ্যমী) means having great energy or enthusiasm. Its synonyms are enthusiastic (উৎসাহী), passionate (আবেগী), fervent (উদ্দীপ্ত), and eager (আগ্রহী)। Antonyms are apathetic (উদাসীন), indifferent (নিরপেক্ষ), uninterested (অরুচি), and lukewarm (ঔদাসীন্য)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Absent'' is:',
              ARRAY['Missing', 'Present', 'Away', 'Gone'],
              1,
              '''Absent'' (অনুপস্থিত) means not present. Its synonyms are missing (অনুপস্থিত), away (দূরে), gone (চলে গেছে), and lacking (অভাব)। Its antonyms are present (উপস্থিত), here (এখানে), attending (উপস্থিত), and existing (বিদ্যমান)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Barrier''?',
              ARRAY['Obstacle', 'Passage', 'Pathway', 'Opening'],
              0,
              '''Barrier'' (বাধা) means something that blocks progress. Its synonyms are obstacle (বাধা), hindrance (বাধা), impediment (প্রতিবন্ধক), and blockade (অবরোধ)। Antonyms are passage (পথ), pathway (পথ), opening (খোলা), and gateway (দরজা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Combine'' is:',
              ARRAY['Merge', 'Separate', 'Unite', 'Join'],
              1,
              '''Combine'' (একত্র করা) means to join together. Its synonyms are merge (একীভূত করা), unite (একত্র করা), join (যোগ দেওয়া), and blend (মেশানো)। Its antonyms are separate (পৃথক করা), divide (ভাগ করা), part (আলাদা করা), and split (ফাটল)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Deliberate''?',
              ARRAY['Accidental', 'Intentional', 'Unplanned', 'Spontaneous'],
              1,
              '''Deliberate'' (ইচ্ছাকৃত) means done consciously and intentionally. Its synonyms are intentional (ইচ্ছাকৃত), purposeful (উদ্দেশ্যমূলক), premeditated (পূর্বপরিকল্পিত), and willful (ইচ্ছাকৃত)। Antonyms are accidental (আকস্মিক), unplanned (অপরিকল্পিত), spontaneous (স্বতঃস্ফূর্ত), and unintentional (অনিচ্ছাকৃত)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Export'' is:',
              ARRAY['Sell abroad', 'Import', 'Ship', 'Trade'],
              1,
              '''Export'' (রপ্তানি করা) means to send goods to another country for sale. Its synonyms are sell abroad (বিদেশে বিক্রি করা), ship (পাঠানো), and trade (বাণিজ্য করা)। Its antonyms are import (আমদানি করা), bring in (আনা), and buy abroad (বিদেশ থেকে কেনা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Fragrant''?',
              ARRAY['Smelly', 'Aromatic', 'Stinking', 'Foul'],
              1,
              '''Fragrant'' (সুগন্ধি) means having a pleasant smell. Its synonyms are aromatic (সুগন্ধি), perfumed (সুগন্ধিযুক্ত), sweet-smelling (মিষ্টি গন্ধ), and scented (সুবাসিত)। Antonyms are smelly (দুর্গন্ধযুক্ত), stinking (দুর্গন্ধযুক্ত), foul (নোংরা), and putrid (পচা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Gather'' is:',
              ARRAY['Collect', 'Scatter', 'Assemble', 'Accumulate'],
              1,
              '''Gather'' (একত্র করা) means to bring together. Its synonyms are collect (সংগ্রহ করা), assemble (জড়ো করা), accumulate (পুঞ্জীভূত করা), and congregate (সমবেত হওয়া)। Its antonyms are scatter (ছড়ানো), disperse (বিচ্ছুরিত করা), spread (প্রসারিত করা), and distribute (বিতরণ করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Hazard''?',
              ARRAY['Safety', 'Danger', 'Protection', 'Security'],
              1,
              '''Hazard'' (ঝুঁকি) means a danger or risk. Its synonyms are danger (বিপদ), risk (ঝুঁকি), peril (সংকট), and threat (হুমকি)। Antonyms are safety (নিরাপত্তা), security (নিরাপত্তা), protection (সুরক্ষা), and certainty (নিশ্চয়তা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Innocent'' is:',
              ARRAY['Guilty', 'Pure', 'Virtuous', 'Sinless'],
              0,
              '''Innocent'' (নির্দোষ) means not guilty. Its synonyms are pure (শুদ্ধ), virtuous (সৎ), sinless (পাপহীন), and blameless (নিরপরাধ)। Its antonyms are guilty (দোষী), culpable (অপরাধী), sinful (পাপী), and corrupt (দুর্নীতিগ্রস্ত)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Jealous''?',
              ARRAY['Envious', 'Trusting', 'Content', 'Secure'],
              0,
              '''Jealous'' (ঈর্ষান্বিত) means feeling envy. Its synonyms are envious (ঈর্ষান্বিত), covetous (লোলুপ), resentful (ক্ষুব্ধ), and begrudging (অসন্তুষ্ট)। Antonyms are trusting (বিশ্বাসী), content (সন্তুষ্ট), secure (নিরাপদ), and satisfied (তৃপ্ত)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Knowledge'' is:',
              ARRAY['Wisdom', 'Ignorance', 'Understanding', 'Awareness'],
              1,
              '''Knowledge'' (জ্ঞান) means facts and information acquired. Its synonyms are wisdom (প্রজ্ঞা), understanding (বোধ), awareness (সচেতনতা), and erudition (পাণ্ডিত্য)। Its antonyms are ignorance (অজ্ঞতা), illiteracy (নিরক্ষরতা), unawareness (অজ্ঞানতা), and folly (মূর্খতা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Laborious''?',
              ARRAY['Easy', 'Effortless', 'Arduous', 'Simple'],
              2,
              '''Laborious'' (পরিশ্রমসাধ্য) means requiring great effort. Its synonyms are arduous (কষ্টসাধ্য), difficult (কঠিন), strenuous (ক্লান্তিকর), and tough (কঠিন)। Antonyms are easy (সহজ), effortless (অনায়াস), simple (সরল), and light (হালকা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Major'' is:',
              ARRAY['Main', 'Minor', 'Chief', 'Principal'],
              1,
              '''Major'' (প্রধান) means important or significant. Its synonyms are main (প্রধান), chief (প্রধান), principal (প্রধান), and leading (প্রধান)। Its antonyms are minor (গৌণ), insignificant (নগণ্য), unimportant (অগুরুত্বপূর্ণ), and secondary (দ্বিতীয়)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Native''?',
              ARRAY['Foreign', 'Indigenous', 'Alien', 'Immigrant'],
              1,
              '''Native'' (স্থানীয়) means belonging to a particular place by birth. Its synonyms are indigenous (আদিবাসী), local (স্থানীয়), domestic (দেশীয়), and original (আদি)। Antonyms are foreign (বিদেশী), alien (বিদেশী), immigrant (অভিবাসী), and exotic (বিদেশী)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Optimistic'' is:',
              ARRAY['Hopeful', 'Pessimistic', 'Positive', 'Cheerful'],
              1,
              '''Optimistic'' (আশাবাদী) means hopeful about the future. Its synonyms are hopeful (আশাবাদী), positive (ইতিবাচক), cheerful (প্রফুল্ল), and confident (আত্মবিশ্বাসী)। Its antonyms are pessimistic (হতাশাবাদী), negative (নেতিবাচক), gloomy (বিষণ্ণ), and cynical (বিদ্রূপকারী)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Praise''?',
              ARRAY['Criticize', 'Commend', 'Blame', 'Condemn'],
              1,
              '''Praise'' (প্রশংসা করা) means to express approval. Its synonyms are commend (প্রশংসা করা), applaud (সাধুবাদ জানানো), compliment (প্রশংসা করা), and acclaim (প্রশংসা করা)। Antonyms are criticize (সমালোচনা করা), blame (দোষারোপ করা), condemn (নিন্দা করা), and disparage (অবমূল্যায়ন করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Qualified'' is:',
              ARRAY['Competent', 'Unqualified', 'Capable', 'Skilled'],
              1,
              '''Qualified'' (যোগ্য) means having the necessary skills. Its synonyms are competent (সক্ষম), capable (যোগ্য), skilled (দক্ষ), and trained (প্রশিক্ষিত)। Its antonyms are unqualified (অযোগ্য), incompetent (অক্ষম), unfit (অনুপযুক্ত), and incapable (অক্ষম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Rival''?',
              ARRAY['Ally', 'Competitor', 'Friend', 'Partner'],
              1,
              '''Rival'' (প্রতিদ্বন্দ্বী) means a person competing with another. Its synonyms are competitor (প্রতিযোগী), opponent (প্রতিপক্ষ), adversary (শত্রু), and challenger (প্রতিদ্বন্দ্বী)। Antonyms are ally (মিত্র), friend (বন্ধু), partner (অংশীদার), and supporter (সমর্থক)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Strict'' is:',
              ARRAY['Lenient', 'Harsh', 'Rigid', 'Severe'],
              0,
              '''Strict'' (কঠোর) means demanding that rules are obeyed. Its synonyms are harsh (কঠোর), rigid (অনমনীয়), severe (কঠোর), and stern (কঠোর)। Its antonyms are lenient (শিথিল), flexible (নমনীয়), gentle (মৃদু), and tolerant (সহনশীল)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Timid''?',
              ARRAY['Bold', 'Shy', 'Brave', 'Fearless'],
              1,
              '''Timid'' (ভীরু) means showing a lack of courage. Its synonyms are shy (লাজুক), fearful (ভীত), cowardly (কাপুরুষ), and hesitant (দ্বিধাগ্রস্ত)। Antonyms are bold (সাহসী), brave (সাহসী), fearless (নির্ভীক), and confident (আত্মবিশ্বাসী)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Urban'' is:',
              ARRAY['City', 'Rural', 'Metropolitan', 'Municipal'],
              1,
              '''Urban'' (শহুরে) means relating to a city. Its synonyms are city (শহর), metropolitan (মহানগরীয়), municipal (পৌর), and civic (নাগরিক)। Its antonyms are rural (গ্রামীণ), country (গ্রাম), pastoral (পল্লী), and rustic (গ্রাম্য)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Vacant''?',
              ARRAY['Occupied', 'Empty', 'Filled', 'Engaged'],
              1,
              '''Vacant'' (খালি) means not occupied. Its synonyms are empty (খালি), unoccupied (অধিকৃত নয়), void (শূন্য), and available (উপলব্ধ)। Antonyms are occupied (অধিকৃত), filled (পূর্ণ), engaged (ব্যবহৃত), and taken (গ্রহণ করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Wealth'' is:',
              ARRAY['Poverty', 'Fortune', 'Prosperity', 'Affluence'],
              0,
              '''Wealth'' (সম্পদ) means abundance of valuable possessions. Its synonyms are fortune (ভাগ্য), prosperity (সমৃদ্ধি), affluence (প্রাচুর্য), and riches (ধন-সম্পদ)। Its antonyms are poverty (দারিদ্র্য), destitution (নিঃস্বতা), need (অভাব), and want (অভাব)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Yield''?',
              ARRAY['Resist', 'Surrender', 'Oppose', 'Withstand'],
              1,
              '''Yield'' (আত্মসমর্পণ করা/উৎপাদন করা) can mean to surrender or produce. Its synonyms for surrender are surrender (আত্মসমর্পণ করা), submit (বশ্যতা স্বীকার করা), capitulate (আত্মসমর্পণ করা), and succumb (পরাস্ত হওয়া)। Antonyms are resist (প্রতিরোধ করা), oppose (বিরোধিতা করা), withstand (সহ্য করা), and fight (লড়াই করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Zenith'' is:',
              ARRAY['Peak', 'Nadir', 'Summit', 'Apex'],
              1,
              '''Zenith'' (চরম শিখর) means the highest point. Its synonyms are peak (শিখর), summit (চূড়া), apex (অগ্রভাগ), and climax (চরম বিন্দু)। Its antonym is nadir (নিম্নতম বিন্দু), meaning the lowest point.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Abrupt''?',
              ARRAY['Gradual', 'Sudden', 'Expected', 'Slow'],
              1,
              '''Abrupt'' (হঠাৎ) means sudden and unexpected. Its synonyms are sudden (আকস্মিক), unexpected (অপ্রত্যাশিত), hasty (তড়িঘড়ি), and rash (অবিবেচক). Antonyms are gradual (ধীরে ধীরে), slow (ধীর), expected (প্রত্যাশিত), and planned (পরিকল্পিত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Beneficial'' is:',
              ARRAY['Advantageous', 'Harmful', 'Helpful', 'Useful'],
              1,
              '''Beneficial'' (উপকারী) means favorable or advantageous. Its synonyms are advantageous (সুবিধাজনক), helpful (সহায়ক), useful (প্রয়োজনীয়), and profitable (লাভজনক). Its antonyms are harmful (ক্ষতিকর), damaging (ক্ষতিকর), detrimental (ক্ষতিকর), and injurious (আঘাতমূলক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Cease''?',
              ARRAY['Begin', 'Stop', 'Start', 'Commence'],
              1,
              '''Cease'' (বন্ধ করা) means to bring or come to an end. Its synonyms are stop (থামানো), halt (বিরাম দেওয়া), discontinue (বন্ধ করা), and terminate (শেষ করা). Antonyms are begin (শুরু করা), start (শুরু করা), commence (শুরু করা), and continue (চালিয়ে যাওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Dense'' is:',
              ARRAY['Thick', 'Sparse', 'Compact', 'Crowded'],
              1,
              '''Dense'' (ঘন) means closely compacted together. Its synonyms are thick (ঘন), compact (সংক্ষিপ্ত), crowded (ভিড়), and solid (কঠিন). Its antonyms are sparse (বিরল), thin (পাতলা), scattered (ছড়িয়ে ছিটিয়ে), and open (খোলা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Explicit''?',
              ARRAY['Vague', 'Clear', 'Ambiguous', 'Unclear'],
              1,
              '''Explicit'' (স্পষ্ট) means stated clearly and in detail. Its synonyms are clear (পরিষ্কার), definite (নির্দিষ্ট), precise (সঠিক), and unambiguous (দ্ব্যর্থহীন). Antonyms are vague (অস্পষ্ট), ambiguous (দ্ব্যর্থক), unclear (অস্পষ্ট), and implicit (পরোক্ষ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Frequent'' is:',
              ARRAY['Common', 'Rare', 'Regular', 'Usual'],
              1,
              '''Frequent'' (ঘন ঘন) means occurring often. Its synonyms are common (সাধারণ), regular (নিয়মিত), repeated (পুনরাবৃত্ত), and usual (স্বাভাবিক). Its antonyms are rare (বিরল), infrequent (অস্বাভাবিক), uncommon (অসাধারণ), and occasional (মাঝে মধ্যে).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Gigantic''?',
              ARRAY['Tiny', 'Huge', 'Small', 'Miniature'],
              1,
              '''Gigantic'' (দৈত্যাকার) means of very great size. Its synonyms are huge (বিশাল), enormous (প্রচণ্ড), colossal (বৃহদাকার), and immense (বিরাট). Antonyms are tiny (ক্ষুদ্র), small (ছোট), miniature (অতিক্ষুদ্র), and minute (অণুবীক্ষণিক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Humid'' is:',
              ARRAY['Moist', 'Dry', 'Damp', 'Wet'],
              1,
              '''Humid'' (আর্দ্র) means marked by a high level of water vapor. Its synonyms are moist (স্যাঁতসেঁতে), damp (ভিজে), wet (ভিজা), and muggy (গরম ও আর্দ্র). Its antonyms are dry (শুষ্ক), arid (শুষ্ক), dehydrated (নিরুদন), and parched (শুষ্ক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Illiterate''?',
              ARRAY['Educated', 'Uneducated', 'Learned', 'Scholarly'],
              1,
              '''Illiterate'' (অশিক্ষিত) means unable to read or write. Its synonyms are uneducated (অশিক্ষিত), ignorant (অজ্ঞ), unlearned (অপণ্ডিত), and unschooled (অপ্রশিক্ষিত). Antonyms are educated (শিক্ষিত), literate (সাক্ষর), learned (পণ্ডিত), and scholarly (পাণ্ডিত্যপূর্ণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Joyful'' is:',
              ARRAY['Happy', 'Sad', 'Delighted', 'Cheerful'],
              1,
              '''Joyful'' (আনন্দিত) means feeling great pleasure. Its synonyms are happy (সুখী), delighted (আনন্দিত), cheerful (প্রফুল্ল), and elated (উল্লসিত). Its antonyms are sad (দুঃখিত), sorrowful (শোকাহত), gloomy (বিষণ্ণ), and miserable (দুঃখী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Kindred''?',
              ARRAY['Alien', 'Related', 'Stranger', 'Foreign'],
              1,
              '''Kindred'' (আত্মীয়/সম্পর্কিত) means similar in kind or related. Its synonyms are related (সম্পর্কিত), akin (সমগোত্রীয়), similar (অনুরূপ), and allied (মিত্র). Antonyms are alien (বিদেশী), foreign (বিদেশী), different (ভিন্ন), and unrelated (অসম্পর্কিত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Liquid'' is:',
              ARRAY['Fluid', 'Solid', 'Watery', 'Molten'],
              1,
              '''Liquid'' (তরল) means flowing freely like water. Its synonyms are fluid (তরল), watery (জলের মতো), molten (গলিত), and runny (তরল). Its antonyms are solid (কঠিন), hard (শক্ত), firm (দৃঢ়), and rigid (অনমনীয়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Mild''?',
              ARRAY['Gentle', 'Harsh', 'Severe', 'Strict'],
              0,
              '''Mild'' (মৃদু) means gentle and not severe. Its synonyms are gentle (মৃদু), soft (নরম), calm (শান্ত), and moderate (মাঝারি). Antonyms are harsh (কঠোর), severe (কঠিন), strict (কঠোর), and intense (তীব্র).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Natural'' is:',
              ARRAY['Normal', 'Artificial', 'Usual', 'Common'],
              1,
              '''Natural'' (প্রাকৃতিক) means existing in or caused by nature. Its synonyms are normal (স্বাভাবিক), usual (সাধারণ), common (সাধারণ), and regular (নিয়মিত). Its antonyms are artificial (কৃত্রিম), unnatural (অস্বাভাবিক), synthetic (কৃত্রিম), and man-made (মানবসৃষ্ট).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Obscure''?',
              ARRAY['Famous', 'Unknown', 'Prominent', 'Renowned'],
              1,
              '''Obscure'' (অস্পষ্ট/অখ্যাত) means not discovered or known about. Its synonyms are unknown (অজানা), unclear (অস্পষ্ট), vague (অস্পষ্ট), and hidden (লুকানো). Antonyms are famous (বিখ্যাত), prominent (প্রধান), renowned (সুপ্রসিদ্ধ), and celebrated (প্রখ্যাত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Permanent'' is:',
              ARRAY['Everlasting', 'Temporary', 'Perpetual', 'Constant'],
              1,
              '''Permanent'' (স্থায়ী) means lasting for a long time. Its synonyms are everlasting (চিরস্থায়ী), perpetual (অবিরাম), constant (অপরিবর্তনীয়), and enduring (টেকসই). Its antonyms are temporary (অস্থায়ী), transient (ক্ষণস্থায়ী), momentary (ক্ষণস্থায়ী), and short-lived (স্বল্পস্থায়ী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Quiet''?',
              ARRAY['Noisy', 'Silent', 'Loud', 'Boisterous'],
              1,
              '''Quiet'' (শান্ত/নীরব) means making little noise. Its synonyms are silent (নীরব), calm (শান্ত), peaceful (শান্তিপূর্ণ), and still (স্থির). Antonyms are noisy (কোলাহলপূর্ণ), loud (উচ্চৈঃস্বরে), boisterous (উদ্বেল), and turbulent (অস্থির).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Regular'' is:',
              ARRAY['Normal', 'Irregular', 'Standard', 'Usual'],
              1,
              '''Regular'' (নিয়মিত) means following a pattern. Its synonyms are normal (স্বাভাবিক), standard (মান), usual (সাধারণ), and routine (রুটিন)। Its antonyms are irregular (অনিয়মিত), abnormal (অস্বাভাবিক), unusual (অসাধারণ), and inconsistent (অসংগত)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Savage''?',
              ARRAY['Wild', 'Tame', 'Gentle', 'Civilized'],
              0,
              '''Savage'' (বর্বর/হিংস্র) means fierce and violent. Its synonyms are wild (বন্য), brutal (নিষ্ঠুর), fierce (হিংস্র), and barbaric (বর্বরোচিত). Antonyms are tame (পোষা), gentle (মৃদু), civilized (সভ্য), and kind (সদয়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Thick'' is:',
              ARRAY['Dense', 'Thin', 'Heavy', 'Fat'],
              1,
              '''Thick'' (ঘন/মোটা) means with opposite sides close together. Its synonyms are dense (ঘন), heavy (ভারী), fat (স্থূল), and bulky (বিশাল)। Its antonyms are thin (পাতলা), slender (ক্ষীণ), slim (চিকন), and narrow (সংকীর্ণ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Urgent''?',
              ARRAY['Pressing', 'Unimportant', 'Trivial', 'Minor'],
              0,
              '''Urgent'' (জরুরি) means requiring immediate action. Its synonyms are pressing (জরুরি), critical (সংকটপূর্ণ), imperative (অত্যাবশ্যক), and crucial (গুরুত্বপূর্ণ)। Antonyms are unimportant (অগুরুত্বপূর্ণ), trivial (তুচ্ছ), minor (গৌণ), and optional (ঐচ্ছিক)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Voluntary'' is:',
              ARRAY['Optional', 'Compulsory', 'Willing', 'Free'],
              1,
              '''Voluntary'' (স্বেচ্ছায়) means done by choice. Its synonyms are optional (ঐচ্ছিক), willing (ইচ্ছুক), free (স্বাধীন), and spontaneous (স্বতঃস্ফূর্ত). Its antonyms are compulsory (বাধ্যতামূলক), mandatory (বাধ্যতামূলক), forced (জোরপূর্বক), and involuntary (অনিচ্ছাকৃত)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Wise''?',
              ARRAY['Foolish', 'Intelligent', 'Silly', 'Stupid'],
              1,
              '''Wise'' (জ্ঞানী) means having experience and good judgment. Its synonyms are intelligent (বুদ্ধিমান), clever (চতুর), smart (চালাক), and sagacious (বিচক্ষণ). Antonyms are foolish (মূর্খ), stupid (মূর্খ), silly (বোকা), and unwise (অবিবেচক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Young'' is:',
              ARRAY['Youthful', 'Old', 'Juvenile', 'Infant'],
              1,
              '''Young'' (তরুণ) means having lived for a short time. Its synonyms are youthful (তরুণ), juvenile (কিশোর), infant (শিশু), and adolescent (কৈশোরের)। Its antonyms are old (বৃদ্ধ), aged (বয়স্ক), elderly (প্রবীণ), and ancient (প্রাচীন)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Zeal''?',
              ARRAY['Apathy', 'Enthusiasm', 'Indifference', 'Lethargy'],
              1,
              '''Zeal'' (আগ্রহ/উদ্দীপনা) means great energy in pursuit of a cause. Its synonyms are enthusiasm (উৎসাহ), passion (আবেগ), fervor (উদ্দীপনা), and ardor (প্রবল ইচ্ছা). Antonyms are apathy (উদাসীনতা), indifference (নিরপেক্ষতা), lethargy (অলসতা), and sluggishness (মন্থরতা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Advance'' is:',
              ARRAY['Progress', 'Retreat', 'Proceed', 'Continue'],
              1,
              '''Advance'' (অগ্রসর হওয়া) means to move forward. Its synonyms are progress (অগ্রগতি), proceed (এগিয়ে যাওয়া), continue (চালিয়ে যাওয়া), and move forward (সামনে এগোনো). Its antonyms are retreat (পিছু হটা), withdraw (প্রত্যাহার করা), recede (সরিয়ে দেওয়া), and regress (পিছিয়ে যাওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Bizarre''?',
              ARRAY['Normal', 'Strange', 'Common', 'Ordinary'],
              1,
              '''Bizarre'' (অদ্ভুত) means very strange or unusual. Its synonyms are strange (অদ্ভুত), weird (বিচিত্র), odd (অদ্ভুত), and peculiar (অস্বাভাবিক). Antonyms are normal (স্বাভাবিক), common (সাধারণ), ordinary (সাধারণ), and typical (সাধারণ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Confident'' is:',
              ARRAY['Unsure', 'Certain', 'Assured', 'Positive'],
              0,
              '''Confident'' (আত্মবিশ্বাসী) means feeling sure of oneself. Its synonyms are certain (নিশ্চিত), assured (আশ্বস্ত), positive (ইতিবাচক), and self-assured (আত্মবিশ্বাসী). Its antonyms are unsure (অনিশ্চিত), uncertain (অনিশ্চিত), doubtful (সন্দেহজনক), and hesitant (দ্বিধাগ্রস্ত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Decrease''?',
              ARRAY['Increase', 'Reduce', 'Grow', 'Expand'],
              1,
              '''Decrease'' (কমানো) means to become smaller in size. Its synonyms are reduce (হ্রাস করা), diminish (ক্ষয় পাওয়া), lessen (কম করা), and decline (হ্রাস পাওয়া). Antonyms are increase (বৃদ্ধি করা), grow (বাড়া), expand (প্রসারিত করা), and enlarge (বড় করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Encourage'' is:',
              ARRAY['Support', 'Discourage', 'Inspire', 'Motivate'],
              1,
              '''Encourage'' (উৎসাহিত করা) means to give support or confidence. Its synonyms are support (সমর্থন করা), inspire (অনুপ্রাণিত করা), motivate (উদ্দীপ্ত করা), and urge (তাগিদ দেওয়া). Its antonyms are discourage (হতাশ করা), dishearten (মনোবল ভাঙ্গা), demotivate (অনুপ্রেরণা হ্রাস করা), and depress (হতাশ করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Fertile''?',
              ARRAY['Barren', 'Productive', 'Sterile', 'Infertile'],
              1,
              '''Fertile'' (উর্বর) means capable of producing abundant vegetation. Its synonyms are productive (উৎপাদনশীল), fruitful (ফলপ্রসূ), rich (সমৃদ্ধ), and plentiful (প্রচুর). Antonyms are barren (অনুর্বর), sterile (অনুর্বর), infertile (অনুর্বর), and unproductive (অফলপ্রসূ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Generous'' is:',
              ARRAY['Charitable', 'Stingy', 'Benevolent', 'Magnanimous'],
              1,
              '''Generous'' (উদার) means showing willingness to give. Its synonyms are charitable (দানশীল), benevolent (সদাশয়), magnanimous (মহানুভব), and liberal (উদার). Its antonyms are stingy (কৃপণ), miserly (কৃপণ), selfish (স্বার্থপর), and greedy (লোভী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Humble''?',
              ARRAY['Proud', 'Modest', 'Arrogant', 'Conceited'],
              1,
              '''Humble'' (নম্র) means having a modest view of oneself. Its synonyms are modest (বিনয়ী), meek (নম্র), unassuming (অভিমানহীন), and lowly (নীচ)। Antonyms are proud (অহংকারী), arrogant (অহংকারী), conceited (আত্মাভিমানী), and haughty (দাম্ভিক)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Increase'' is:',
              ARRAY['Expand', 'Decrease', 'Enlarge', 'Multiply'],
              1,
              '''Increase'' (বৃদ্ধি করা) means to become larger. Its synonyms are expand (প্রসারিত করা), enlarge (বড় করা), multiply (গুণ করা), and augment (বৃদ্ধি করা)। Its antonyms are decrease (কমানো), reduce (হ্রাস করা), diminish (ক্ষয় করা), and lessen (কম করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Jovial''?',
              ARRAY['Cheerful', 'Gloomy', 'Sad', 'Miserable'],
              0,
              '''Jovial'' (প্রফুল্ল) means cheerful and friendly. Its synonyms are cheerful (প্রফুল্ল), happy (খুশি), merry (আনন্দিত), and jolly (হাসিখুশি)। Antonyms are gloomy (বিষণ্ণ), sad (দুঃখিত), miserable (দুঃখী), and sorrowful (শোকাহত)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Knowledge'' is:',
              ARRAY['Wisdom', 'Ignorance', 'Understanding', 'Awareness'],
              1,
              '''Knowledge'' (জ্ঞান) means facts and information acquired. Its synonyms are wisdom (প্রজ্ঞা), understanding (বোধ), awareness (সচেতনতা), and erudition (পাণ্ডিত্য)। Its antonyms are ignorance (অজ্ঞতা), illiteracy (নিরক্ষরতা), unawareness (অজ্ঞানতা), and folly (মূর্খতা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Lenient''?',
              ARRAY['Strict', 'Merciful', 'Harsh', 'Rigid'],
              1,
              '''Lenient'' (শিথিল/দয়ালু) means permissive or merciful. Its synonyms are merciful (দয়ালু), forgiving (ক্ষমাশীল), tolerant (সহনশীল), and gentle (মৃদু)। Antonyms are strict (কঠোর), harsh (কঠোর), severe (কঠিন), and rigid (অনমনীয়)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Mature'' is:',
              ARRAY['Adult', 'Immature', 'Grown', 'Ripe'],
              1,
              '''Mature'' (পরিপক্ক) means fully developed. Its synonyms are adult (প্রাপ্তবয়স্ক), grown (বড় হওয়া), ripe (পাকা), and seasoned (অভিজ্ঞ)। Its antonyms are immature (অপরিপক্ক), childish (শিশুসুলভ), inexperienced (অনভিজ্ঞ), and young (তরুণ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Necessary''?',
              ARRAY['Optional', 'Essential', 'Unimportant', 'Voluntary'],
              1,
              '''Necessary'' (প্রয়োজনীয়) means required. Its synonyms are essential (অপরিহার্য), vital (অত্যাবশ্যক), indispensable (অনিবার্য), and required (প্রয়োজনীয়). Antonyms are optional (ঐচ্ছিক), unnecessary (অপ্রয়োজনীয়), unimportant (অগুরুত্বপূর্ণ), and voluntary (স্বেচ্ছায়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Optimistic'' is:',
              ARRAY['Hopeful', 'Pessimistic', 'Positive', 'Cheerful'],
              1,
              '''Optimistic'' (আশাবাদী) means hopeful about the future. Its synonyms are hopeful (আশাবাদী), positive (ইতিবাচক), cheerful (প্রফুল্ল), and confident (আত্মবিশ্বাসী)। Its antonyms are pessimistic (হতাশাবাদী), negative (নেতিবাচক), gloomy (বিষণ্ণ), and cynical (বিদ্রূপকারী)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Patient''?',
              ARRAY['Restless', 'Tolerant', 'Impatient', 'Agitated'],
              1,
              '''Patient'' (ধৈর্যশীল) means able to wait without becoming annoyed. Its synonyms are tolerant (সহনশীল), enduring (সহিষ্ণু), forbearing (সহিষ্ণু), and composed (স্থির)। Antonyms are impatient (অধৈর্য), restless (অস্থির), agitated (উত্তেজিত), and intolerant (অসহিষ্ণু)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Qualified'' is:',
              ARRAY['Competent', 'Unqualified', 'Capable', 'Skilled'],
              1,
              '''Qualified'' (যোগ্য) means having the necessary skills. Its synonyms are competent (সক্ষম), capable (যোগ্য), skilled (দক্ষ), and trained (প্রশিক্ষিত)। Its antonyms are unqualified (অযোগ্য), incompetent (অক্ষম), unfit (অনুপযুক্ত), and incapable (অক্ষম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Rival''?',
              ARRAY['Ally', 'Competitor', 'Friend', 'Partner'],
              1,
              '''Rival'' (প্রতিদ্বন্দ্বী) means a person competing with another. Its synonyms are competitor (প্রতিযোগী), opponent (প্রতিপক্ষ), adversary (শত্রু), and challenger (প্রতিদ্বন্দ্বী)। Antonyms are ally (মিত্র), friend (বন্ধু), partner (অংশীদার), and supporter (সমর্থক)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Secure'' is:',
              ARRAY['Safe', 'Unsafe', 'Protected', 'Guarded'],
              1,
              '''Secure'' (নিরাপদ) means safe from danger. Its synonyms are safe (নিরাপদ), protected (সুরক্ষিত), guarded (রক্ষিত), and sheltered (আশ্রিত)। Its antonyms are unsafe (অনিরাপদ), vulnerable (অরক্ষিত), exposed (উন্মুক্ত), and insecure (অনিরাপদ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Timid''?',
              ARRAY['Bold', 'Shy', 'Brave', 'Fearless'],
              1,
              '''Timid'' (ভীরু) means showing a lack of courage. Its synonyms are shy (লাজুক), fearful (ভীত), cowardly (কাপুরুষ), and hesitant (দ্বিধাগ্রস্ত)। Antonyms are bold (সাহসী), brave (সাহসী), fearless (নির্ভীক), and confident (আত্মবিশ্বাসী)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Urban'' is:',
              ARRAY['City', 'Rural', 'Metropolitan', 'Municipal'],
              1,
              '''Urban'' (শহুরে) means relating to a city. Its synonyms are city (শহর), metropolitan (মহানগরীয়), municipal (পৌর), and civic (নাগরিক)। Its antonyms are rural (গ্রামীণ), country (গ্রাম), pastoral (পল্লী), and rustic (গ্রাম্য)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Vacant''?',
              ARRAY['Occupied', 'Empty', 'Filled', 'Engaged'],
              1,
              '''Vacant'' (খালি) means not occupied. Its synonyms are empty (খালি), unoccupied (অধিকৃত নয়), void (শূন্য), and available (উপলব্ধ)। Antonyms are occupied (অধিকৃত), filled (পূর্ণ), engaged (ব্যবহৃত), and taken (গ্রহণ করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Wealth'' is:',
              ARRAY['Poverty', 'Fortune', 'Prosperity', 'Affluence'],
              0,
              '''Wealth'' (সম্পদ) means abundance of valuable possessions. Its synonyms are fortune (ভাগ্য), prosperity (সমৃদ্ধি), affluence (প্রাচুর্য), and riches (ধন-সম্পদ)। Its antonyms are poverty (দারিদ্র্য), destitution (নিঃস্বতা), need (অভাব), and want (অভাব)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Yield''?',
              ARRAY['Resist', 'Surrender', 'Oppose', 'Withstand'],
              1,
              '''Yield'' (আত্মসমর্পণ করা/উৎপাদন করা) can mean to surrender or produce. Its synonyms for surrender are surrender (আত্মসমর্পণ করা), submit (বশ্যতা স্বীকার করা), capitulate (আত্মসমর্পণ করা), and succumb (পরাস্ত হওয়া)। Antonyms are resist (প্রতিরোধ করা), oppose (বিরোধিতা করা), withstand (সহ্য করা), and fight (লড়াই করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Zenith'' is:',
              ARRAY['Peak', 'Nadir', 'Summit', 'Apex'],
              1,
              '''Zenith'' (চরম শিখর) means the highest point. Its synonyms are peak (শিখর), summit (চূড়া), apex (অগ্রভাগ), and climax (চরম বিন্দু)। Its antonym is nadir (নিম্নতম বিন্দু), meaning the lowest point.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Adversity''?',
              ARRAY['Prosperity', 'Misfortune', 'Fortune', 'Success'],
              1,
              '''Adversity'' (দুর্দশা/প্রতিকূলতা) means difficulties or misfortune. Its synonyms are misfortune (দুর্ভাগ্য), hardship (কষ্ট), difficulty (সমস্যা), and affliction (দুঃখ). Antonyms are prosperity (সমৃদ্ধি), fortune (ভাগ্য), success (সফলতা), and advantage (সুবিধা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Bold'' is:',
              ARRAY['Brave', 'Cowardly', 'Fearless', 'Daring'],
              1,
              '''Bold'' (সাহসী) means showing courage. Its synonyms are brave (সাহসী), fearless (নির্ভীক), daring (সাহসী), and audacious (দুঃসাহসী). Its antonyms are cowardly (কাপুরুষ), timid (ভীরু), shy (লাজুক), and meek (নম্র).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Confess''?',
              ARRAY['Deny', 'Admit', 'Conceal', 'Hide'],
              1,
              '''Confess'' (স্বীকার করা) means to admit to something. Its synonyms are admit (স্বীকার করা), acknowledge (স্বীকার করা), reveal (প্রকাশ করা), and disclose (প্রকাশ করা). Antonyms are deny (অস্বীকার করা), conceal (গোপন করা), hide (লুকানো), and cover up (ঢেকে রাখা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Distant'' is:',
              ARRAY['Far', 'Near', 'Remote', 'Separate'],
              1,
              '''Distant'' (দূরবর্তী) means far away. Its synonyms are far (দূরে), remote (দূরবর্তী), separate (পৃথক), and isolated (বিচ্ছিন্ন). Its antonyms are near (নিকটে), close (কাছে), adjacent (সংলগ্ন), and neighboring (প্রতিবেশী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Eliminate''?',
              ARRAY['Remove', 'Include', 'Add', 'Insert'],
              0,
              '''Eliminate'' (অপসারণ করা) means to completely remove. Its synonyms are remove (সরানো), eradicate (উৎপাটন করা), erase (মুছে ফেলা), and abolish (বিলুপ্ত করা). Antonyms are include (অন্তর্ভুক্ত করা), add (যোগ করা), insert (প্রবেশ করানো), and keep (রাখা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Flexible'' is:',
              ARRAY['Adaptable', 'Rigid', 'Plastic', 'Elastic'],
              1,
              '''Flexible'' (নমনীয়) means capable of bending easily. Its synonyms are adaptable (অভিযোজিত), plastic (নমনীয়), elastic (স্থিতিস্থাপক), and supple (নমনীয়). Its antonyms are rigid (অনমনীয়), stiff (শক্ত), inflexible (অনমনীয়), and firm (দৃঢ়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Gloomy''?',
              ARRAY['Bright', 'Dark', 'Sunny', 'Cheerful'],
              1,
              '''Gloomy'' (অন্ধকার/বিষণ্ণ) means dark or sad. Its synonyms are dark (অন্ধকার), dismal (বিষণ্ণ), sad (দুঃখিত), and depressing (হতাশাজনক). Antonyms are bright (উজ্জ্বল), sunny (রৌদ্রোজ্জ্বল), cheerful (প্রফুল্ল), and joyful (আনন্দিত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Honest'' is:',
              ARRAY['Truthful', 'Dishonest', 'Sincere', 'Trustworthy'],
              1,
              '''Honest'' (সৎ) means truthful and fair. Its synonyms are truthful (সত্যবাদী), sincere (আন্তরিক), trustworthy (বিশ্বাসযোগ্য), and upright (ন্যায়পরায়ণ). Its antonyms are dishonest (অসৎ), deceitful (প্রতারক), untruthful (মিথ্যাবাদী), and corrupt (দুর্নীতিগ্রস্ত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Ignorant''?',
              ARRAY['Educated', 'Unaware', 'Learned', 'Informed'],
              1,
              '''Ignorant'' (অজ্ঞ) means lacking knowledge. Its synonyms are unaware (অজ্ঞাত), uneducated (অশিক্ষিত), illiterate (অশিক্ষিত), and uninformed (অজ্ঞাত). Antonyms are educated (শিক্ষিত), learned (পণ্ডিত), informed (জ্ঞাত), and aware (সচেতন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Joyful'' is:',
              ARRAY['Happy', 'Sorrowful', 'Delighted', 'Cheerful'],
              1,
              '''Joyful'' (আনন্দিত) means feeling great pleasure. Its synonyms are happy (সুখী), delighted (আনন্দিত), cheerful (প্রফুল্ল), and merry (আনন্দিত). Its antonyms are sorrowful (শোকাহত), sad (দুঃখিত), miserable (দুঃখী), and gloomy (বিষণ্ণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Keen''?',
              ARRAY['Sharp', 'Dull', 'Blunt', 'Obtuse'],
              0,
              '''Keen'' (তীক্ষ্ণ/আগ্রহী) means having a sharp edge or great interest. Its synonyms are sharp (তীক্ষ্ণ), eager (আগ্রহী), enthusiastic (উৎসাহী), and acute (গভীর). Antonyms are dull (ভোঁতা), blunt (ভোঁতা), apathetic (উদাসীন), and indifferent (নিরপেক্ষ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Lazy'' is:',
              ARRAY['Idle', 'Active', 'Lethargic', 'Sluggish'],
              1,
              '''Lazy'' (অলস) means unwilling to work. Its synonyms are idle (অলস), lethargic (অলস), sluggish (মন্থর), and indolent (অলস). Its antonyms are active (সক্রিয়), energetic (উদ্যমী), industrious (পরিশ্রমী), and diligent (অধ্যবসায়ী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Mend''?',
              ARRAY['Break', 'Repair', 'Damage', 'Ruin'],
              1,
              '''Mend'' (মেরামত করা) means to repair something. Its synonyms are repair (মেরামত করা), fix (ঠিক করা), restore (পুনরুদ্ধার করা), and patch (জোড়া দেওয়া). Antonyms are break (ভাঙ্গা), damage (ক্ষতি করা), ruin (ধ্বংস করা), and destroy (বিনষ্ট করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Naughty'' is:',
              ARRAY['Mischievous', 'Disobedient', 'Well-behaved', 'Bad'],
              2,
              '''Naughty'' (দুষ্ট) means badly behaved. Its synonyms are mischievous (দুষ্টু), disobedient (অবাধ্য), bad (খারাপ), and wayward (অবাধ্য). Its antonyms are well-behaved (ভদ্র), obedient (বাধ্য), good (ভালো), and polite (বিনয়ী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Obtain''?',
              ARRAY['Lose', 'Get', 'Forfeit', 'Relinquish'],
              1,
              '''Obtain'' (অর্জন করা) means to get something. Its synonyms are get (পাওয়া), acquire (অর্জন করা), gain (লাভ করা), and secure (নিরাপদ করা). Antonyms are lose (হারানো), forfeit (বাজেয়াপ্ত করা), relinquish (ত্যাগ করা), and surrender (সমর্পণ করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Public'' is:',
              ARRAY['Open', 'Private', 'General', 'Common'],
              1,
              '''Public'' (সর্বজনীন) means open to everyone. Its synonyms are open (খোলা), general (সাধারণ), common (সাধারণ), and communal (গণ-). Its antonyms are private (ব্যক্তিগত), personal (ব্যক্তিগত), confidential (গোপনীয়), and secret (গোপন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Question''?',
              ARRAY['Answer', 'Interrogate', 'Reply', 'Respond'],
              1,
              '''Question'' (প্রশ্ন করা) means to ask. Its synonyms are interrogate (জিজ্ঞাসাবাদ করা), inquire (জিজ্ঞাসা করা), query (প্রশ্ন করা), and quiz (পরীক্ষা করা). Antonyms are answer (উত্তর দেওয়া), reply (জবাব দেওয়া), respond (সাড়া দেওয়া), and rejoin (প্রত্যুত্তর দেওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Rapid'' is:',
              ARRAY['Fast', 'Slow', 'Quick', 'Swift'],
              1,
              '''Rapid'' (দ্রুত) means happening quickly. Its synonyms are fast (দ্রুত), quick (দ্রুত), swift (দ্রুত), and speedy (শীঘ্র). Its antonyms are slow (ধীর), sluggish (মন্থর), leisurely (আরামদায়ক), and gradual (ধীরে ধীরে).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Secure''?',
              ARRAY['Safe', 'Unsafe', 'Vulnerable', 'Risky'],
              0,
              '''Secure'' (নিরাপদ) means safe from danger. Its synonyms are safe (নিরাপদ), protected (সুরক্ষিত), guarded (রক্ষিত), and sheltered (আশ্রিত). Antonyms are unsafe (অনিরাপদ), vulnerable (অরক্ষিত), risky (ঝুঁকিপূর্ণ), and exposed (উন্মুক্ত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Truth'' is:',
              ARRAY['Fact', 'Lie', 'Reality', 'Verity'],
              1,
              '''Truth'' (সত্য) means that which is true. Its synonyms are fact (সত্য), reality (বাস্তবতা), verity (সত্যতা), and accuracy (নির্ভুলতা). Its antonyms are lie (মিথ্যা), falsehood (মিথ্যা), untruth (অসত্য), and deception (প্রতারণা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Under''?',
              ARRAY['Above', 'Below', 'Over', 'Upon'],
              1,
              '''Under'' (নীচে) means extending directly below. Its synonyms are below (নীচে), beneath (নিম্নে), underneath (নিচে), and lower (নিম্নতর). Antonyms are above (উপরে), over (উপরে), higher (উচ্চতর), and beyond (বাইরে).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Victory'' is:',
              ARRAY['Triumph', 'Defeat', 'Conquest', 'Success'],
              1,
              '''Victory'' (জয়) means success in a contest. Its synonyms are triumph (জয়), conquest (বিজয়), success (সাফল্য), and win (জয়). Its antonyms are defeat (পরাজয়), loss (ক্ষতি), failure (ব্যর্থতা), and downfall (পতন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Whole''?',
              ARRAY['Part', 'Entire', 'Partial', 'Fraction'],
              1,
              '''Whole'' (সমগ্র) means all of something. Its synonyms are entire (সম্পূর্ণ), total (মোট), full (পূর্ণ), and complete (সম্পূর্ণ). Antonyms are part (অংশ), partial (আংশিক), fraction (ভগ্নাংশ), and segment (খণ্ড).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Young'' is:',
              ARRAY['Youthful', 'Old', 'Juvenile', 'Infant'],
              1,
              '''Young'' (তরুণ) means having lived for a short time. Its synonyms are youthful (তরুণ), juvenile (কিশোর), infant (শিশু), and adolescent (কৈশোরের). Its antonyms are old (বৃদ্ধ), aged (বয়স্ক), elderly (প্রবীণ), and ancient (প্রাচীন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Zealous''?',
              ARRAY['Apathetic', 'Enthusiastic', 'Indifferent', 'Uninterested'],
              1,
              '''Zealous'' (উদ্যমী) means having great energy or enthusiasm. Its synonyms are enthusiastic (উৎসাহী), passionate (আবেগী), fervent (উদ্দীপ্ত), and eager (আগ্রহী). Antonyms are apathetic (উদাসীন), indifferent (নিরপেক্ষ), uninterested (অরুচি), and lukewarm (ঔদাসীন্য).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Accept'' is:',
              ARRAY['Receive', 'Reject', 'Agree', 'Admit'],
              1,
              '''Accept'' (গ্রহণ করা) means to agree to receive something. Its synonyms are receive (গ্রহণ করা), agree (সম্মত হওয়া), admit (স্বীকার করা), and embrace (অংশীদার করা). Its antonyms are reject (প্রত্যাখ্যান করা), refuse (অস্বীকার করা), decline (বাতিল করা), and deny (অস্বীকার করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Barren''?',
              ARRAY['Fertile', 'Sterile', 'Productive', 'Rich'],
              1,
              '''Barren'' (অনুর্বর) means too poor to produce much. Its synonyms are sterile (অনুর্বর), infertile (অনুর্বর), unproductive (অফলপ্রসূ), and arid (শুষ্ক). Antonyms are fertile (উর্বর), productive (উৎপাদনশীল), rich (সমৃদ্ধ), and fruitful (ফলপ্রসূ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Calm'' is:',
              ARRAY['Peaceful', 'Agitated', 'Serene', 'Tranquil'],
              1,
              '''Calm'' (শান্ত) means not showing strong emotions. Its synonyms are peaceful (শান্তিপূর্ণ), serene (নিশ্চিন্ত), tranquil (শান্ত), and composed (স্থির). Its antonyms are agitated (উত্তেজিত), excited (উত্তেজিত), disturbed (বিক্ষুব্ধ), and turbulent (অস্থির).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Delicate''?',
              ARRAY['Fragile', 'Strong', 'Tough', 'Sturdy'],
              0,
              '''Delicate'' (সূক্ষ্ম/ভঙ্গুর) means very fine in structure or easily broken. Its synonyms are fragile (ভঙ্গুর), fine (সূক্ষ্ম), dainty (সুস্বাদু/সুন্দর), and elegant (মার্জিত). Antonyms are strong (শক্তিশালী), tough (কঠিন), sturdy (মজবুত), and robust (শক্তিশালী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Empty'' is:',
              ARRAY['Vacant', 'Full', 'Hollow', 'Bare'],
              1,
              '''Empty'' (খালি) means containing nothing. Its synonyms are vacant (খালি), hollow (ফাঁপা), bare (খালি), and void (শূন্য). Its antonyms are full (ভরা), filled (পূর্ণ), loaded (বোঝাই), and packed (ঠাসা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Famous''?',
              ARRAY['Unknown', 'Renowned', 'Obscure', 'Anonymous'],
              1,
              '''Famous'' (বিখ্যাত) means known about by many people. Its synonyms are renowned (সুপ্রসিদ্ধ), celebrated (প্রখ্যাত), eminent (বিশিষ্ট), and notable (উল্লেখযোগ্য). Antonyms are unknown (অজানা), obscure (অস্পষ্ট/অখ্যাত), anonymous (নামহীন), and nameless (নামবিহীন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Gentle'' is:',
              ARRAY['Mild', 'Harsh', 'Soft', 'Tender'],
              1,
              '''Gentle'' (মৃদু) means mild in character. Its synonyms are mild (মৃদু), soft (নরম), tender (কোমল), and kind (সদয়). Its antonyms are harsh (কঠোর), rough (রুক্ষ), severe (কঠিন), and violent (হিংস্র).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Hinder''?',
              ARRAY['Obstruct', 'Help', 'Aid', 'Assist'],
              0,
              '''Hinder'' (বাধা দেওয়া) means to make it difficult for something to happen. Its synonyms are obstruct (বাধা দেওয়া), impede (বাধা দেওয়া), prevent (প্রতিরোধ করা), and block (অবরোধ করা). Antonyms are help (সাহায্য করা), aid (সাহায্য করা), assist (সহায়তা করা), and facilitate (সহজতর করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Interesting'' is:',
              ARRAY['Boring', 'Engaging', 'Fascinating', 'Captivating'],
              0,
              '''Interesting'' (আকর্ষণীয়) means arousing curiosity. Its synonyms are engaging (মনোরম), fascinating (মুগ্ধকর), captivating (চিত্তাকর্ষক), and intriguing (কৌতূহলোদ্দীপক). Its antonyms are boring (বিরক্তিকর), dull (নীরস), uninteresting (অরুচিকর), and tedious (ক্লান্তিকর).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Join''?',
              ARRAY['Connect', 'Separate', 'Divide', 'Detach'],
              0,
              '''Join'' (যোগদান করা) means to connect or link. Its synonyms are connect (সংযোগ করা), link (যুক্ত করা), attach (সংযুক্ত করা), and unite (একত্র করা). Antonyms are separate (পৃথক করা), detach (আলাদা করা), divide (ভাগ করা), and disconnect (সংযোগ বিচ্ছিন্ন করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Kind'' is:',
              ARRAY['Cruel', 'Gentle', 'Compassionate', 'Tender'],
              0,
              '''Kind'' (সদয়) means having a friendly nature. Its synonyms are gentle (মৃদু), compassionate (দয়ালু), tender (কোমল), and benevolent (সদাশয়). Its antonyms are cruel (নিষ্ঠুর), unkind (অদয়ালু), harsh (কঠোর), and mean (অর্থপূর্ণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Legal''?',
              ARRAY['Lawful', 'Illegal', 'Unlawful', 'Criminal'],
              0,
              '''Legal'' (আইনি) means permitted by law. Its synonyms are lawful (বৈধ), legitimate (বৈধ), permissible (অনুমোদিত), and authorized (অনুমোদিত). Antonyms are illegal (অবৈধ), unlawful (অবৈধ), criminal (অপরাধী), and prohibited (নিষিদ্ধ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Maximum'' is:',
              ARRAY['Minimum', 'Greatest', 'Supreme', 'Utmost'],
              0,
              '''Maximum'' (সর্বোচ্চ) means the greatest possible. Its synonyms are greatest (সর্বশ্রেষ্ঠ), supreme (সর্বোচ্চ), utmost (চরম), and topmost (সর্বোচ্চ). Its antonyms are minimum (সর্বনিম্ন), least (সর্বনিম্ন), lowest (সর্বনিম্ন), and smallest (ছোট).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Necessary''?',
              ARRAY['Essential', 'Optional', 'Unimportant', 'Voluntary'],
              0,
              '''Necessary'' (প্রয়োজনীয়) means required. Its synonyms are essential (অপরিহার্য), vital (অত্যাবশ্যক), indispensable (অনিবার্য), and required (প্রয়োজনীয়). Antonyms are optional (ঐচ্ছিক), unnecessary (অপ্রয়োজনীয়), unimportant (অগুরুত্বপূর্ণ), and voluntary (স্বেচ্ছায়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Often'' is:',
              ARRAY['Seldom', 'Frequently', 'Regularly', 'Usually'],
              0,
              '''Often'' (প্রায়ই) means frequently. Its synonyms are frequently (ঘন ঘন), regularly (নিয়মিত), usually (সাধারণত), and repeatedly (পুনঃপুন). Its antonyms are seldom (কদাচিৎ), rarely (বিরল), occasionally (মাঝে মধ্যে), and infrequently (অস্বাভাবিকভাবে).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Power''?',
              ARRAY['Strength', 'Weakness', 'Impotence', 'Inability'],
              0,
              '''Power'' (ক্ষমতা) means ability to do something. Its synonyms are strength (শক্তি), force (বল), energy (শক্তি), and might (পরাক্রম). Antonyms are weakness (দুর্বলতা), impotence (অক্ষমতা), inability (অক্ষমতা), and powerlessness (ক্ষমতাহীনতা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Quality'' is:',
              ARRAY['Defect', 'Standard', 'Merit', 'Virtue'],
              0,
              '''Quality'' (গুণ) means a distinctive attribute. Its synonyms are standard (মান), merit (যোগ্যতা), virtue (সদগুণ), and excellence (উৎকর্ষ). Its antonyms are defect (ত্রুটি), flaw (খুঁত), fault (দোষ), and imperfection (অসম্পূর্ণতা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Rich''?',
              ARRAY['Affluent', 'Poor', 'Needy', 'Destitute'],
              0,
              '''Rich'' (ধনী) means having great wealth. Its synonyms are affluent (সমৃদ্ধ), wealthy (ধনী), prosperous (উন্নতিশীল), and opulent (বিলাসবহুল). Antonyms are poor (দরিদ্র), needy (অভাবী), destitute (নিঃস্ব), and impoverished (দরিদ্র).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Sorrow'' is:',
              ARRAY['Joy', 'Grief', 'Sadness', 'Misery'],
              0,
              '''Sorrow'' (দুঃখ) means deep distress. Its synonyms are grief (শোক), sadness (দুঃখ), misery (দুর্দশা), and woe (শোক). Its antonyms are joy (আনন্দ), happiness (সুখ), delight (পরমানন্দ), and pleasure (আনন্দ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Tired''?',
              ARRAY['Exhausted', 'Energetic', 'Fresh', 'Lively'],
              0,
              '''Tired'' (ক্লান্ত) means in need of rest. Its synonyms are exhausted (ক্লান্ত), fatigued (শ্রান্ত), weary (ক্লান্ত), and drained (নিঃশেষিত). Antonyms are energetic (উদ্যমী), fresh (তাজা), lively (প্রাণবন্ত), and active (সক্রিয়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Up'' is:',
              ARRAY['Down', 'Above', 'High', 'Over'],
              0,
              '''Up'' (উপরে) means towards a higher position. Its synonyms are upward (ঊর্ধ্বগামী), higher (উচ্চতর), above (উপরে), and overhead (উপরে). Its antonyms are down (নিচে), downward (নিম্নগামী), below (নীচে), and beneath (নিম্নে).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Valiant''?',
              ARRAY['Brave', 'Cowardly', 'Timid', 'Fearful'],
              0,
              '''Valiant'' (বীর/সাহসী) means possessing courage. Its synonyms are brave (সাহসী), courageous (সাহসী), fearless (নির্ভীক), and heroic (বীরোচিত). Antonyms are cowardly (কাপুরুষ), timid (ভীরু), fearful (ভীত), and weak (দুর্বল).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Wide'' is:',
              ARRAY['Broad', 'Narrow', 'Expansive', 'Vast'],
              1,
              '''Wide'' (প্রশস্ত) means of great width. Its synonyms are broad (প্রশস্ত), expansive (বিস্তৃত), vast (বিশাল), and extensive (ব্যাপক). Its antonyms are narrow (সংকীর্ণ), limited (সীমিত), restricted (সীমাবদ্ধ), and slender (ক্ষীণ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Yield''?',
              ARRAY['Surrender', 'Resist', 'Oppose', 'Withstand'],
              0,
              '''Yield'' (আত্মসমর্পণ করা/উৎপাদন করা) can mean to surrender or produce. Its synonyms for surrender are surrender (আত্মসমর্পণ করা), submit (বশ্যতা স্বীকার করা), capitulate (আত্মসমর্পণ করা), and succumb (পরাস্ত হওয়া). Antonyms are resist (প্রতিরোধ করা), oppose (বিরোধিতা করা), withstand (সহ্য করা), and fight (লড়াই করা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Zenith'' is:',
              ARRAY['Nadir', 'Peak', 'Summit', 'Apex'],
              0,
              '''Zenith'' (চরম শিখর) means the highest point. Its synonyms are peak (শিখর), summit (চূড়া), apex (অগ্রভাগ), and climax (চরম বিন্দু). Its antonym is nadir (নিম্নতম বিন্দু), meaning the lowest point.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Abdicate''?',
              ARRAY['Retain', 'Renounce', 'Keep', 'Hold'],
              1,
              '''Abdicate'' (ত্যাগ করা) means to give up power or responsibility. Its synonyms are renounce (ত্যাগ করা), relinquish (পরিত্যাগ করা), surrender (সমর্পণ করা), and resign (পদত্যাগ করা). Antonyms are retain (ধরে রাখা), keep (রাখা), hold (ধরা), and maintain (বজায় রাখা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Barbaric'' is:',
              ARRAY['Brutal', 'Civilized', 'Savage', 'Cruel'],
              1,
              '''Barbaric'' (বর্বর) means savagely cruel. Its synonyms are brutal (নিষ্ঠুর), savage (বর্বর), cruel (নিষ্ঠুর), and inhuman (অমানুষিক). Its antonyms are civilized (সভ্য), cultured (সংস্কৃতিবান), refined (পরিমার্জিত), and humane (মানবিক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Chronic''?',
              ARRAY['Temporary', 'Persistent', 'Brief', 'Momentary'],
              1,
              '''Chronic'' (দীর্ঘস্থায়ী) means persisting for a long time. Its synonyms are persistent (অবিরাম), constant (স্থির), continual (অবিরত), and incessant (নিরন্তর). Antonyms are temporary (অস্থায়ী), brief (সংক্ষিপ্ত), momentary (ক্ষণস্থায়ী), and acute (তীব্র কিন্তু স্বল্পস্থায়ী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Defend'' is:',
              ARRAY['Protect', 'Attack', 'Guard', 'Shield'],
              1,
              '''Defend'' (রক্ষা করা) means to protect from harm. Its synonyms are protect (রক্ষা করা), guard (পাহারা দেওয়া), shield (ঢাল দেওয়া), and safeguard (নিরাপদ রাখা). Its antonyms are attack (আক্রমণ করা), assault (আক্রমণ করা), offend (আক্রমণ করা), and threaten (হুমকি দেওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Exaggerate''?',
              ARRAY['Understate', 'Overstate', 'Minimize', 'Belittle'],
              1,
              '''Exaggerate'' (অতিরঞ্জিত করা) means to represent something as larger than it really is. Its synonyms are overstate (অতিরঞ্জিত করা), magnify (বড় করে দেখা), amplify (বর্ধিত করা), and embellish (সজ্জিত করা). Antonyms are understate (হ্রাস করে বলা), minimize (কমিয়ে বলা), belittle (ছোট করা), and play down (গুরুত্ব কমানো).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Fragile'' is:',
              ARRAY['Delicate', 'Sturdy', 'Breakable', 'Brittle'],
              1,
              '''Fragile'' (ভঙ্গুর) means easily broken. Its synonyms are delicate (সূক্ষ্ম/ভঙ্গুর), breakable (ভাঙনযোগ্য), brittle (ভঙ্গুর), and weak (দুর্বল). Its antonyms are sturdy (মজবুত), strong (শক্তিশালী), tough (কঠিন), and durable (টেকসই).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Grim''?',
              ARRAY['Cheerful', 'Stern', 'Happy', 'Pleasant'],
              1,
              '''Grim'' (কঠোর/নির্মম) means very serious or gloomy. Its synonyms are stern (কঠোর), severe (কঠিন), harsh (কঠোর), and gloomy (বিষণ্ণ). Antonyms are cheerful (প্রফুল্ল), happy (সুখী), pleasant (আনন্দদায়ক), and gentle (মৃদু).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Hasty'' is:',
              ARRAY['Rash', 'Careful', 'Quick', 'Sudden'],
              1,
              '''Hasty'' (তাড়াহুড়ো) means done with excessive speed. Its synonyms are rash (অবিবেচক), quick (দ্রুত), sudden (হঠাৎ), and hurried (তাড়াহুড়ো)। Its antonyms are careful (সতর্ক), cautious (সতর্ক), deliberate (ইচ্ছাকৃত), and thoughtful (চিন্তাশীল).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Inevitable''?',
              ARRAY['Avoidable', 'Unavoidable', 'Preventable', 'Optional'],
              1,
              '''Inevitable'' (অনিবার্য) means certain to happen. Its synonyms are unavoidable (অনিবার্য), inescapable (অপরিহার্য), certain (নিশ্চিত), and fated (ভাগ্য নির্ধারিত). Antonyms are avoidable (এড়ানো যায়), preventable (প্রতিরোধযোগ্য), uncertain (অনিশ্চিত), and optional (ঐচ্ছিক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Jubilant'' is:',
              ARRAY['Joyful', 'Mournful', 'Elated', 'Ecstatic'],
              1,
              '''Jubilant'' (আনন্দিত) means feeling great happiness. Its synonyms are joyful (আনন্দিত), elated (উল্লসিত), ecstatic (পরমানন্দিত), and overjoyed (অতিশয় আনন্দিত). Its antonyms are mournful (শোকাহত), sad (দুঃখিত), gloomy (বিষণ্ণ), and sorrowful (দুঃখিত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Knave''?',
              ARRAY['Hero', 'Villain', 'Saint', 'Angel'],
              1,
              '''Knave'' (দুর্বৃত্ত/বদমাশ) means a dishonest man. Its synonyms are villain (খলনায়ক), rogue (দুর্বৃত্ত), scoundrel (বদমাশ), and rascal (দুর্বৃত্ত). Antonyms are hero (নায়ক), saint (সাধু), angel (ফেরেশতা), and gentleman (ভদ্রলোক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Lament'' is:',
              ARRAY['Rejoice', 'Mourn', 'Grieve', 'Weep'],
              0,
              '''Lament'' (বিলাপ করা) means to express sorrow. Its synonyms are mourn (শোক করা), grieve (দুঃখ করা), weep (কান্না করা), and wail (বিলাপ করা). Its antonyms are rejoice (আনন্দ করা), celebrate (উদযাপন করা), cheer (উল্লাস করা), and delight (আনন্দিত হওয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Malice''?',
              ARRAY['Kindness', 'Spite', 'Benevolence', 'Goodwill'],
              1,
              '''Malice'' (বিদ্বেষ) means the desire to harm others. Its synonyms are spite (বিদ্বেষ), ill-will (বিদ্বেষ), hatred (ঘৃণা), and animosity (শত্রুতা). Antonyms are kindness (দয়া), benevolence (সদিচ্ছা), goodwill (সদিচ্ছা), and compassion (দয়া).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Naive'' is:',
              ARRAY['Inexperienced', 'Sophisticated', 'Simple', 'Innocent'],
              1,
              '''Naive'' (সরল/অনভিজ্ঞ) means lacking experience or sophistication. Its synonyms are innocent (নির্দোষ), simple (সরল), inexperienced (অনভিজ্ঞ), and artless (অকপট). Its antonyms are sophisticated (পরিশীলিত), experienced (অভিজ্ঞ), worldly (বাস্তবজ্ঞানী), and cunning (ধূর্ত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Obsolete''?',
              ARRAY['Modern', 'Outdated', 'New', 'Current'],
              1,
              '''Obsolete'' (অপ্রচলিত) means no longer produced or used. Its synonyms are outdated (পুরোনো), outmoded (সেকেলে), archaic (প্রাচীন), and antiquated (প্রাচীন). Antonyms are modern (আধুনিক), new (নতুন), current (বর্তমান), and contemporary (সমসাময়িক).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Plentiful'' is:',
              ARRAY['Abundant', 'Scarce', 'Copious', 'Ample'],
              1,
              '''Plentiful'' (প্রচুর) means existing in large amounts. Its synonyms are abundant (প্রচুর), copious (প্রচুর), ample (যথেষ্ট), and bountiful (প্রচুর)। Its antonyms are scarce (দুর্লভ), rare (বিরল), limited (সীমিত), and insufficient (অপর্যাপ্ত).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Quench''?',
              ARRAY['Extinguish', 'Ignite', 'Light', 'Kindle'],
              0,
              '''Quench'' (নির্বাপিত করা/মেটানো) means to satisfy thirst or extinguish a fire. Its synonyms are extinguish (নিভানো), slake (মেটানো), satisfy (তৃপ্ত করা), and douse (জল দেওয়া). Antonyms are ignite (জ্বালানো), light (আলো দেওয়া), kindle (জ্বালানো), and inflame (জ্বালানো).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Rigid'' is:',
              ARRAY['Stiff', 'Flexible', 'Firm', 'Hard'],
              1,
              '''Rigid'' (অনমনীয়) means unable to bend or be changed. Its synonyms are stiff (শক্ত), firm (দৃঢ়), hard (কঠিন), and inflexible (অনমনীয়)। Its antonyms are flexible (নমনীয়), elastic (স্থিতিস্থাপক), adaptable (অভিযোজিত), and pliable (নমনীয়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Sacred''?',
              ARRAY['Holy', 'Profane', 'Secular', 'Worldly'],
              0,
              '''Sacred'' (পবিত্র) means connected with God or religion. Its synonyms are holy (পবিত্র), divine (ঐশ্বরিক), blessed (পুণ্য), and hallowed (পবিত্র). Antonyms are profane (অপবিত্র), secular (ধর্মনিরপেক্ষ), worldly (পার্থিব), and unholy (অপবিত্র).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Temporary'' is:',
              ARRAY['Momentary', 'Permanent', 'Brief', 'Short-lived'],
              1,
              '''Temporary'' (অস্থায়ী) means lasting for only a limited period. Its synonyms are momentary (ক্ষণস্থায়ী), brief (সংক্ষিপ্ত), short-lived (স্বল্পস্থায়ী), and passing (অস্থায়ী). Its antonyms are permanent (স্থায়ী), lasting (টেকসই), enduring (স্থায়ী), and perpetual (চিরস্থায়ী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Urbane''?',
              ARRAY['Rude', 'Polished', 'Crude', 'Boorish'],
              1,
              '''Urbane'' (ভদ্র/মার্জিত) means courteous and refined. Its synonyms are polished (পরিমার্জিত), sophisticated (পরিশীলিত), suave (ভদ্র), and courteous (বিনয়ী). Antonyms are rude (অভদ্র), crude (অপরিশোধিত), boorish (অমার্জিত), and uncouth (অভদ্র).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Virtue'' is:',
              ARRAY['Morality', 'Vice', 'Goodness', 'Righteousness'],
              1,
              '''Virtue'' (সৎগুণ) means behavior showing high moral standards. Its synonyms are morality (নৈতিকতা), goodness (ভালো), righteousness (ধার্মিকতা), and integrity (সততা). Its antonyms are vice (পাপ), immorality (অনৈতিকতা), sin (পাপ), and evil (মন্দ).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Wary''?',
              ARRAY['Cautious', 'Reckless', 'Rash', 'Careless'],
              0,
              '''Wary'' (সতর্ক) means feeling caution about possible dangers. Its synonyms are cautious (সতর্ক), careful (সতর্ক), vigilant (জাগ্রত), and alert (সতর্ক). Antonyms are reckless (বেপরোয়া), rash (অবিবেচক), careless (অসতর্ক), and heedless (অমনোযোগী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Young'' is:',
              ARRAY['Youthful', 'Old', 'Juvenile', 'Infant'],
              1,
              '''Young'' (তরুণ) means having lived for a short time. Its synonyms are youthful (তরুণ), juvenile (কিশোর), infant (শিশু), and adolescent (কৈশোরের). Its antonyms are old (বৃদ্ধ), aged (বয়স্ক), elderly (প্রবীণ), and ancient (প্রাচীন).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Zeal''?',
              ARRAY['Enthusiasm', 'Apathy', 'Indifference', 'Lethargy'],
              0,
              '''Zeal'' (আগ্রহ/উদ্দীপনা) means great energy in pursuit of a cause. Its synonyms are enthusiasm (উৎসাহ), passion (আবেগ), fervor (উদ্দীপনা), and ardor (প্রবল ইচ্ছা). Antonyms are apathy (উদাসীনতা), indifference (নিরপেক্ষতা), lethargy (অলসতা), and sluggishness (মন্থরতা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Absurd'' is:',
              ARRAY['Ridiculous', 'Sensible', 'Foolish', 'Irrational'],
              1,
              '''Absurd'' (অযৌক্তিক) means wildly unreasonable. Its synonyms are ridiculous (হাস্যকর), foolish (মূর্খ), irrational (অযৌক্তিক), and preposterous (অসংগত). Its antonyms are sensible (বুদ্ধিমান), logical (যুক্তিসংগত), reasonable (যুক্তিসঙ্গত), and rational (যুক্তিবাদী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Barrier''?',
              ARRAY['Obstacle', 'Pathway', 'Opening', 'Passage'],
              0,
              '''Barrier'' (বাধা) means something that blocks progress. Its synonyms are obstacle (বাধা), hindrance (বাধা), impediment (প্রতিবন্ধক), and blockade (অবরোধ). Antonyms are passage (পথ), pathway (পথ), opening (খোলা), and gateway (দরজা).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Compassion'' is:',
              ARRAY['Sympathy', 'Cruelty', 'Kindness', 'Mercy'],
              1,
              '''Compassion'' (দয়া) means sympathetic concern for others. Its synonyms are sympathy (সহানুভূতি), kindness (দয়া), mercy (ক্ষমা), and empathy (সহমর্মিতা)। Its antonyms are cruelty (নিষ্ঠুরতা), indifference (উদাসীনতা), harshness (কঠোরতা), and barbarity (বর্বরতা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Deceive''?',
              ARRAY['Mislead', 'Enlighten', 'Inform', 'Guide'],
              0,
              '''Deceive'' (প্রতারণা করা) means to make someone believe something false. Its synonyms are mislead (ভুল পথে চালিত করা), trick (ফাঁকি দেওয়া), cheat (প্রতারণা করা), and dupe (ঠকানো)। Antonyms are enlighten (জ্ঞান দেওয়া), inform (জানানো), guide (পথ দেখানো), and advise (পরামর্শ দেওয়া)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Eager'' is:',
              ARRAY['Keen', 'Reluctant', 'Enthusiastic', 'Avid'],
              1,
              '''Eager'' (আগ্রহী) means strongly wanting to do something. Its synonyms are keen (আগ্রহী), enthusiastic (উৎসাহী), avid (আগ্রহী), and zealous (সোৎসাহী)। Its antonyms are reluctant (অনিচ্ছুক), unwilling (অনিচ্ছুক), apathetic (উদাসীন), and indifferent (নিরপেক্ষ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Fierce''?',
              ARRAY['Gentle', 'Ferocious', 'Mild', 'Tame'],
              1,
              '''Fierce'' (হিংস্র) means having an aggressive nature. Its synonyms are ferocious (হিংস্র), savage (বর্বর), violent (হিংস্র), and brutal (নিষ্ঠুর)। Antonyms are gentle (মৃদু), mild (মৃদু), tame (পোষা), and calm (শান্ত)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Generous'' is:',
              ARRAY['Charitable', 'Stingy', 'Benevolent', 'Magnanimous'],
              1,
              '''Generous'' (উদার) means showing willingness to give. Its synonyms are charitable (দানশীল), benevolent (সদাশয়), magnanimous (মহানুভব), and liberal (উদার). Its antonyms are stingy (কৃপণ), miserly (কৃপণ), selfish (স্বার্থপর), and greedy (লোভী).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Hostile''?',
              ARRAY['Friendly', 'Unfriendly', 'Warm', 'Kind'],
              1,
              '''Hostile'' (বিরোধী) means unfriendly or antagonistic. Its synonyms are unfriendly (অবন্ধুসুলভ), antagonistic (বিরোধী), aggressive (আক্রমণাত্মক), and belligerent (যুদ্ধপ্রিয়)। Antonyms are friendly (বন্ধুত্বপূর্ণ), kind (সদয়), warm (উষ্ণ), and amicable (সৌহার্দ্যপূর্ণ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Innocent'' is:',
              ARRAY['Pure', 'Guilty', 'Virtuous', 'Sinless'],
              1,
              '''Innocent'' (নির্দোষ) means not guilty. Its synonyms are pure (শুদ্ধ), virtuous (সৎ), sinless (পাপহীন), and blameless (নিরপরাধ)। Its antonyms are guilty (দোষী), culpable (অপরাধী), sinful (পাপী), and corrupt (দুর্নীতিগ্রস্ত)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Jealous''?',
              ARRAY['Envious', 'Content', 'Satisfied', 'Secure'],
              0,
              '''Jealous'' (ঈর্ষান্বিত) means feeling envy. Its synonyms are envious (ঈর্ষান্বিত), covetous (লোলুপ), resentful (ক্ষুব্ধ), and begrudging (অসন্তুষ্ট)। Antonyms are content (সন্তুষ্ট), satisfied (তৃপ্ত), secure (নিরাপদ), and trusting (বিশ্বাসী)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Knowledge'' is:',
              ARRAY['Wisdom', 'Ignorance', 'Understanding', 'Awareness'],
              1,
              '''Knowledge'' (জ্ঞান) means facts and information acquired. Its synonyms are wisdom (প্রজ্ঞা), understanding (বোধ), awareness (সচেতনতা), and erudition (পাণ্ডিত্য)। Its antonyms are ignorance (অজ্ঞতা), illiteracy (নিরক্ষরতা), unawareness (অজ্ঞানতা), and folly (মূর্খতা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Loyal''?',
              ARRAY['Faithful', 'Disloyal', 'Treacherous', 'Unfaithful'],
              0,
              '''Loyal'' (অনুগত) means giving constant support to someone. Its synonyms are faithful (বিশ্বস্ত), devoted (অনুরক্ত), trustworthy (বিশ্বাসযোগ্য), and dependable (নির্ভরযোগ্য). Antonyms are disloyal (অনুগত নয়), unfaithful (অবিশ্বস্ত), treacherous (বিশ্বাসঘাতক), and traitorous (বিশ্বাসঘাতক)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Mature'' is:',
              ARRAY['Adult', 'Immature', 'Grown', 'Ripe'],
              1,
              '''Mature'' (পরিপক্ক) means fully developed. Its synonyms are adult (প্রাপ্তবয়স্ক), grown (বড় হওয়া), ripe (পাকা), and seasoned (অভিজ্ঞ)। Its antonyms are immature (অপরিপক্ক), childish (শিশুসুলভ), inexperienced (অনভিজ্ঞ), and young (তরুণ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Necessary''?',
              ARRAY['Essential', 'Optional', 'Unimportant', 'Voluntary'],
              0,
              '''Necessary'' (প্রয়োজনীয়) means required. Its synonyms are essential (অপরিহার্য), vital (অত্যাবশ্যক), indispensable (অনিবার্য), and required (প্রয়োজনীয়). Antonyms are optional (ঐচ্ছিক), unnecessary (অপ্রয়োজনীয়), unimportant (অগুরুত্বপূর্ণ), and voluntary (স্বেচ্ছায়).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Optimistic'' is:',
              ARRAY['Hopeful', 'Pessimistic', 'Positive', 'Cheerful'],
              1,
              '''Optimistic'' (আশাবাদী) means hopeful about the future. Its synonyms are hopeful (আশাবাদী), positive (ইতিবাচক), cheerful (প্রফুল্ল), and confident (আত্মবিশ্বাসী)। Its antonyms are pessimistic (হতাশাবাদী), negative (নেতিবাচক), gloomy (বিষণ্ণ), and cynical (বিদ্রূপকারী)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Precious''?',
              ARRAY['Valuable', 'Worthless', 'Cheap', 'Valueless'],
              0,
              '''Precious'' (মূল্যবান) means of great value. Its synonyms are valuable (মূল্যবান), costly (ব্যয়বহুল), dear (প্রিয়), and prized (মূল্যবান). Antonyms are worthless (অকিঞ্চিতকর), cheap (সস্তা), valueless (মূল্যহীন), and insignificant (নগণ্য).'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Qualified'' is:',
              ARRAY['Competent', 'Unqualified', 'Capable', 'Skilled'],
              1,
              '''Qualified'' (যোগ্য) means having the necessary skills. Its synonyms are competent (সক্ষম), capable (যোগ্য), skilled (দক্ষ), and trained (প্রশিক্ষিত)। Its antonyms are unqualified (অযোগ্য), incompetent (অক্ষম), unfit (অনুপযুক্ত), and incapable (অক্ষম)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Rival''?',
              ARRAY['Competitor', 'Ally', 'Friend', 'Partner'],
              0,
              '''Rival'' (প্রতিদ্বন্দ্বী) means a person competing with another. Its synonyms are competitor (প্রতিযোগী), opponent (প্রতিপক্ষ), adversary (শত্রু), and challenger (প্রতিদ্বন্দ্বী)। Antonyms are ally (মিত্র), friend (বন্ধু), partner (অংশীদার), and supporter (সমর্থক)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Secure'' is:',
              ARRAY['Safe', 'Unsafe', 'Protected', 'Guarded'],
              1,
              '''Secure'' (নিরাপদ) means safe from danger. Its synonyms are safe (নিরাপদ), protected (সুরক্ষিত), guarded (রক্ষিত), and sheltered (আশ্রিত)। Its antonyms are unsafe (অনিরাপদ), vulnerable (অরক্ষিত), exposed (উন্মুক্ত), and insecure (অনিরাপদ)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Timid''?',
              ARRAY['Shy', 'Bold', 'Brave', 'Fearless'],
              0,
              '''Timid'' (ভীরু) means showing a lack of courage. Its synonyms are shy (লাজুক), fearful (ভীত), cowardly (কাপুরুষ), and hesitant (দ্বিধাগ্রস্ত)। Antonyms are bold (সাহসী), brave (সাহসী), fearless (নির্ভীক), and confident (আত্মবিশ্বাসী)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Urban'' is:',
              ARRAY['City', 'Rural', 'Metropolitan', 'Municipal'],
              1,
              '''Urban'' (শহুরে) means relating to a city. Its synonyms are city (শহর), metropolitan (মহানগরীয়), municipal (পৌর), and civic (নাগরিক)। Its antonyms are rural (গ্রামীণ), country (গ্রাম), pastoral (পল্লী), and rustic (গ্রাম্য)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'Which word is the synonym of ''Vacant''?',
              ARRAY['Empty', 'Occupied', 'Filled', 'Engaged'],
              0,
              '''Vacant'' (খালি) means not occupied. Its synonyms are empty (খালি), unoccupied (অধিকৃত নয়), void (শূন্য), and available (উপলব্ধ)। Antonyms are occupied (অধিকৃত), filled (পূর্ণ), engaged (ব্যবহৃত), and taken (গ্রহণ করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Wealth'' is:',
              ARRAY['Poverty', 'Fortune', 'Prosperity', 'Affluence'],
              0,
              '''Wealth'' (সম্পদ) means abundance of valuable possessions. Its synonyms are fortune (ভাগ্য), prosperity (সমৃদ্ধি), affluence (প্রাচুর্য), and riches (ধন-সম্পদ)। Its antonyms are poverty (দারিদ্র্য), destitution (নিঃস্বতা), need (অভাব), and want (অভাব)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'What is the synonym of ''Yield''?',
              ARRAY['Surrender', 'Resist', 'Oppose', 'Withstand'],
              0,
              '''Yield'' (আত্মসমর্পণ করা/উৎপাদন করা) can mean to surrender or produce. Its synonyms for surrender are surrender (আত্মসমর্পণ করা), submit (বশ্যতা স্বীকার করা), capitulate (আত্মসমর্পণ করা), and succumb (পরাস্ত হওয়া)। Antonyms are resist (প্রতিরোধ করা), oppose (বিরোধিতা করা), withstand (সহ্য করা), and fight (লড়াই করা)।'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'english',
              'English 2nd Paper : Synonym & Antonym',
              'The antonym of ''Zenith'' is:',
              ARRAY['Nadir', 'Peak', 'Summit', 'Apex'],
              0,
              '''Zenith'' (চরম শিখর) means the highest point. Its synonyms are peak (শিখর), summit (চূড়া), apex (অগ্রভাগ), and climax (চরম বিন্দু)। Its antonym is nadir (নিম্নতম বিন্দু), meaning the lowest point.'
            );
INSERT INTO questions (category_group, subject_id, chapter_name, question_text, options, correct_option, explanation) VALUES (
              'hsc',
              'ict',
              'ICT অধ্যায় ৫',
              'প্রোগ্রামিং ভাষায় ''Variable'' কাকে বলে?',
